{"title_page": "1904 Glamorgan County Council election", "text_new": "The '''Glamorgan County Council election, 1904''' was the sixth contest for seats on [[Glamorgan County Council|this authority]] in south [[Wales]]. It was preceded by the [[1901 Glamorgan County Council election|1901 election]] and followed by the [[1907 Glamorgan County Council election|1907 election]]. Glamorgan was by far the largest county in Wales in terms of population. [[Glamorgan County Council]] had been established by the ''[[Local Government Act 1888]]'', the first elections being held in early 1889.\n \n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Overview of the result==\nAs in most parts of Wales, the [[UK Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] was once again triumphant and won a majority of the seats. In 1904 the majority of the seats were uncontested, in contrast to the position at previous elections.<ref name=\"CT 27-2-04 nominations\">{{cite news|title=Glamorganshire|url=http://welshnewspapers.llgc.org.uk/en/page/view/3427019/ART254|accessdate=6 April 2014|newspaper=Cardiff Times|date=27 February 1904}}</ref>\n\nResults are drawn from a number of sources. The include a number of newspapers.<ref name=\"WkM 12-3-04 results\">{{cite news|title=County Council Elections. Radicals Gain Four Seats in Glamorganshire|url=http://welshnewspapers.llgc.org.uk/en/page/view/3376731/ART189|accessdate=6 April 2014|newspaper=Weekly Mail|date=12 March 1904}}</ref>\n\n==Boundary changes==\nThere were no boundary changes at this election.\n\n==Retiring aldermen==\nEight of the eleven retiring aldermen were Liberals.\n\n==Contested elections==\n\nIn the Rhondda district, the local paper stated that 'no truer manifestation of good faith and respect for the retiring County Councillors could have been shown than that eight of them were returned unopposed.' There were only two contested elections in the valley.<ref name=\"RL 5-3-04 cc els\">{{cite news|title=5 March Impending Elections. County Council.|url=http://welshnewspapers.llgc.org.uk/en/page/view/3828317/ART33|accessdate=8 May 2014|newspaper=Rhondda Leader|date=5 March 1904}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n\n===[[Aberaman (electoral ward)|Aberaman]]===\n{{Election box begin | title = Aberaman 1904 }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party = Liberal Party (UK)\n   |candidate = '''Thomas Luther Davies'''\n   |votes = unopposed\n   |percentage = \n   |change =  \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===[[Aberavon (electoral ward)|Aberavon]]===\nJohn Morgan Smith held on to the seat he had held since [[1889 Glamorgan County Council election|1889]] by a mere two votes. At previously elections he had described himself both as a Conservative and Independent and had been returned unopposed on several occasions.\n{{Election box begin | title = [[Aberavon]] 1904 }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party = Independent (politician)\n   |candidate = '''John Morgan Smith*'''\n   |votes = 538\n   |percentage = \n   |change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party = Liberal Party (UK)\n   |candidate = Frank B. Smith\n   |votes = 536\n   |percentage = \n   |change =\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  |votes         = 2\n  |percentage    = \n  |change        =\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Independent (politician)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===[[Aberdare Town (electoral ward)|Aberdare Town]]===\nRetiring alderman J.W. Evans was returned unopposed. Retiring councillor David Hughes did not stand.<ref name=\"AL 5-3-04 noms\" /> \n{{Election box begin | title = Aberdare Town 1904 }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party = Liberal Party (UK)\n   |candidate = '''[[John William Evans (Welsh Liberal politician)|John William Evans]]**'''\n   |votes = unopposed\n   |percentage =\n   |change =  \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |swing      = 