icerche, scoperte, progetti, Roma, p. 203-214\n* {{cite book |last1=Soren |first1=David |last2=Khader |first2=Aicha B. |last3=Slim |first3=Hedi |year=1990 |title=Carthage |url=https://archive.org/details/carthageuncoveri00sore |url-access=registration |location = New York, NY |publisher=Simon & Schuster |ref=harv }}\n* Urquhart, David, \"Mount Lebanon\"; Google Archives\n* {{cite book |last=Warmington |first = Brian H. |year=1964 |title=Carthage |publisher=Penguin (original ed.:Robert Hale 1960) |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Carayon, Nicolas, ''[http://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/docs/00/28/32/10/PDF/3vol.pdf Les ports ph\u00e9niciens et puniques]'', PhD Thesis, 2008, Strasbourg, France.\n* Cerqueiro, Daniel, ''{{lang|es|Las Naves de Tarshis o qui\u00e9nes fueron los Fenicios}}'', Buenos Aires, Ed. Peq. Venecia, 2002, {{ISBN|987-9239-13-X}}.\n* Cioffi, Robert L., \"A Palm Tree, a Colour and a Mythical Bird\" (review of Josephine Quinn, ''In Search of the Phoenicians'', Princeton, 2017, 360 pp., {{ISBN|978 0 691 17527 0}}), ''[[London Review of Books]]'', vol. 41, no. 1 (3 January 2019), pp. 15\u201316.\n* [[George Rawlinson|Rawlinson, George]], ''The History of Phoenicia'', 1889, available [http://digital.library.upenn.edu/webbin/gutbook/lookup?num=2331 online] under [[Project Gutenberg]]. Rawlinson's 19th-century text needs updating for modern improvements in historical understanding.\n* [[Jean-Pierre Thiollet|Thiollet, Jean-Pierre]], ''{{lang|fr|Je m'appelle Byblos}}'', foreword by Guy Gay-Para, H & D, Paris, 2005, {{ISBN|2-914266-04-9}}.\n* {{cite book |last=Todd |first=Malcolm |authorlink=Malcolm Todd |author2=Andrew Fleming |title=The South West to AD 1,000 (Regional history of England series No.:8) |publisher=Longman |location=Harlow, Essex |year=1987 |isbn=978-0-582-49274-5 }}, for a critical examination of the evidence of Phoenician trade with the South West of the U.K.\n* Silva, Di\u00f3genes. \"La literatura sobre fenicios en el territorio brasile\u00f1o: or\u00edgenes y razones\", PhD Thesis, Madrid - 2016. Available in https://eprints.ucm.es/39468/\n\n== External links ==\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Phoenicia\n |viaf= |lccn= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03szw8l BBC Radio4 \u2013 In Our Time: The Phoenicians (audio archive)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090110073346/http://www.nowlebanon.com/NewsArticleDetails.aspx?ID=69741&MID=123&PID=2 The quest for the Phoenicians in South Lebanon]\n* [https://www.omniglot.com/writing/phoenician.htm Phoenician Alphabet]\n* {{cite web|url=https://aeon.co/essays/phoenicia-an-imaginary-friend-to-nations-in-need-of-ancestors|title=Phoenicia: An imaginary friend to nations in need of ancestors|work=Josephine Quinn, associate professor in ancient history at Worcester College, [[University of Oxford]]|editor=Sam Haselby|publisher=Aeon}}\n\n{{Ancient states and regions of the Levant |state=collapsed}}\n{{Ancient Syria and Mesopotamia}}\n{{Phoenician cities and colonies navbox}}\n{{Empires}}\n{{Subject bar |commons=y|wikt=y|s=y }}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Phoenicia| ]]\n[[Category:Ancient Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Ancient Levant]]\n[[Category:Ancient Near East]]\n[[Category:Bronze Age Asia]]\n[[Category:Bronze Age cultures]]\n[[Category:Iron Age cultures of Asia]]\n[[Category:Iron Age cultures of Africa]]\n[[Category:History of the Mediterranean]]\n[[Category:Ancient Asia]]\n[[Category:Ancient Africa]]\n[[Category:Ancient Europe]]\n[[Category:Ancient Syria]]\n[[Category:Ancient history of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ancient history of the Iberian Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Ancient history of North Africa]]\n[[Category:History of Palestine (region)]]\n[[Category:History of Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Civilizations]]\n[[Category:2nd millennium BC]]\n[[Category:9th century BC]]\n[[Category:8th century BC]]\n[[Category:7th century BC]]\n[[Category:6th century BC]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in the 16th century BC]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in the 6th century BC]]\n[[Category:12th-century BC establishments]]\n[[Category:6th-century BC disestablishments]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ancient Semitic civilization}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{Coord|34|07|25|N|35|39|04|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox former country\n| native_name = Phoenicia <br /> {{Phoenician|pe|taw}} <br /> {{native name|phn|\ud802\udd10\ud802\udd15 / P\u016bt}} <br /> {{lang|grc|\u03a6\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7}} <br /> {{native name|el|Phoin\u00edk\u0113}}\n| common_name = Phoenicia\n| national_motto =\n| era = [[Classical antiquity]]\n| government_type = [[City-state]]s ruled by [[Monarchy|kings]]\n| year_start = 2500&nbsp;BC<ref name=\"BentleyZiegler2000\">{{cite book|author1=Jerry H. Bentley|author2=Herbert F. Ziegler|title=Traditions & Encounters: From the Beginnings to 1500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1qtiYjVlmDgC|year=2000|publisher=McGraw Hill|isbn=978-0-07-004949-9|quote=By about 2500 b.c.e. Phoenician merchants and ships already dominated trade in the Mediterranean basin.}}</ref>\n| date_event1 = 969&nbsp;BC\n| event1 = [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in [[Lebanon|South Lebanon]], under the reign of [[Hiram I]], becomes the dominant city-state\n| event2 = [[Dido]] founds [[Carthage]] (legendary)\n| date_event2 = 814&nbsp;BC\n| event_end = [[Cyrus the Great]] conquers Phoenicia \n| year_end = 539&nbsp;BC\n| p1 = Canaanites\n| p2 = Hittite Empire\n| p3 = Egyptian Empire\n| s1 = Achaemenid Phoenicia\n| flag_s1 = Achaemenid Empire.jpg\n| s2 = Ancient Carthage\n| flag_s2 = Symbol of Tanit.png\n| image_map = PhoenicianTrade.png\n| image_map_caption = Map of Phoenicia and its Mediterranean trade routes\n| capital = <small>[[Byblos]] (2500\u20131000 BC)<br>[[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] (900\u2013550 BC)<ref name=\"Aubet2001\">{{cite book|author=Mar\u00eda Eugenia Aubet|title=The Phoenicians and the West: Politics, Colonies and Trade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B7SLWT2vpNcC&pg=PA18|date=6 September 2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-79543-2|pages=18, 44}}</ref></small>\n| common_languages = [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]], [[Punic language|Punic]]\n| religion = [[Canaanite religion]]\n| leader1 = [[Ahiram]]\n| year_leader1 = {{circa|1000&nbsp;BC}}\n| leader2 = [[Hiram I]]\n| year_leader2 = 969&nbsp;\u2013 936&nbsp;BC\n| leader3 = [[Pygmalion of Tyre]]\n| year_leader3 = 820&nbsp;\u2013 774&nbsp;BC\n| title_leader = Well-known kings of Phoenician cities\n| legislature =\n| stat_year1 =\n| stat_pop1 = \n| stat_area2 = 20000\n| stat_year2 = 1000 BC\n}}\n\n'''Phoenicia''' ({{IPAc-en|f|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u026a|\u0283|\u0259}};<ref>[https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/phoenicia \"Phoenicia\"]. ''[[Collins English Dictionary]]''.</ref> from {{lang-grc|\u03a6\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7}}, ''{{transl|el|Phoin\u00edk\u0113}}'') was an [[ancient Semitic-speaking peoples|ancient Semitic-speaking]] [[thalassocracy|thalassocratic]] civilization centered around the Mediterranean that originated in the [[Levant]], specifically [[Lebanon]], west of the [[Fertile Crescent]]. It was concentrated along the coastal areas of modern Lebanon and included parts of what are now northern [[Israel]] and western [[Syria]], reaching as far north as [[Arwad]], and possibly as far south as either [[Acre, Israel|Acre]] or [[Gaza City|Gaza]].<ref name=\"Xella\">Paolo Xella, 2017, Phoenician Inscriptions in Palestine, in U. H\u00fcbner and H. Niehr (eds.), Sprachen in Pal\u00e4stina im 2. und 1. Jahrtausend v. Chr., ADPV 43, Wiesbaden 2017, 153-169; \u201cFirst of all, it is necessary to state that, instead of speaking of \u201cPhoenicians in Palestine\u201d, it is much more correct to speak of \u201cSouthern Phoenicians\u201d. In other words, we must simply invert our modern and unfounded perspective, which is conditioned by current politics. Particularly as far as regions like Upper Galilee or the Plain of Sharon are concerned, it is not a question of \u201cstrangers\u201d who settle abroad and decide to live beyond the borders of their country. Instead, it is about people who are and feel themselves&nbsp;at home&nbsp;there. As [[:de: Manfred Weippert| Manfred Weippert]] remarked some years ago, it concerns the fact that \u201cPh\u00f6nizier in dem Bereich, den wir heute \u2018Pal\u00e4stina\u2019 nennen, und gerade auch in Galil\u00e4a, dem nat\u00fcrlichen Hinterland von Tyrus, ein wichtiges Bev\u00f6lkerungselement waren\u201d. [Translation: Phoenicians in what we now call 'Palestine', and especially in Galilee, the natural hinterland of Tyre, were an important element of the population]\u201d</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Jigoulov|first=Vadim S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IbzsCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199&dq=gaza+phoenicia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj44YOn7ePoAhWRYMAKHZdCBh8Q6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=gaza%20phoenicia&f=false|title=The Social History of Achaemenid Phoenicia: Being a Phoenician, Negotiating Empires|date=2016-04-08|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93809-4|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hornblower|first=Simon|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TkW_BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT1174&dq=gaza+phoenicia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiUup6f8OPoAhU7QEEAHTpaABUQ6AEInAQwOw#v=onepage&q=gaza%20phoenicia&f=false|title=The Oxford Companion to Classical Civilization|last2=Spawforth|first2=Antony|last3=Eidinow|first3=Esther|date=2014-09-11|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-101676-9|language=en}}</ref> The civilization spread across the Mediterranean between 1500 BC and 300 BC, its colonies reaching as west as [[Carthage]] in North Africa, and even [[C\u00e1diz]] on the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic coast]] of Spain. \n\n''Phoenicia'' is an [[ancient Greek]] term used for the major export of the region, cloth dyed [[Tyrian purple]] from the ''[[Murex]]'' mollusc, and referred to the major [[Canaan]]ite port towns; it did not correspond precisely to Phoenician culture overall as it would have been understood natively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historytoday.com/reviews/who-were-phoenicians|title=Who Were The Phoenicians? {{!}} History Today|website=www.historytoday.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Phoenician civilization was organized in [[city-state]]s, similar to those of [[ancient Greece]],{{sfnp|Aubet|2001|p=17}} of which the most notable were [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], [[Sidon]], Arwad, [[Berytus]], [[Byblos]], and [[ancient Carthage|Carthage]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ancient.eu/phoenicia/|title=Phoenicia|encyclopedia=Ancient History Encyclopedia|access-date=2017-08-09}}</ref> Each city-state was politically independent, and there is no archaeological evidence proving that the Phoenicians viewed themselves as a single nationality.<ref name=\"Quinn201203\">{{cite book|author=Josephine Quinn|authorlink=Josephine Crawley Quinn|title=In Search of the Phoenicians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8QAuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|date=11 December 2017|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8911-2|page=201, 203|quote=My starting point was that we have no good evidence for the ancient people that we call Phoenician identifying themselves as a single people or acting as a stable collective. I do not conclude from this absence of evidence that the Phoenicians did not exist, nor that nobody ever called her- or himself a Phoenician under any circumstances: Phoenician-speakers undoubtedly had a larger repertoire of self-classifications than survives in our fragmentary evidence, and it would be surprising if, for instance, they never described themselves as Phoenicians to the Greeks who invented that term; indeed, I have drawn attention to several cases where something very close to that is going on... A distaste even for self-government could also explain a phenomenon I have drawn attention to throughout the book: our \u201cPhoenicians\u201d not only fail to visibly identify as Phoenician, they often omit to identify at all. It is striking in this light that the first surviving visible expression of an explicitly \u201cPhoenician\u201d identity was imposed by the Carthaginians on their subjects as they extended state power to a degree unprecedented among Phoenician-speakers, that it was then adopted by Tyre as a symbol of colonial success, and that it was subsequently exploited by Roman rulers in support of their imperial activities.}}</ref> In terms of culture, language, lifestyle, and religion there was little to set the Phoenicians significantly apart from other residents of the Levant.<ref name=\"Quinn24204\">{{cite book|author=Josephine Quinn|authorlink=Josephine Crawley Quinn|title=In Search of the Phoenicians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8QAuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|date=11 December 2017|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8911-2|page=24, 204|quote=My answer to the question Moscati posed in 1963 is that nothing did in fact unite the Phoenicians in their own eyes or those of their neighbors, and that his Phoenician people, or civilization, or nation, is not actually a real historical object, but rather a product of the scholarly and political ideologies I have discussed in this chapter. Such modern ideas about the ancient Phoenicians are thoroughly interwoven with ideas about the modern nation-state. That does not in itself, of course, mean that they cannot also be true. But the picture presented by our ancient sources is very different... In the end, it is modern nationalism that has created the Phoenicians, along with much else of our modern idea of the ancient Mediterranean.}}</ref>\n\nAround 1050 BC, a [[Phoenician alphabet]] was used for the writing of [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]].<ref name=\"Markoe 2000 p. 111\">Markoe (2000) p. 111</ref> It became one of the most widely used [[writing system]]s in the region, spread by Phoenician merchants across the Mediterranean world, where it evolved and was assimilated by many other cultures.<ref name=\"Fischer 2004 90\">{{cite book|last=Fischer|first=Steven Roger|title=A history of writing|publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2004|page=90}}</ref> The Phoenician alphabet gave rise to the [[Greek alphabet]], which in turn gave rise to the [[Latin alphabet]]. \n\n== Etymology ==\n[[File:Image from page 35 of \"Ancient seals of the Near East\" (1940).jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Early Phoenician seal, dedicated to goddess [[Kubaba]] by Matrunna, daughter of [[Aplahanda]], 19th century BCE.]]\nThe name ''Phoenicians'', like [[Latin]] ''{{lang|la|Poen\u012b}}'' (adj. ''{{lang|la|poenicus}}'', later ''{{lang|la|p\u016bnicus}}''), comes from [[ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc|\u03a6\u03bf\u03af\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b5\u03c2}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|Pho\u00ednikes}}''). The word {{lang|grc|\u03c6\u03bf\u1fd6\u03bd\u03b9\u03be}} ''{{lang|grc-Latn|pho\u00eenix}}'' meant variably \"Phoenician person\", \"[[Tyrian purple]], [[crimson]]\" or \"[[date palm]]\" and is attested with all three meanings already in Homer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0057:entry=foi=nic|title=Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, A Greek-English Lexicon, \u03c6\u03bf\u1fd6\u03bd\u03b9\u03be|website=www.perseus.tufts.edu|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref> (The mythical bird [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]] also carries the same name, but this meaning is not attested until centuries later.) The word may be derived from {{lang|grc|\u03c6\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2}} ''{{lang|grc-Latn|phoin\u00f3s}}'' \"blood-red\",<ref>Gove, Philip Babcock, ed. ''Webster's Third New International Dictionary of the English Language Unabridged''. Springfield, MA: Merriam-Webster, 1993.</ref> itself possibly related to {{lang|grc|\u03c6\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2}} ''{{lang|grc-Latn|ph\u00f3nos}}'' \"murder\".\n\nIt is difficult to ascertain which meaning came first, but it is understandable how Greeks may have associated the crimson or purple color of dates and dye with the merchants who traded both products. [[Robert S. P. Beekes]] has suggested a [[Pre-Greek substrate|pre-Greek origin]] of the ethnonym.<ref>[[Robert S. P. Beekes]], ''Etymological Dictionary of Greek'', Brill, 2009, p. 1583.</ref> The oldest attested form of the word in Greek may be the [[Mycenaean Greek|Mycenaean]] ''{{lang|gmy|po-ni-ki-jo}}'', ''{{lang|gmy|po-ni-ki}}'', possibly borrowed from {{lang-egy|fn\u1e2bw}} <ref>Fran\u00e7oise Briquel-Chatonnet and \u00c9ric Gubel, {{lang|fr|Les Ph\u00e9niciens : Aux origines du Liban}}, collection \u00ab [[D\u00e9couvertes Gallimard]] \u00bb (n\u00ba 358). Paris: Gallimard, 1999, {{p.|18}}.</ref> (literally \"carpenters\", \"woodcutters\"; likely in reference to the famed [[Cedrus libani|Lebanon cedars]] for which the Phoenicians were well-known), although this derivation is disputed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Aubet Semmler|first=Mar\u00eda Eugenia |authorlink=Mar\u00eda Eugenia Aubet Semmler|title=The Phoenicians and the West: Politics, Colonies and Trade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B7SLWT2vpNcC&pg=PA9|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-79543-2|page=9}}</ref> The [[folk etymology|folk etymological]] association of {{lang|grc|\u03a6\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7 }} with {{lang|grc|\u03c6\u03bf\u1fd6\u03bd\u03b9\u03be}} mirrors that in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]], which tied ''{{lang|akk|kina\u1e2bni}}'', ''{{lang|akk|kina\u1e2b\u1e2bi}}'' \"[[Canaan]]\" to ''{{lang|akk|kina\u1e2b\u1e2bu}}'' \"red-dyed wool\".<ref>Mireille Hadas-Lebel, {{lang|fr|Entre la Bible et l'Histoire : Le Peuple h\u00e9breu}}, collection \u00ab [[D\u00e9couvertes Gallimard]] \u00bb (n\u00ba 313). Paris: Gallimard, 1997, {{p.|14}}.</ref><ref>B. Landesberger has shown that ''{{lang|akk|kina\u1e2b\u1e2bu}}'' should be read as ''{{lang|akk|qina\u1e2b\u1e2bu}}'' and was borrowed from [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] ''{{lang|sux|q\u00ecn}}'' (compare Akk ''{{lang|akk|uqn\u00fb}}'', [[Ugaritic]] ''{{lang|uga|iqnu}}'', Syrian ''{{lang|syc|q\u02bfn\u00e2\u02bf(a)}}''/''{{lang|syc|qun\u02bf(a)}}'', and Gk ''{{lang|grc-Latn|k\u00fdanos}}'' 'dark blue').</ref>\n\nThe land was natively known as ''{{lang|phn|\ud802\udd10\ud802\udd15}}'' (P\u016bt) and its people as the ''{{lang|phn|\ud802\udd10\ud802\udd0d\ud802\udd09\ud802\udd0c}}'' (P\u014dnnim).<ref name=krahmalkov>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=DbC9CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1&dq=Ph|title=A Phoenician-Punic Grammar|last=Krahmalkov|first=Charles R.|date=2000-11-28|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004294202|location=|pages=1|language=en}}</ref> In the [[Amarna letters]] of the 14th century BC, people from the region called themselves ''Kenaani'' or ''Kinaani'', equivalent to [[Canaan]]ite. The common Canaanite identity was gradually differentiated into regional subgroups, of which the Phoenicians were one, so they continued to use ''Canaanite'' as one of their self-designations.<ref name=krahmalkov/> Thus, much later, in the sixth century BC, [[Hecataeus of Miletus]] writes that Phoenicia was formerly called {{lang|grc|\u03c7\u03bd\u03b1}} ''{{lang|grc-Latn|khna}}'', a name that [[Philo of Byblos]] later adopted into his mythology as his [[eponym]] for the Phoenicians: \"{{lang|grc-Latn|Khna}} who was afterwards called {{lang|grc-Latn|Phoinix}}\".<ref>[[Eusebius]], ''{{lang|la|[[Praeparatio evangelica]]}}'', Book 1 chapter 10 section 10, {{cite book|title=Egypt's Place in Universal History: An Historical Investigation in Five Books|url=https://archive.org/details/egyptsplaceinun01unkngoog|year=1860|publisher=Longman, Brown, Green, and Longmans|page=[https://archive.org/details/egyptsplaceinun01unkngoog/page/n296 268]}}</ref> The ethnonym survived in [[North Africa]] until the fourth century AD (see [[Punic language]]). As late as the 3rd century, as mentioned by [[Augustine of Hippo]], an African identified himself as ''Chanani''.<ref name=krahmalkov/> Conversely, the names of the inhabitants of most prominent Phoenician cities Tyre and Sidon could sometimes also be used to refer to Phoenicians in general, so that for instance the self-designation ''Sorim'', Tyrians, was used in [[Tripolitania]].<ref name=krahmalkov/>\n\n[[File:Couvercle sarcophage sa\u00efda Sidon Liban Louvre AO5012.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Cover of a Phoenician anthropoid [[sarcophagus]] of a woman, made of marble, 350\u2013325 BC, from [[Sidon]], now in the [[Louvre]].]]\n\n== History ==\nThe Phoenicians left few records behind, so most of what is known about their origins and history comes from the texts of other civilizations and inferences of their material culture excavated throughout the Mediterranean.\n\n=== Origins ===\n[[File:Eshmunazar II sarcophagus.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|[[Eshmunazar II sarcophagus|Sarcophagus of Eshmunazor II]] (5th century BC), Phoenician king of Sidon found near Sidon, in southern Lebanon]]\n{{main|Canaan|Retjenu|Prehistory of the Levant}}Writing some time in 440 B.C., the ancient Greek historian [[Herodotus]] makes reference to the Phoenicians in his retelling of the Hellenistic-Phoenician myths of [[Io (mythology)|Io]] and [[Europa (mythology)|Europa]]:\n\n{{Quote|text=According to the [[Persian people|Persians]] best informed in history, the Phoenicians began the quarrel. These people, who had formerly dwelt on the shores of the [[Erythraean Sea]], having migrated to the Mediterranean and settled in the parts which they now inhabit, began at once, they say, to adventure on long voyages, freighting their vessels with the wares of Egypt and Assyria&nbsp;...|author={{harvnb|Herodotus, The History|loc=[http://classics.mit.edu/Herodotus/history.1.i.html I.1]}}|title=|source=}}\n\n[[Herodotus]] believed that the Phoenicians originated from [[Bahrain]],<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=leHFqMQ9mw8C&pg=PA48&dq |title=Beyond Price: Pearls and Pearl-fishing : Origins to the Age of Discoveries, Volume 224 |page=48 |author=R. A. Donkin|isbn=0-87169-224-4 |year=1998 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2hmbc9evgB0C&pg=PA401&dq |title=Bahrain Through The Ages \u2013 the Archaeology |publisher=Routledge |year=1986 |isbn=0-7103-0112-X |chapter=Tylos and Tyre. Bahrain in the Graeco-Roman World |editor-last2=Rice |editor-first2=Michael |author=Bowersock, G.W. |editor-last1=Khalifa |editor-first1=Haya Ali |pp=401\u20132 }}</ref> a view shared centuries later by Greco-Roman historian [[Strabo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aulaorientalis.org/AuOr%20escaneado/AuOr%2019-2001/2/7.pdf |title=Canaan. Phoenicia. Sidon. |page=274 |author=Ju. B. Tsirkin}}</ref> This theory was accepted by the 19th-century German classicist [[Arnold Hermann Ludwig Heeren|Arnold Heeren]], who noted that \"In the Greek geographers, for instance, we read of two islands, named Tyrus or [[Tylos]], and [[Arad, Bahrain|Aradus]], which boasted that they were the mother country of the Phoenicians, and exhibited relics of Phoenician temples.\"<ref>Arnold Heeren, p441</ref> The people of [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in [[southern Lebanon]] in particular have long maintained [[Persian Gulf]] origins, and the similarity in the words \"Tylos\" and \"Tyre\" has been commented upon.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Archaeology of the Arabian Gulf|publisher=Routledge|year=1994|isbn=0-415-03268-7 |author=Rice, Michael|p=20}}</ref> The [[Dilmun]] civilization [[History of Bahrain#Dilmun civilization|thrived in Bahrain]] during the period 2200\u20131600 BC, as shown by excavations of settlements and the [[Dilmun burial mounds]]. However, some claim there is little evidence that Bahrain was occupied during the time when such migration had supposedly taken place.<ref>Rice (1994), p. 21.</ref>\n\nThe Phoenician's Semitic language, along with evidence of an invasion at the site of Byblos, suggest they emerged from Semitic migrations to the Fertile Crescent between 2300 and 2100 B.C. By contrast, some scholars, such as [[Sabatino Moscati]], believe the Phoenicians originated from an admixture of previous non-Semitic inhabitants with the Semitic arrivals. The Canaanite culture that gave rise to the Phoenicians apparently developed ''in situ'' from the earlier [[Ghassulian]] [[chalcolithic]] culture. Ghassulian itself developed from the [[nomadic pastoralism|Circum-Arabian Nomadic Pastoral Complex]], which in turn developed from a fusion of their ancestral [[Natufian culture|Natufian]] and [[Harifian]] cultures with [[Pre-Pottery Neolithic B]] (PPNB) farming cultures, practicing the [[domestication of animals]] during the [[8.2 kiloyear event|6200&nbsp;BC climatic crisis]], which led to the [[Neolithic Revolution]] in the [[Levant]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Zarins |first=Juris |year=1992 |chapter=Pastoral Nomadism in Arabia: Ethnoarchaeology and the Archaeological Record\u2014A Case Study |editor-first=O. |editor-last=Bar-Yosef |editor2-first=A. |editor2-last=Khazanov |title=Pastoralism in the Levant |location=Madison |publisher=Prehistory Press |isbn=0-9629110-8-9 |pages= }}</ref> [[Byblos]] is attested as an archaeological site from the [[Early Bronze Age]]. The Late Bronze Age state of [[Ugarit]] is considered quintessentially Canaanite archaeologically,<ref name=\"tubb\">Tubb, Jonathan N. (1998), \"Canaanites\" (British Museum People of the Past)</ref> even though the Ugaritic language does not belong to the [[Canaanite languages]] proper.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Roger |last=Woodard |year=2008 |title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia |location=New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-68498-9 }}</ref><ref name=\"NavehJ1987\">\n{{Cite book |first=Joseph |last=Naveh |year=1987 |chapter=Proto-Canaanite, Archaic Greek, and the Script of the Aramaic Text on the Tell Fakhariyah Statue |editor1-last=Miller |title=Ancient Israelite Religion |display-editors=etal |isbn=0-8006-0831-3 |chapter-url-access=registration |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/ancientisraelite00unse }}. {{harvp|Coulmas|1996}}.</ref>\n\n=== Phoenician alphabet ===\n{{Main|Phoenician alphabet}}\n\nThe Canaanite-Phoenician [[alphabet]] consists of 22 letters, all [[consonant]]s.<ref name=\"Fischer 2004 90\"/> Starting around 1050 BC,<ref name=\"NavehJ1987\"/> this script was used for the writing of [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]], a Northern [[Semitic languages|Semitic]] language. It is believed to be one of the ancestors of modern alphabets.{{sfnp|Markoe |2000|p=108}}<ref>Zellig Sabbettai Harris. ''A grammar of the Phoenician language''. p6. 1990</ref> By their maritime trade, the Phoenicians spread the use of the alphabet to [[Anatolia]], North Africa, and Europe, where it was adopted by the [[ancient Greece|Greeks]] who developed it into an alphabetic script to have distinct letters for [[vowel]]s as well as [[consonant]]s.<ref>Edward Clodd, ''Story of the Alphabet'' (Kessinger) 2003:192ff</ref><ref>[http://www.arcalog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Near-Eastern-Chronology-and-the-development-of-the-Greek-Alphabet.pdf The Development of the Greek Alphabet within the Chronology of the ANE] (2009), Quote: \"Naveh gives four major reasons why it is universally agreed that the Greek alphabet was developed from an early Phoenician alphabet.<br />1 According to Herodutous \"the Phoenicians who came with Cadmus... brought into Hellas the alphabet, which had hitherto been unknown, as I think, to the Greeks.\"<br />2 The Greek Letters, alpha, beta, gimmel have no meaning in Greek but the meaning of most of their Semitic equivalents is known. For example, 'aleph' means 'ox', 'bet' means 'house' and 'gimmel' means 'throw stick'.<br />3 Early Greek letters are very similar and sometimes identical to the West Semitic letters.<br />4 The letter sequence between the Semitic and Greek alphabets is identical. (Naveh 1982)\"</ref>\n\nThe name \"Phoenician\" is by convention given to inscriptions beginning around 1050 BC, because [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]], [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], and other [[Canaanite languages|Canaanite dialects]] were largely indistinguishable before that time.<ref name=\"NavehJ1987\"/><ref name=\"Markoe 2000 p. 111\"/> The so-called [[Ahiram sarcophagus|Ahiram epitaph]], engraved on the sarcophagus of king [[Ahiram]] from about 1000 BC shows essentially a fully developed Phoenician script.<ref>Coulmas (1989) p. 141.</ref><ref name=\"AhiramSarcoph1000\">The date remains the subject of controversy, according to Glenn E. Markoe, \"The Emergence of Phoenician Art\" ''Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research'' No. 279 (August 1990):13\u201326) p. 13. \"Most scholars have taken the Ahiram inscription to date from around 1000 B.C.E.\", notes Edward M. Cook, \"On the Linguistic Dating of the Phoenician Ahiram Inscription (KAI 1)\", ''Journal of Near Eastern Studies'' ''' 53'''.1 (January 1994:33\u201336) p. 33 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/545356 JSTOR]. Cook analyses and dismisses the date in the thirteenth century adopted by C. Garbini, \"Sulla datazione della'inscrizione di Ahiram\", ''Annali'' (Istituto Universitario Orientale, Naples) '''37''' (1977:81\u201389), which was the prime source for early dating urged in {{cite book |title = Cadmean Letters: The Transmission of the Alphabet to the Aegean and further West before 1400 BC|last = Bernal|first = Martin|authorlink = |year = 1990|publisher = Eisenbrauns|location = Winona Lake, Ind.|isbn = 978-0-931464-47-8|pages = }} Arguments for a mid 9th -8th century B.C.E. date for the sarcophagus reliefs themselves\u2014and hence the inscription, too\u2014 were made on the basis of comparative art history and archaeology by Edith Porada, \"Notes on the Sarcophagus of Ahiram,\" ''Journal of the Ancient Near East Society'' 5 (1973:354-72); and on the basis of paleography among other points by Ronald Wallenfels, \"Redating the Byblian Inscriptions,\" ''Journal of the Ancient Near East Society'' 15 (1983:79\u2013118).</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Phoenicia|title=Phoenicia {{!}} historical region, Asia|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-08-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Phoenicians were among the first state-level societies to make extensive use of [[alphabet]]s: the family of [[Canaanite languages]], spoken by Israelites, [[Phoenicians]], [[Amorites]], [[Ammon]]ites, [[Moabites]] and [[Edomites]], was the first historically attested group of languages to use an alphabet, derived from the [[Proto-Canaanite]] script, to record their writings. The Proto-Canaanite script uses around 30 symbols but was not widely used until the rise of [[Syro-Hittite|new Semitic kingdoms]] in the 13th and 12th centuries BC.<ref name=\"JMH2004-23\">{{cite book|last1=Hoffman|first1=Joel M.|title=In the beginning : a short history of the Hebrew language|date=2004|publisher=New York Univ. Press|location=New York, NY [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-8147-3654-8|page=23|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Pj0TCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167&dq=In+the+beginning+:+a+short+history+of+the+Hebrew+language#v=snippet&q=canaanite&f=false|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref> The Proto-Canaanite script is derived from [[Egyptian hieroglyphs]].<ref>Michael C. Howard (2012). [https://books.google.com/books?id=6QPWXrCCzBIC&pg=PA23 Transnationalism in Ancient and Medieval Societies. P. 23.]</ref>\n\n=== Emergence in the Late Bronze Age ===\nVery little is known of Phoenicia before it was conquered by Tutmoses III of Egypt around 1500 B.C. The Amarna Letters, an Egyptian record of diplomatic exchanges dated 1411-1358 B.C. reveal that neighboring Amorites and Hittites were capturing Phoenician vassals of Egypt between 1350 and 1300 B.C. The Late Bronze Age collapse severely weakened or destroyed numerous civilization in the region, including the Egyptians and Hittites. The Phoenicians, now free from foreign domination and interference, appeared to have weathered the crisis relatively well, emerging as a distinct and organized civilization around 1230 B.C.\n\nThe first textual account of the Phoenicians during the Iron Age comes from the Assyrian King Tiglath-Pileser I, in relation to his campaign against the Phoenicians between 1114 and 1076 B.C.\n\n=== High point: 1200\u2013800 BC ===\n[[Fernand Braudel]] remarked that Phoenicia was an early example of a \"world-economy\" surrounded by empires. The pinnacle of Phoenician culture and sea power is usually placed roughly between 1200 and 800&nbsp;BC. Archaeological evidence consistent with this understanding has been difficult to identify. A unique concentration in Phoenicia of silver hoards dated some time during this high point contains [[hacksilver]] with lead isotope ratios matching ores in Sardinia and Spain.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chamorro|first1=Javier G.|title=Survey of Archaeological Research on Tartessos|journal=American Journal of Archaeology|date=1987|volume=91|issue=2|pages=197\u2013232|jstor=505217|doi=10.2307/505217}}</ref> This metallic evidence agrees with the [[Biblical]] attestation of a western Mediterranean [[Tartessos|Tarshish]] said to have supplied [[Solomon|King Solomon]] of Israel with silver via Phoenicia, during the latter's heyday.<ref name=ThompsonSkaggs2013>{{cite journal |author1=Thompson, C. |author2=Skaggs, S. |title=King Solomon's Silver? Southern Phoenician Hacksilber Hoards and the Location of Tarshish |journal=Internet Archaeology |volume=35 |issue=35 |doi=10.11141/ia.35.6 |url=http://intarch.ac.uk/journal/issue35/6/index.html |year=2013 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n[[File:AssyrianWarship.jpg|thumb|[[Assyria]]n warship (probably built by Phoenicians) with two rows of oars, relief from [[Nineveh]], c. 700 BC.]]\nMany of the most important Phoenician settlements had been established long before this: [[Byblos]], [[Tyre (Lebanon)|Tyre]], [[Sidon]], [[Simyra]], [[Arwad]], and [[Beirut|Berytus]], (now thhe capital of [[Lebanon]]) all appear in the [[Amarna tablets]].\n\nThe league of independent city-state ports, along with others on the islands and along other coasts of the Mediterranean Sea, was ideally suited for trade between the [[Levant]] area, rich in natural resources, and the rest of the ancient world. Around 1200&nbsp;BC, a series of [[Late Bronze Age collapse|poorly-understood events]] weakened and destroyed the adjacent [[New Kingdom of Egypt|Egyptian]] and [[Collapse of the Hittite Empire|Hittite]] empires. In the resulting power vacuum, a number of Phoenician cities rose as significant maritime powers.\n\nPhoenician societies rested on three power-bases: the king; temples and their priests; and councils of elders. [[Byblos]] first became the predominant center from where the Phoenicians dominated the Mediterranean and Erythraean (Red) Sea routes. It was here that the first inscription in the Phoenician alphabet was found, on the sarcophagus of [[Ahiram]] (c. 1200&nbsp;BC).{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nLater, [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] gained in power. One of its kings, the priest [[Ithobaal I|Ithobaal]] (887\u2013856&nbsp;BC), ruled Phoenicia as far north as Beirut, and part of Cyprus. [[Carthage]] was founded in 814&nbsp;BC under [[Pygmalion of Tyre|Pygmalion]] of Tyre (820\u2013774&nbsp;BC).{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}} The collection of city-states constituting Phoenicia came to be characterized by outsiders and the Phoenicians as ''Sidonia'' or ''Tyria,'' and Phoenicians and Canaanites alike were called ''Sidonians'' or ''Tyrians'', as one Phoenician city came to prominence after another.\n\n=== Decline: 539\u201365 BC ===\n\n==== Persian rule ====\n{{Main|Achaemenid Phoenicia}}\n[[File:A naval action during the siege of Tyre by Andre Castaigne (1898-1899).jpg|right|thumb|A naval action during the siege of [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in [[Lebanon|South Lebanon]] (350 BC). Drawing by {{lang|fr|[[Andr\u00e9 Castaigne]]}}, 1888\u201389.]]\nPhoenicia was came under Persian domination followed the conquests of King [[Cyrus the Great]] in 539&nbsp;BC. The Phoenicians were then divided into four vassal kingdoms: [[Sidon]], [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], [[Arwad]], and [[Byblos]]. Under [[Darius the Great|Darius I]], the area comprising Phoenicia, Palestine, Syria, and Cyprus was consolidated into a single [[Satrap|''satrapy'']] (province) and made to pay a yearly tribute of 350 ''[[Talent (measurement)|talents]]''. By comparison, Egypt and Libya paid 700 talents.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Histories, Book III|last=Herodotus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=218, \u00a791}}</ref> The otherwise decentralized nature of Persian administration meant the Phoenicians, while declining in influence, remained relatively autonomous in their affairs and mercantile activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brewminate.com/a-history-of-phoenician-civilization/|title=A History of Phoenician Civilization|last=MAMcIntosh|date=2018-08-29|website=Brewminate|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nDuring this period, many Phoenicians left to establish independent city-states elsewhere in the Mediterranean, particularly father west, including Carthage in the North Africa. The Phoenicians of [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] showed greater solidarity with their former colony [[Carthage]] than loyalty towards Persian king [[Cambyses II]], refusing the latter's order's to sail against the former.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Histories, Book III|last=Herodotus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=\u00a719}}</ref> In fact, \n\nThe Phoenicians furnished the bulk of the Persian fleet during the [[Greco-Persian Wars]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Histories, Book V|last=Herodotus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=\u00a7109}}</ref> Herodotus considers them \"the best sailors\" in the Persian fleet.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Histories, Book V|last=Herodotus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=\u00a796}}</ref> Phoenicians under [[Xerxes I]] were equally commended for their ingenuity in building the [[Xerxes Canal]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Histories, Book VII|last=Herodotus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=\u00a723}}</ref> Nevertheless, they were harshly punished by the Persian king following the defeat of the [[Achaemenid Empire]] at the [[Battle of Salamis]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Histories, Book VIII|last=Herodotus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=\u00a790}}</ref>\n\nIn 350 or 345&nbsp;BC, King [[Tennes]] of Sidon led a failed rebellion against [[Artaxerxes III]], enlisting the help of the Egyptians, who were subsequently drawn into a war with the Persians. A detailed account of the rebellion and subsequent conflict was described by [[Diodorus Siculus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/16C*.html|title=LacusCurtius \u2022 Diodorus Siculus \u2014 Book\u00a0XVI Chapters\u00a040\u201165|website=penelope.uchicago.edu|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Macedonian rule ====\n[[Alexander the Great]] took Tyre in 332&nbsp;BC after the [[Siege of Tyre (332 BC)|Siege of Tyre]]. Alexander was exceptionally harsh to Tyre, [[Crucifixion|crucifying]] 2,000 of the leading citizens, but he maintained the king in power.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ancient.eu/article/107/alexanders-siege-of-tyre-332-bce/|title=Alexander's Siege of Tyre, 332 BCE|website=Ancient History Encyclopedia|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref> He gained control of the other cities peacefully: the ruler of Aradus submitted; the king of Sidon was overthrown. Following Alexander, the Phoenician homeland was controlled by a succession of Macedonian rulers: [[Laomedon of Mytilene|Laomedon]] (323&nbsp;BC), [[Ptolemy I]] (320), [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]] (315), [[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius]] (301), and [[Seleucus I Nicator|Seleucus]] (296). The [[rise of Macedon]] gradually ousted the remnants of Phoenicia's former dominance over the Eastern Mediterranean trade routes. Between 286 and 197&nbsp;BC, Phoenicia (except for Aradus) fell to the Ptolemies of Egypt, who installed the high priests of [[Astarte]] as vassal rulers in Sidon ([[Eshmunazar I]], [[Tabnit]], [[Eshmunazar II]]).\n\nIn 197&nbsp;BC, Phoenicia along with Syria reverted to the [[Seleucids]]. The region became increasingly Hellenized, although Tyre became autonomous in 126&nbsp;BC, followed by Sidon in 111. While Phoenician culture disappeared entirely in the motherland, Carthage continued to flourish in Northwest Africa. It oversaw the mining of iron and [[precious metal]]s from Iberia, and used its considerable naval power and mercenary armies to protect commercial interests, until Rome finally destroyed it in 146&nbsp;BC at the end of the [[Punic Wars]].\n\nSyria, including Phoenicia, was seized and ruled by king [[Tigranes the Great]] of [[Armenia]] from 82 until 69&nbsp;BC, when he was defeated by [[Lucullus]]. In 65&nbsp;BC, [[Pompey]] finally incorporated the territory as part of the [[Roman Syria|Roman province of Syria]]. Phoenicia became a [[Phoenice (Roman province)|separate province]] c. AD&nbsp;200.\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n=== Genetic studies ===\n{{History of Lebanon (ancient)}}{{History of Syria}}\n[[File:MuseoArqueologicoCadiz-P1050192.JPG|thumb|left|Phoenician [[Sarcophagus|sarcophagi]] found in C\u00e1diz, now in the Archaeological Museum of C\u00e1diz; the sarcophagi are thought to have been imported from the Phoenician homeland around Sidon.<ref>A. B. Freijeiro, R. Corzo S\u00e1nchez, Der neue anthropoide Sarkophag von Cadiz. In: Madrider Mitteilungen 22, 1981.</ref>]]\n\n[[Levant]]ine [[Semitic people|Semites]] ([[Lebanese people|Lebanese]], [[Mizrahi Jews]], [[Palestinians]], and [[Syrians]]) are thought to be the closest surviving relatives of the ancient Phoenicians, with more than 90% genetic similarity between the modern day Lebanese and Bronze Age [[Sidonian]]s.<ref>https://www.latimes.com/science/sciencenow/la-sci-sn-canaanite-lebanese-genetics-20170727-story.html</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lucotte|first=G\u00e9rard|last2=Mercier|first2=G\u00e9raldine|date=2003|title=Y-chromosome DNA haplotypes in Jews: comparisons with Lebanese and Palestinians|journal=Genetic Testing|volume=7|issue=1|pages=67\u201371|doi=10.1089/109065703321560976|issn=1090-6576|pmid=12820706}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2000/05/000509003653.htm|title=Jews Are The Genetic Brothers Of Palestinians, Syrians, And Lebanese|work=ScienceDaily|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Haber|first=Marc|last2=Doumet-Serhal|first2=Claude|last3=Scheib|first3=Christiana|last4=Xue|first4=Yali|last5=Danecek|first5=Petr|last6=Mezzavilla|first6=Massimo|last7=Youhanna|first7=Sonia|last8=Martiniano|first8=Rui|last9=Prado-Martinez|first9=Javier|date=2017-08-03|title=Continuity and Admixture in the Last Five Millennia of Levantine History from Ancient Canaanite and Present-Day Lebanese Genome Sequences|url=http://www.cell.com/ajhg/fulltext/S0002-9297(17)30276-8|journal=The American Journal of Human Genetics|language=English|volume=101|issue=2|pages=274\u2013282|doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2017.06.013|pmid=28757201|pmc=5544389|issn=0002-9297}}</ref> \n\nA 2008 study led by [[Pierre Zalloua]] claimed that six subclades of [[Haplogroup J-M172|haplogroup J2]] (J-M172) J2 were \"a Phoenician signature\" amongst modern male populations tested in \"the coastal Lebanese Phoenician Heartland and the broader area of the rest of the Levant (the \"Phoenician Periphery\")\", followed by \"Cyprus and South Turkey; then Crete; then Malta and East Sicily; then South Sardinia, Ibiza, and Southern Spain; and, finally, Coastal Tunisia and cities like Tingris [sic] in Morocco\". (Samples from other areas with significant Phoenician settlements, in Libya and southern France could not be included.) This deliberately sequential sampling represented an attempt to develop a methodology that could link the documented historical expansion of a population, with a particular geographic genetic pattern or patterns. The researchers suggested that the proposed genetic signature stemmed from \"a common source of related lineages rooted in [[Lebanon]]\".<ref name=\"Zalloua 2008\">{{cite journal |last=Zalloua |first=Pierre A. |title=Identifying Genetic Traces of Historical Expansions: Phoenician Footprints in the Mediterranean |journal=[[American Journal of Human Genetics]] |year=2008 |volume=83 |issue=5 |pages=633\u2013642 |doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2008.10.012 |pmid=18976729 |pmc=2668035|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\nA follow up study by Zalloua in 2013 subsequently showed that none of the geographical communities tested carried significantly higher levels of the proposed \"Phoenician signature\" than the others. This suggested that genetic variation preceded religious variation and divisions and, by the time it became Phoenicia, \"[[Lebanon]] already had well-differentiated communities with their own genetic peculiarities, but not significant differences, and religions came as layers of paint on top.\" <ref>{{cite web |last=Maroon |first=Habib |title=A geneticist with a unifying message |url=http://www.nature.com/nmiddleeast/2013/130331/full/nmiddleeast.2013.46.html |work=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |accessdate=3 October 2013 |date=31 March 2013 }}</ref> Another study found evidence for genetic persistence on the Spanish island of [[Ibiza]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tom\u00e0s |first1=Carme|title=Differential maternal and paternal contributions to the genetic pool of Ibiza Island, Balearic Archipelago |journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology |date=2006 |volume=129 |issue=2 |pages=268\u2013278 |doi=10.1002/ajpa.20273 |pmid=16323196 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a sixth-century B.C. skeleton of a young Carthaginian man, excavated from a Punic tomb in [[Byrsa]] Hill in Tunsia, was found bearing the rare [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|U5b2c1]] maternal haplogroup. The lineage of this \"Young Man of Byrsa\" is believed to represent early gene flow from [[Iberia]] to the [[Maghreb]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matisoo-Smith |first1=Elizabeth A. |last2=Gosling |first2=Anna L. |last3=Boocock |first3=James |last4=Kardailsky |first4=Olga |last5=Kurumilian |first5=Yara |last6=Roudesli-Chebbi |first6=Sihem |date=25 May 2016 |title=A European Mitochondrial Haplotype Identified in Ancient Phoenician Remains from Carthage, North Africa |journal=[[PLoS ONE]] |volume=11 |issue=5 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0155046 |display-authors=etal |pages=e0155046 |pmid=27224451 |pmc=4880306|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1155046M }}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Phoenicia map-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|Map of Phoenicia.]]\n\n=== Trade ===\n{{See also|Phoenicians and wine}}\nThe Phoenicians were among the greatest traders of their time and owed much of their prosperity to trade. At first, they traded mainly with the Greeks, trading [[wood]], [[slave]]s, [[glass]] and powdered [[Tyrian purple]]. Tyrian purple was a violet-purple dye used by the Greek [[elite]] to color garments. As trading and colonizing spread over the Mediterranean, Phoenicians and Greeks seemed to have split that sea in two: the Phoenicians sailed along and eventually dominated the southern shore, while the Greeks were active along the northern shores. The two cultures rarely clashed, mainly in the [[Sicilian Wars]], and eventually settled into two spheres of influence, the Phoenician in the west and the Greek to the east.\n\nIn the centuries after 1200&nbsp;BC, the Phoenicians were the major naval and trading power of the region. Phoenician trade was founded on the Tyrian purple dye, a violet-purple dye derived from the [[hypobranchial gland]] of the ''[[Murex]]'' sea-snail, once profusely available in coastal waters of the eastern Mediterranean Sea but exploited to local extinction. [[James B. Pritchard]]'s excavations at [[Sarepta]] in present-day [[Lebanon]] revealed crushed ''Murex'' shells and pottery containers stained with the dye that was being produced at the site. The Phoenicians established a second production center for the dye in [[Mogador]], in present-day [[Morocco]]. Brilliant textiles were a part of Phoenician wealth, and Phoenician [[glass]] was another export ware.\n\nTo Egypt, where grapevines would not grow, the eighth century Phoenicians sold [[wine]]; the wine trade with Egypt is vividly documented by the shipwrecks located in 1997 in the open sea {{convert|50|km|-1}} west of [[Ashkelon|Ascalon]].<ref>{{cite book |first=L. E. |last=Stager |chapter=Phoenician shipwrecks in the deep sea |title=Sea routes: From Sidon to Huelva: Interconnections in the Mediterranean, 16th\u20136th&nbsp;c.&nbsp;BC |year=2003 |pages=233\u2013248 |isbn=978-960-7064-40-0 }}</ref> Pottery kilns at [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in [[Lebanon|South Lebanon]] and [[Sarepta]] produced the large terracotta jars used for transporting wine. From Egypt, the Phoenicians bought [[Nubia]]n gold. Additionally, great cedar logs were traded with lumber-poor Egypt for significant sums. Sometime between 1075 and 1060 BC an Egyptian envoy by the name of Wen-Amon visited Phoenicia and secured seven great cedar logs in exchange for a mixed cargo including \"4 crocks and 1 kak-men of gold; 5 silver jugs; 10 garments of royal linen; 10 kherd of good linen from Upper Egypt; 500 rolls of finished papyrus; 500 cows' hides; 500 ropes; 20 bags of lentils and 30 baskets of fish.\" Those logs were then moved by ship from Phoenicia to Egypt.{{sfnp|Cunliffe|2008|pp=241\u20132}}\n\nFrom elsewhere, they obtained other materials, perhaps the most important being [[silver]] from (at least) [[Sardinia]] and the [[Iberian Peninsula]]. Tin was required which, when smelted with copper from Cyprus, created the durable metal alloy bronze. The archaeologist Glenn Markoe suggests that tin \"may have been acquired from [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] by way of the Atlantic coast or southern Spain; alternatively, it may have come from northern Europe ([[Cornwall]] or [[Brittany]]) via the [[Rhone valley]] and coastal [[Marseille|Massalia]]\".{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|p=103}} [[Strabo]] states that there was a highly lucrative Phoenician trade with Britain for tin via the [[Cassiterides]] whose location is unknown but may have been off the northwest coast of the Iberian Peninsula.<ref>Christopher Hawkes, \"Britain and Julius Caesar,\" Proceedings of the British Academy 63 (1977) 124\u2013192</ref> Professor Timothy Champion, discussing Diodorus Siculus's comments on the tin trade, states that \"Diodorus never actually says that the Phoenicians sailed to Cornwall. In fact, he says quite the opposite: the production of [[Mining in Cornwall and Devon|Cornish tin]] was in the hands of the natives of Cornwall, and its transport to the Mediterranean was organised by local merchants, by sea and then over land through France, well outside Phoenician control.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Champion |first=Timothy |title=The appropriation of the Phoenicians in British imperial ideology |journal=Nations and Nationalism |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=451\u2013465 |doi=10.1111/1469-8219.00027 |year=2001 }}</ref>\n\n[[Tarshish]] ({{lang-he|\u05ea\u05b7\u05bc\u05e8\u05b0\u05e9\u05b4\u05c1\u05d9\u05e9\u05c1}}) occurs in the Hebrew Bible with several uncertain meanings, and one of the most recurring is that Tarshish is a place, probably a city or country, that is far from the [[Land of Israel]] by sea where trade occurs with Israel and Phoenicia. It was a place where Phoenicians reportedly obtained different metals, particularly silver, during the reign of Solomon. The [[Septuagint]], the Vulgate and the Targum of Jonathan render Tarshish as Carthage, but other biblical commentators read it as [[Tartessos]] perhaps in ancient {{lang|la|Hispania}} (Iberian Peninsula). William F. Albright (1941) and Frank M. Cross (1972)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Albright |first1=W.F. |year=1941 |title=New light on the early history of Phoenician colonization |journal=Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research |volume=83 |issue=83 |pages=14\u201322 |doi=10.2307/3218739|jstor=3218739 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cross |first1=Frank M. |year=1972 |title=An interpretation of the Nora Stone |journal=Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research |volume=208 |issue=208 |pages=13\u201319 |doi=10.2307/1356374 |jstor=1356374 }}</ref> suggested Tarshish might be or was Sardinia because of the discovery of the Nora Stone and Nora Fragment, the former of which mentions Tarshish in its Phoenician inscription. Christine M. Thompson (2003)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thompson |first1=C.M. |year=2003 |title=Sealed silver in Iron Age Cisjordan and the 'invention' of coinage |journal=Oxford Journal of Archaeology |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=67\u2013107 |doi=10.1111/1468-0092.00005 }}</ref> identified a concentration of [[hacksilver]] hoards dating between {{circa|1200}} and 586 BC in Cisjordan Corpus. This silver-dominant Cisjordan Corpus is unparalleled in the contemporary Mediterranean, and within it occurs a unique concentration in Phoenicia of silver hoards dated between 1200 and 800 B.C. [[Hacksilver]] objects in these Phoenician hoards display lead isotope ratios that match ores in Sardinia and Spain.{{r|ThompsonSkaggs2013}} This metallic evidence agrees with the biblical memory of a western Mediterranean Tarshish that supplied Solomon with silver via Phoenicia. Assyrian records indicate Tarshish was an island, and the poetic construction of [[Psalm 72]] points to its identity as a large island in the west \u2014 the island of Sardinia.{{r|ThompsonSkaggs2013}}\n\nThe Phoenicians established commercial outposts throughout the Mediterranean, the most strategically important being [[Carthage]] in northwest Africa, southeast of Sardinia on the peninsula of present day Tunisia. Ancient Gaelic mythologies attribute a Phoenician/Scythian influx to Ireland by a leader called [[Fenius Farsa]]. Others also sailed south along the coast of Africa. A Carthaginian expedition led by [[Hanno the Navigator]] explored and colonized the Atlantic coast of Africa as far as the [[Gulf of Guinea]]; Herodotus described a Phoenician expedition sent down the [[Red Sea]] by Egyptian pharaoh [[Necho II]] ({{circa|600&nbsp;BC}}) that [[circumnavigation|circumnavigated]] Africa and returned through the [[Pillars of Hercules]] after three years.\n\nIn the [[2nd millennium BC|2nd millennium B.C.]], the Phoenicians had a flourishing trade with Somali city-states in the Horn of Africa, particularly [[Mosylon]], [[Opone]], [[Malao (ancient)|Malao]], [[Sarapion]], [[Mundus (city)|Mundus]] and [[Tabae]]. \n\n=== Phoenician ships ===\nAs a predominately maritime people, the Phoenicians were among the earliest and most influential pioneers in shipbuilding and design. Naval historian [[Richard Woodman]] described them as \"the first true seafarers, founding the art of pilotage, cabotage, and navigation\" and the inventors of \"the first true ship, built of planks, capable of carrying a deadweight cargo and being sailed and steered.\" \n\nAs early as 1200 B.C., the Phoenicians were building large merchant ships. During the Bronze Age, they developed the [[keel]], the bottom-most longitudinal structural element on a ship, which was a significant advancement over the more common [[Dugout canoe|dugout]] vessels, which were limited in size, durability, maneuverability. Pegged [[Mortise and tenon|mortise-and-tenon]] joints were developed to make Phoenician ships sturdier, and proved effective enough to serve as a standard template across the Mediterranean until late into the Roman Empire.\n\nOther key ship components, such as the [[Brail|brailed rig sail]], which allowed for greater maneuverability, and the [[crow's nest]], which provided a vital lookout point, most likely originated in the Levant. Around 700 B.C., the Phoenicians were possibly the first to introduce the [[bireme]], a large war [[galley]] that had two banks of oars staggered on either side of the vessel, allowing for significantly greater propulsion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/technology/galley-ship|title=Galley {{!}} ship|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> The Carthaginians, who descended from the Phoenicians, had become a major power in the western Mediterranean largely because of their ability to efficient mass produce ships; parts were even labeled with the Punic alphabet.<ref>Piero Bartoloni, \u201cShips and Navigation,\u201d in The Phoenicians, ed. Sabatino Moscati (New York: Abbeville, 1988), p 76.</ref>\n\nIn addition to ships, the Phoenicians developed or contributed several other maritime inventions. the [[amphora]], a type of container used for both dry and liquid gods, was an ancient Phoenician invention that became a standardized measurement of volume for close to two thousand years. The remnants of sophisticated and self-cleaning artificial harbors have been discovered in Sidon, Tyre, Atlit, and Acre.<ref>Arad Haggi, \u201cReport on Underwater Excavation at the Phoenician Harbour, Atlit, Israel,\u201d International Journal of Nautical Archeology 39 (2010): 283.</ref> The Phoenicians relied on [[celestial navigation]], and most likely discovered Polaris (the North Star), which enabled nighttime sailing and shorter open-sea routes; the Greeks subsequently called Polaris the \"Phoenician Star.\" The wind rose, a precursor to the compass rose, was apparently of Phoenician, or at least Levantine, origin. The first example of [[admiralty law]] also appears in the Levant.<ref>Shelley Wachsmann, Seagoing Ships & Seamanship in the Bronze Age Levant (College Station, TX: Texas A & M University Press, 1998), 300, 51, 323-325, 332.</ref> The Phoenicians continued to contribute to cartography into the Iron Age.<ref>Mark Woolmer, Ancient Phoenicia: An Introduction (London: Bristol Classical Press, 2011), p. 84.</ref>\n\nThe Greeks had two names for Phoenician ships: {{lang|grc-Latn|Galloi}} (tubs) and {{lang|grc-Latn|hippoi}} (horses). The names are readily explained by depictions of Phoenician ships in the palaces of Assyrian kings from the 7th and 8th centuries, which were tub shaped (''{{lang|grc-Latn|galloi}}'') and had horse heads on both ends. (''{{lang|grc-Latn|hippoi}}''). It is possible that the ''{{lang|grc-Latn|hippoi}}'' come from Phoenician connections with the Greek god [[Poseidon]], equated with the Semitic-Levantine god [[Yam (god)|Yam]].\n\nIn 2014, a Phoenician trading ship was found near [[Gozo]] island in Malta. Dated 700 BC, it is one of the oldest wrecks in the Mediterranean. The vessel was about 50 feet long and contained 50 amphorae full of wine and oil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seeker.com/2700-year-old-phoenician-shipwreck-discovered-1769022411.html|title=2,700-Year-Old Phoenician Shipwreck Discovered|work=Seeker|date=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tel Balawat]] gates of an Assyrian palace (ninth century B.C.) located near Nimrud portrays ships coming to honor [[Shalmaneser III]].{{sfnp|Markoe|2000}}<ref>http://www.qsov.com/UK2006/718BM.JPG</ref> In another Assyrian palace, built for [[Sargon II]] and located in northern Iraq, the [[Khorsabad]] bas-relief (7th century B.C.) shows ships transporting timber, most likely cedar, from Lebanon.<ref>{{cite web |title=Assyria: Khorsabad (Room10c) |publisher=[[British Museum]] |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/galleries/middle_east/room_10c_assyria_khorsabad.aspx }}</ref>\n\n== Important cities and colonies ==\n{{main|List of Phoenician cities}}\n\nThe Phoenicians were not a nation in the political sense, but were organized into independent city-states that shared a common language and culture. The leading city states were Sur ([[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]), Sydon ([[Sidon]]), and Jbail (modern [[Byblos]], one of the oldest sites of civilization). Numerous others existed, including Berut (modern [[Beirut]]) Ampi, Amia, Arqa, [[Baalbek]], Botrys, Sarepta and [[Tripoli]]. From the late tenth century BC, the Phoenician's expansive culture led them to establish cities and colonies beyond Lebanon and throughout the Mediterranean. Canaanite deities like [[Baal]] and [['Ashtart|Astarte]] were being worshiped from Cyprus and Sicily to Spain and Portugal, most notably at Carthage (''{{lang|phn|Qart Hada\u0161t}}'') in modern Tunisia.\n{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| direction = \n| width = 330\n| image1 = Griechischen und ph\u00f6nizischen Kolonien.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Carthage Holdings.png\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Left, map of Phoenician (in yellow) and Greek colonies around 8th to 6th century BC (with German legend). Right, extent of [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] influence prior to 264 BC.\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n\n'''Modern [[Lebanon]] (the center of Phoenicia)'''\n* [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] (one of Phoenicia's two leading-city states)\n* Sydon [[Sidon]] (one of Phoenicia's two leading-city states)\n* Berut (modern [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]'s capital today)\n* Ampi\n* Amia\n* Arqa\n* [[Baalbek]]\n* Botrys\n* Jbail (modern [[Byblos]] and one of the oldest sites of civilization)\n* Sarepta\n* [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]]\n\n'''Modern [[Algeria]]'''\n* [[Cirta]] (modern [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]])\n* [[Calama (Numidia)|Calama]] (modern [[Guelma]])\n* Igigili (modern [[Jijel]])\n* [[Hippo Regius|Hippo]] (modern [[Annaba]])\n* [[Icosium]] (modern [[Algiers]])\n* Iol (modern [[Cherchell]])\n* Tipasa (modern [[Tipaza]])\n* Timgad (modern [[Timgad]])\n'''[[Cyprus]]'''\n* Kition (modern [[Larnaca]])\n* Idalion (modern [[Dali, Cyprus]])\n* [[Marion, Cyprus|Marion]] (modern [[Polis, Cyprus]])\n'''Modern Italy'''\n* [[Sardinia]]\n** Karalis (modern [[Cagliari]])\n** [[Nora, Italy|Nora]]\n** [[Olbia]]\n** [[Sulci]]<ref>Claudian, B. Gild. 518</ref>\n** [[Tharros]]\n* [[Sicily]]\n** Kosyra ([[Pantelleria]])\n** Lampas ([[Lampedusa]])\n** Lilybaeaum (modern [[Marsala]]) after the [[Siege of Motya]] and its destruction\n** [[Motya]]\n** [[Soluntum]]\n** Zyz (modern [[Palermo]])\n'''Modern [[Libya]]'''\n* [[Leptis Magna]]\n* [[Oea]] (modern [[Tripoli]])\n* [[Sabratha]]\n* [[Thubactis]] (modern [[Misurata]])\n'''The islands of [[Malta]]'''\n* [[Melite (ancient city)|Maleth]] (modern {{lang|mt|[[Mdina]]}}){{r|MaltaHist}}\n* {{lang|mt|G\u0127ajn Qajjet}}<ref>{{cite journal |first=J. G. |last=Baldacchino |first2=T. J. |last2=Dunbabin |title=Rock tomb at G\u0127ajn Qajjet, near Rabat, Malta |journal=Papers of the British School at Rome |volume=21 |year=1953 |pages=32\u201341 |jstor=40310522 |doi=10.1017/s0068246200006413|url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar//handle/123456789/7274 }}</ref>\n* {{lang|mt|[[Tas-Sil\u0121]]}}<ref name=MaltaHist>[http://members.ziggo.nl/bezver/romans.html A History of Malta]</ref>\n* {{lang|mt|[[Mtarfa]]}}<ref>Annual Report on the Working of the Museum Department 1926\u201327, Malta 1927, 8</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=W. |last=Culican |chapter=The repertoire of Phoenician pottery |title=Ph\u00f6nizier im Westen |location=Mainz |publisher=Zabern |year=1982 |pages=45\u201382 |isbn=978-3-8053-0486-3 }}</ref>\n* {{lang|mt|Qallilija}}<ref>Annual Report on the Working of the Museum Department 1916\u20137, Malta 1917, 9\u201310.</ref>\n* {{lang|mt|[[Ras il-Wardija]]}} in [[Gozo]]{{r|MaltaHist}}\n'''Modern Portugal'''\n* ''Baal Saphon'' or ''Baal Shamen'', later romanized as [[Balsa (Roman town)|Balsa]] (modern [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]], [[Algarve]])<ref>{{cite web |author=Lu\u00eds Fraga da Silva |year=2008 |title=The Roman Town of Balsa |publisher=Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Campo Arqueol\u00f3gico de [[Tavira]], Portugal |url=http://www.arkeotavira.com/balsa/BALSA-wikipedia.pdf }}<br /> {{cite web |author=Lu\u00eds Fraga da Silva |year=2003 |title=Tavira: Cidades e Regi\u00e3o antes de Portugal |website=Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Campo Arqueol\u00f3gico de [[Tavira]] |language=Pt |url=http://geohistorica.net/arkeotavira.com/arqueologia/tavira/atlas/TAVIRA.pdf }} From [http://geohistorica.net/arkeotavira.com/arqueologia/tavira/atlas/index.html Campo Arqueol\u00f3gico de Tavira]</ref>\n* [[Lisbon#Pre-Roman|Lisbon]] was probably a Phoenician trading post, rather than a settlement.\n'''Modern Spain'''\n* [[Abdera, Spain|Abdera]] (modern [[Adra, Spain|Adra]]) and its dependencies in the 3rd century BC.\n* Abyla (modern [[Ceuta]], on the Moroccan coast)\n* Akra Leuke (modern [[Alicante]])\n* Gadir (modern [[C\u00e1diz]])\n* Speculum Rotae (modern Rota)\n* Ibossim (modern [[Ibiza]])\n* Malaka or ''mlk'' (modern [[M\u00e1laga]]){{sfnp|Aubet|2001}}\n* Onoba (modern [[Huelva]])\n* [[Cartagena, Spain|Qart Hada\u0161t]] ({{lang-el|\u039d\u03ad\u03b1 \u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b7\u03b4\u03cc\u03bd\u03b1}}; {{lang-la|Carthago Nova}}; {{lang-es|Cartagena}})\n* Rusadir (modern [[Melilla]], on the Moroccan coast)\n* [[Sexi (Phoenician colony)|Sexi]] (modern [[Almu\u00f1\u00e9car]])\n'''Modern [[Tunisia]]'''\n* [[Carthage|Qart Hada\u0161t]] ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b7\u03b4\u03cc\u03bd\u03b1}}; {{lang-la|Carthago}}; {{lang-es|Cartago}})\n* [[Hadrumetum]] (modern [[Sousse|Susat]])\n* [[Bizerte|Hippo Diarrhytus]] (modern [[Bizerte]])\n* [[Kerkouane]]\n* Sicca (modern [[El Kef]])\n* [[Thapsus]] (near modern [[Bekalta]])\n* [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]]\n'''Modern [[Turkey]]'''\n* Phoenicus (modern [[Finike]])\n'''Modern [[Morocco]]'''\n* Acra\n* [[Mogador|Arambys]] (Mogador)<ref>{{cite book |first=C. Michael |last=Hogan |chapter=Mogador: promontory fort |title=The Megalithic Portal |editor-first=A. |editor-last=Burnham |date=Nov 2, 2007 |chapterurl=http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=17926 }}</ref>\n* Caricus Murus\n* Gytta\n* [[Lixus (ancient city)|Lixus]] (modern [[Larache]])\n* Tingis (modern [[Tangier]])\n* [[Volubilis]]\n'''Modern [[Mauritania]]'''\n* [[Hanno the Navigator | Cerne]]\n'''Other colonies'''\n* Callista (on modern [[Santorini]])\n* Calpe (modern [[Gibraltar]])\n* Gunugu\n* Thenae\n* Tipassa\n* Sundar\n* Surya\n* Shobina\n* Tara\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Society and Culture ==\nVery little of the Phoenician's own records and writings have survived, meaning much of what is known comes from the accounts of contemporary civilizations or inferences from archaeological discoveries. The first century A.D. geographer [[Pomponius Mela]] once described the Phoenicians as \"a clever race, who prospered in war and peace\" and \"excelled in writing and literature, and in other arts, in seamanship, and in ruling an empire.\"<ref name=\":0\">The Phoenicians: A Captivating Guide to the History of Phoenicia and the Impact Made by One of the Greatest Trading Civilizations of the Ancient World, ''Captivating History'' (December 16, 2019), ISBN: 9781647482053, p. 31.</ref> By contrast, their reputation as primarily traders and merchants meant they were sometimes regarded as overly materialistic, unprincipled, and rapacious.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nPhoenicians had much in common with other Canaanites, including language, religion, social customs, and a monarchical political system centered around city-states. However, by the early Iron Age (roughly 1300 B.C.) the Phoenicians had emerged as a distinct people, with their culture, economy, and daily life being heavily centered on commerce and maritime trade. Their propensity for seafaring brought them into contact with numerous other civilizations, possibly more so than any other contemporary people, leading to a uniquely cosmopolitan society that incorporated different customs, artistic styles, and faith traditions. \n\n=== Political structure ===\nDespite a shared language, culture, and religion, the Phoenicians never constituted a single, cohesive political unit, and it is unknown whether they viewed themselves as a nation in the modern sense. The Phoenicians organized themselves along city-states that were fiercely independent in both domestic and foreign affairs. Formal alliances between city-states was rare, and cooperation was generally informal, loosely aligned, and ad hoc. Unlike their Greek counterparts, warfare between Phoenician city-states was rare, although rivalries did exist and coercion was sometimes employed. The relative power and influence of city-states varied over time. Sidon was dominant between the 12th and 11th centuries B.C., and exercise some influence over its neighbors, but by the tenth century B.C., Tyre rose to become the most powerful polity. \n\nPhoenician society was highly stratified and predominantly [[Monarchy|monarchical]]. Heredity kings usually governed with absolute power and had responsibilities over civic, commercial, and religious affairs. Rulers often relied upon senior officials derived from the noble and merchant classes. The priesthood was a distinct class, though usually of royal lineage or from leading merchant families. The king was considered a representative of the gods and carried many obligations and duties with respective to religious processions and rituals. Priests were thus highly influential and often became intertwined with the royal family. \n\nUnlike their Greek and Egyptian counterparts, Phoenician kings did not commemorate their reign through sculptures or monuments. Their wealth, power, and accomplishments were usually conveyed through ornate sarcophaguses, of which the most famous is [[Ahiram sarcophagus|Ahiram]] of Byblos. The Phoenicians kept fairly meticulous records of their rulers in the form of tomb inscriptions, which are among the few primary sources still available. Historians have been able to determine a clear line of succession spanning centuries for some city-states, notably Byblos and Tyre.\n\n==== Proto-democratic government ====\nNot all Phoenician city-states were governed as absolute monarchies. The long span of Phoenician history yielded various political changes and experiments. In the sixth century B.C., Tyre adopted a system of government consisting of a pair of judges known as ''suffetes,'' each chosen from the most powerful noble families and wielding absolute power. By the seventh century B.C., many city-states had circumscribed the power of their kings, who thereafter had to share power with largely independent sailors and traders, on whom the prosperity of the city-state heavily rested. Kings increasingly required the support of different stakeholders, and there is evidence that the councils and assemblies that had previously played an advisory role had accumulated some power over the state. The Greek historian [[Arrian]] reported that senior officials were sometimes called upon to govern when the king was predisposed, and accounts from other outsiders claimed that councils were the true rulers, such that they could impose their decisions on the king during emergencies.\n\nThere is some sparse evidence, mostly from Egyptian and Assyrian diplomatic records, that certain Phoenician city-states had constitutions and republican forms of government. As early as the fourteenth century B.C., Egyptian envoys reported that assemblies \"might act on their own behalf;\" when the city-state of Irqata declared its allegiance to the pharaoh, it did so as \"Irqata and its elders\" without reference to a king.<ref name=\":1\">Stephen Stockwell, Geopolitics, History, and International Relations , Vol. 2, No. 2 (2010), pp. 123- 135</ref> Similarly, the pharaoh is addressed by \"the citizens of Tunip,\" the \u201cpeople from Gubla (Byblos),\" and \"the men of Arwad.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> In the fourth century B.C., when the armies of Alexander the Great approached Tyre, they were met not by a king but by \"representatives\" of the \"the commonwealth\" or the \"community.\" In a diplomatic exchange, it was \"the people\" of Tyre who passed a decree in response.\n\nIn light of these accounts, some scholars have argued that the Phoenicians had at least experimented with proto-democratic forms of government, possibly evening influencing the development of democracy in Athens.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Stephen Stockwell, \u201cBefore Athens: Early Popular Government in Phoenician and Greek City States,\u201d Geopolitics, History, and International Relations 2 (2010): 123-133.</ref>\n\n=== Law and administration ===\nAfter the king and council, the two most important political positions in virtually every Phoenician city-state were that of governor and commander of the army. Details regarding the duties of these offices are sparse, but it is known that the governor was responsible for collecting taxes, implementing decrees, supervising judges, and ensuring the administration of law and justice.<ref name=\":0\" /> As warfare was rare among the mostly mercantile Phoenicians, the commander of the army was generally responsible for ensuring the defense and security of the city-state and its hintelands.\n\nThe Phoenicians had a system of courts and judges that resolved disputes and punished crimes based on a semi-codified body of law and traditional. Laws were implemented by the state and were the responsibility of the ruler and certain designated officials. In common with other Levantine societies, laws were harsh and biased, reflecting the social stratification of society. The murder of a commoner was treated as less serious than of a nobleman, and the upper classes had the most rights; the wealthy could often escape punishment by paying a fine. Free men could represent themselves in court and had more rights than women and children, while slaves had no rights at all. Men could often deflect punishment to their wives, children, or slaves, even having them serve his sentence in his place. Lawyers eventually emerged as a profession for those who could not plead their own case.\n\nAs in neighboring societies at the time, penalties for crimes were often severe, usually reflecting the principle of reciprocity; for example, the killing of a slave would be punished by having the offender's slave killed. Imprisonment was rare, with fines, exile, punishment, and execution were main remedies.\n\n=== Language ===\n{{Main|Phoenician language|Phoenician alphabet|Alphabet}}\n\nThe Phoenician alphabet was one of the first (consonantal) alphabets with a strict and consistent form. It is assumed that it adopted its simplified linear characters from an as-yet unattested early pictorial [[Proto-Canaanite|Semitic alphabet]] developed some centuries earlier in the southern Levant.{{sfnp|Coulmas|1996}}<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Millard |first=A. R. |year=1986 |title=The Infancy of the Alphabet |journal=World Archaeology |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=390\u2013398 |doi=10.1080/00438243.1986.9979978 |ref=harv }}</ref> It is likely that the precursor to the Phoenician alphabet was of Egyptian origin, since [[Middle Bronze Age alphabets]] from the southern Levant resemble Egyptian hieroglyphs or an early alphabetic writing system found at [[Wadi el-Hol#The Wadi el-Hol script|Wadi-el-Hol]] in central Egypt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ancient Scripts: Proto-Sinaitic |website=Ancientscripts.com |url=http://www.ancientscripts.com/protosinaitic.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227060348/http://ancientscripts.com/protosinaitic.html |archivedate=2009-02-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/national/science/111499sci-alphabet-origin.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1999-11-13 |accessdate=2010-05-22 |title=Discovery of Egyptian Inscriptions Indicates an Earlier Date for Origin of the Alphabet }}</ref> In addition to being preceded by proto-Canaanite, the Phoenician alphabet was also preceded by an alphabetic script of Mesopotamian origin called [[Ugaritic script|Ugaritic]]. The development of the Phoenician alphabet from the Proto-Canaanite coincided with the rise of the Iron Age in the 11th century BC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omniglot.com/writing/phoenician.htm|title=Phoenician alphabet and language}}</ref>\n\nThis alphabet has been termed an ''[[abjad]]'' \u2014 that is, a script that contains no [[vowel]]s \u2014 from the first four letters ''aleph'', ''beth'', ''gimel'', and ''daleth''.\n\n[[File:Ahiram sarcophag from Biblos XIII-XBC.jpg|thumb|right|Sarcophagus of [[Ahiram]] in the [[National Museum of Beirut]]]]\n\nThe oldest known representation of the Phoenician alphabet is inscribed on the sarcophagus of King [[Ahiram]] of Byblos, dating to the 11th century BC at the latest. Phoenician inscriptions are found in Lebanon, Syria, Israel, Cyprus and other locations, as late as the early centuries of the Christian Era. The Phoenicians are credited with spreading the [[Phoenician alphabet]] throughout the Mediterranean world.<ref>{{cite book | last = Beck | first = Roger B. | last2 = Black| first2 =Linda |first3=Larry S. |last3=Krieger|first4= Phillip C.|last4= Naylor|first5= Dahia Ibo|last5= Shabaka | title = World History: Patterns of Interaction | publisher = McDougal Littell | year = 1999 | location = Evanston, IL | pages = | url =https://archive.org/details/mcdougallittellw00beck| url-access = registration | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-395-87274-1 }}</ref> Phoenician traders disseminated this writing system along Aegean trade routes, to Crete and Greece. The Greeks adopted the majority of these letters but changed some of them to vowels which were significant in their language, giving rise to the first true alphabet.\n\nThe [[Phoenician languages|Phoenician language]] is classified in the [[Canaanite languages|Canaanite]] subgroup of Northwest [[Semitic languages|Semitic]]. Its later descendant in [[northwest Africa]] is termed [[Punic language|Punic,]] which evolved in Phoenician colonies around the western Mediterranean, beginning in the 9th century BC. Punic Phoenician was still spoken in the 5th century AD; [[Augustine of Hippo|St. Augustine]], who grew up in [[Northwest Africa]], was familiar with the language.\n\n=== Art ===\nPhoenician art was largely centered on ornamental objects, particularly jewelry, pottery, glassware, and reliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancient.eu/Phoenician_Art/|title=Phoenician Art|website=Ancient History Encyclopedia|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Large sculptures were rare, although figurines were more common, and while typically crude, depicted individualized features. Phoenician art generally lacked unique characteristics that might distinguish it from its contemporaries; it was highly influenced by the many cultures the Phoenicians traded and interacted with, primarily [[Ancient Egypt|Egypt]], Greece and [[Assyria]]. These influences were sometimes reflected in specific categories of art; Greek inspiration was particularly pronounced in pottery, while Egyptian styles were most reflected in ivory work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancient.eu/Phoenician_Art/|title=Phoenician Art|website=Ancient History Encyclopedia|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Phoenicians who were taught on the banks of the [[Nile]] and the [[Euphrates]] gained a wide artistic experience and finally came to create their own art, which was an amalgam of foreign models and perspectives.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1879/01/05/81740354.pdf|title=Phoenician Art|work = The New York Times |accessdate=2008-06-20 | date=1879-01-05}}</ref> \n\nAn 1879 article from ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Phoenician art thusly:\n\n{{bquote|He entered into other men's labors and made most of his heritage. The [[Sphinx]] of Egypt became [[Asian people|Asiatic]], and its new form was transplanted to [[Nineveh]] on the one side and to Greece on the other. The rosettes and other patterns of the [[Babylonia]]n cylinders were introduced into the handiwork of Phoenicia, and so passed on to the West, while the hero of the ancient [[Chaldea]]n epic became first the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] [[Melkart]]h, and then the [[Herakles]] of Hellas.}}Over time, Egyptian artistic influence became especially prominent, often reflecting the evolving political and economic relations between the two civilization.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/phoe/hd_phoe.htm|title=The Phoenicians (1500\u2013300 B.C.)|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> For example, the famed [[Ahiram sarcophagus]] shows little influence from the concurrent [[Twentieth dynasty of Egypt|20th]] and [[Twenty-first dynasty of Egypt|21st dynasties]] of Egypt\u2014instead bearing heavy influence by cultures in northern Syria<ref name=\":3\">Glenn E. Markoe, ''The Emergence of Phoenician Art'', Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research, No. 279 (Aug., 1990), pp. 13-26, www.jstor.org/stable/1357205</ref>\u2014while subsequent art reflected the revival of Phoenician ties with the [[Twenty-second dynasty of Egypt|22nd Dynasty of Egypt]].<ref>Ellen Rehm: ''Der Ahiram-Sarkophag'', Mainz 2004 (Forschungen zur ph\u00f6nizisch-punischen und zyprischen Plastik, hg. von Renate Bol, II.1. Dynastensarkophage mit szenischen Reliefs aus Byblos und Zypern Teil 1.1)</ref>\n\nPhoenician art also differed from its contemporaries in its continuance of otherwise discarded Bronze Age conventions well into the Iron Age. Based on contemporary accounts, Phoenician artisans were known for their skill with wood, ivory, bronze, and textiles.<ref name=\":2\" /> In the [[Old Testament]], a craftsman from Tyre was commissioned to build and decorate the legendary [[Solomon's Temple]] in Jerusalem, which \"presupposes a well-developed and highly respected craft industry in Phoenicia by the mid-tenth century B.C\".<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>2 Chronicles.</ref> The ''[[Iliad]]'' mentions the embroidered robes of [[Priam]]\u2019s wife, Hecabe, as \"the work of Sidonian women\"<ref>Book 6.</ref> and describes a mixing bowl of [[Repouss\u00e9 and chasing|chased silver]] as \"a masterpiece of Sidonian craftsmanship.\"<ref>Book 13.</ref> The Assyrians appeared to have valued Phoenician ivory work in particular, collecting vast quantities in their palaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/325564|title=Furniture plaque carved in high relief with two Egyptianizing figures flanking a volute tree, ca. 9th\u20138th century B.C.|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nThe Phoenician artistic tradition appears to have been indelibly tied to its people's commercial interests.<ref name=\":4\">Glenn Markoe and Patrick E. McGovern, ''A NATION OF ARTISANS,'' Archaeology, Vol. 43, No. 2 (MARCH/APRIL 1990), p. 32. www.jstor.org/stable/41765806</ref> The second century historian [[Philo of Byblos]] noted that the Phoenician god of craftsmanship, Chousor, was also the inventor of the raft and the first sailor. There are Greek accounts describing the arrival of Phoenician traders bearing \"trinkets and baubles.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> The Phoenicians appeared to have used their knowledge of foreign artistic styles to craft goods that would specifically appeal to certain trading partners, distinguishing not only different cultures but even socioeconomic classes.<ref name=\":4\" /> This is also evidenced in the broad distribution of Phoenician goods, which have been found as west as Spain and Morocco, as north as Russia and as east as Iraq. In fact, much of what is known about Phoenician art is based from excavations outside of Phoenicia proper.\n\n==== Tyrian purple ====\nThe most famed and coveted of Phoenician artistic and commercial goods were fabrics and textiles dyed with [[Tyrian purple]] (named after the major Phoenician city-state of Tyre). In fact, the name ''Phoenicia'' may have derived from the Greek root word for \"purple,\" indicating the extent to which it was the Phoenician's most sought after trading good. The dye was extracted from sea snails native to the Mediterranean, and may have been discovered by the Phoenicians as early as 1750 BC.<ref>St. Clair, Kassia (2016). ''The Secret Lives of Colour''. London: John Murray. p. 162\u2013164.</ref> According to contemporaneous accounts by neighboring civilizations, Tyrian purple was highly prized because of its resistance to weathering and sunlight, which only made it brighter. \n\nBecause the Phoenicians were the sole purveyor of the dye, and due its labor-intensive creation, Tyrian purple was expensive; it subsequently became associated with the upper classes and soon became a [[status symbol]] in several civilizations, most notably the Roman Empire. Assyrian records of tribute from the Phoenicians include \"garments of brightly colored stuff\" that most likely included Tyrian purple. While the designs, ornamentation, and embroidery used in Phoenician textiles were apparently well regarded, the techniques and specific descriptions are unknown.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Women ===\nAs was common in ancient and classical times, Phoenician women had few rights and were considered the property of their fathers or husbands. Nonetheless, compared to their counterparts in most of the Mediterranean and Western Asia, they appeared to have enjoyed some freedoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phoenicia.org/dress.html|title=Phoenicia, Phoenician Dress, Ornaments and Social Habits|website=phoenicia.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> They took part in public events and religious processions, and depictions of banquets show them casually sitting or reclining with men, dancing, and playing music. Women could engage in trade and other business activities, often working as laborers, construction workers, farmers, weavers, and even minors. As in most civilizations at the time, the women's primary role in society was to raise children and tend to the household. Women were expected to dress far more modestly than men; female figures are almost always portrayed as draped from head to feet, with the arms sometimes covered as well. Although they rarely had political power, women took part in community affairs and had some voice in popular civic assembles.<ref>Sanford Holst, ''Phoenician Secrets,'' Santorini Books (2011), p. 44.</ref> At least one woman, Unmiashtart, is recorded to have ruled Sidon in the fifth century B.C.<ref name=\":0\" /> The two most famous Phoenician women are [[Jezebel|Jezebe]]<nowiki/>l, portrayed the Bible as the assertive princess of Sidon, and [[Dido]], the semi-legendary founder and first queen of Carthage.\n\n== Religion ==\n{{Main|Canaanite religion}}\n{{See also|Sanchuniathon}}\n\nThe religious practices and beliefs of Phoenicia were cognate generally to their neighbours in [[Canaanite religion|Canaan]], which in turn shared characteristics common throughout the [[Ancient Semitic religions|ancient Semitic world]].{{sfnp|Moscati|1957|loc=e.g., p. 40 & 113}}<ref>[[William Robertson Smith|W. Robertson Smith]], ''Lectures on the Religion of the Semites'' (Edinburgh: A. & C. Black 1889; 2d ed. 1894; 3d ed. 1927); reprint by Meridian Library, New York, 1956, at 1\u201315.</ref><ref>Cf. Julian Baldick, who posits an even greater and more ancient sweep of a common religious culture in his ''Black God. [[Afro-Asiatic|Afroasiatic]] roots of Jewish, Christian, and Muslim religions'' (London: Tauris 1998).</ref> \"Canaanite religion was more of a public institution than of an individual experience.\" Its rites were primarily for city-state purposes; payment of taxes by citizens was considered in the category of religious sacrifices.{{sfnp|Gaster|1965|pp=113\u2013143, 114\u20135}} Unfortunately, many of the Phoenician sacred writings known to the ancients have been lost.{{sfnp|Harden|1962|pp=83\u20134}}<ref>Much of what is now known about Canaanite religion comes from one source: cuneiform tablets found in 1928 at temple ruins of Ras Shamra (ancient [[Ugarit]]). {{harvp|Gaster|1965|pp=113\u2013143, 114\u20135}}.</ref>\n\nPhoenician society was devoted to the state Canaanite religion.{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 173 (\"Canaanite Religion\")}}<ref>Dmitri Baramki, ''Phoenicia and the Phoenicians'' (Beirut: Khayats 1961) at 55\u201358.</ref>{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|pp=115\u2013142}} Several of its reported practices have been mentioned by scholars, such as [[temple prostitution]],{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=pp. 512\u2013513 (\"Sacred Prostitution\")}} and [[child sacrifice]].{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 448 (\"Molech\")}} \"Tophets\", built \"to burn their sons and their daughters in the fire\", are condemned by Yahweh in the Hebrew bible, particularly in ''[[Jeremiah]]'' 7:30\u201332, and in ''[[Books of Kings|2nd Kings]]'' 23:10 (also 17:17). Notwithstanding these and other important differences, cultural religious similarities between the ancient Hebrews and the Phoenicians persisted.{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 173 (\"Canaanite Religion\")}}<ref>E.g., like the early Hebrews, in Carthage little importance was attached to the idea of life after death. {{harvp|Warmington|1964|p=162}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Baal Ugarit Louvre AO17330.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Figure of [[Ba'al]] with raised arm, 14th\u201312th century BC, found at ancient [[Ugarit]] (''Ras Shamra'' site), a city at the far north of the Phoenician coast.<br /> [[Louvre|Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]]]]\n\n[[Canaanite religion|Canaanite religious mythology]] does not appear as elaborated compared with existent literature of their cousin Semites in Mesopotamia. In Canaan the supreme god was called [[El (god)|El]] (\ud802\udd00\ud802\udd0b, \"god\").{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 258 (\"El\")}}<ref>Cf. {{harvp|Cross|1973|loc=pp. 10\u201375, i.e., \"'El and the God of the Fathers\" (13\u201343), \"Yahweh and 'El\" (44\u201375); and pp. 177\u2013186, i.e., \"'El's modes of revelation\" in \"Yahweh and Ba'l\" (147\u2013194)}}</ref> The son of El was [[Baal]] (\ud802\udd01\ud802\udd0f\ud802\udd0b, \"master\", \"lord\"), a powerful [[Dying-and-rising deity|dying-and-rising]] [[storm god]].<ref>Here, Baal was used instead of the storm god's name [[Hadad]]. {{harvp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 315 (\"Hadad\"), p. 28 (\"Adad \u2013 Mesopotamia\"), p. 124 (\"Baal\").}}</ref> Other gods were called by royal titles, as in [[Melqart]] meaning \"king of the city\",{{sfnp|Moscati|1957|pp=113\u20134}} or [[Adonis]] for \"lord\".{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=pp. 29\u201330 (\"Adonis\")}} (Such epithets may often have been merely local titles for the same deities.) On the other hand, the Phoenicians, notorious for being secretive in business, might use these nondescript words as cover for the secluded name of the god,{{sfnp|Warmington|1964|loc=p. 156 (as an epithet to hide a god's real name)}} known only to a select few initiated into the inmost circle, or not even used by them, much as their neighbors and close relatives the ancient [[Israelites]]/[[Judea]]ns sometimes used the honorific [[Adonai]] ([[Hebrew language|Heb]]: \"My Lord\") in place of the [[tetragrammaton]]\u2014a practice which became standard (if not mandatory) in the [[Second Temple period]] onward.{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 655 (\"[[Yahweh|YHVH]]\"), p. 173 (\"Canaanite Religion\")}}\n\nThe Semitic pantheon was well-populated; which god became primary evidently depended on the exigencies of a particular city-state or tribal locale.<ref>In Phoenicia and Canaan: the rejuvenating [[Melqart]] was the chief god of Tyre, [[Eshmun]] the god of healing at [[Sidon]], [[Dagon]] (his son was [[Baal]]) at [[Ashdod]], Terah the moon god of the [[Zebulun]]. In Mesopotamia: the moon god at [[Ur]] was called [[Sin (god)|Sin]] ([[Sumerian language|Sum]]: Nanna), the sun god [[Shamash]] at [[Larsa]], the fertility goddess of [[Uruk]] being [[Ishtar]], and the great god of [[Babylon]] being [[Marduk]]. {{harvp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 173 (\"Canaanite Religion\"), p. 501 (\"Phoenician Religion\")}}</ref><ref>Carlyon, Richard. ''A Guide to the Gods'' (New York 1981) pp. 311, 315, 320, 324, 326, 329, 332\u20133.</ref> Due perhaps to the leading role of the city-state of Tyre, its reigning god [[Melqart]] was prominent throughout Phoenicia and overseas. Also of great general interest was [[Astarte]] (\ud802\udd00\ud802\udd14\ud802\udd15\ud802\udd13\ud802\udd15)\u2014a form of the [[Babylonian religion|Babylonian]] [[Ishtar]]\u2014a fertility goddess who also enjoyed regal and matronly aspects. The prominent deity [[Eshmun]] of [[Sidon]] was a healing god, seemingly cognate with deities such as Adonis (possibly a local variant of the same) and [[Attis]]. Associated with the fertility and harvest myth widespread in the region, in this regard Eshmun was linked with Astarte; other like pairings included Ishtar and [[Tammuz (deity)|Tammuz]] in Babylon, and [[Isis]] and [[Osiris]] in Egypt.{{sfnp|Harden|1962|pp=85\u20138}}\n\nReligious institutions of great antiquity in [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], called ''{{lang|phn|marzeh}}'' (\ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd13\ud802\udd06\ud802\udd04, \"place of reunion\"), did much to foster social bonding and \"kin\" loyalty.<ref>Kinship status was not infrequently granted to genetically unrelated persons. Cf., Meyer Fortes, ''Kinship and the Social Order. The Legacy of Lewis Henry Morgan'' (Chicago: Aldine 1969) at 256.</ref> These institutions held banquets for their membership on festival days. Various ''{{lang|phn|marzeh}}'' societies developed into elite [[fraternity|fraternities]], becoming very influential in the commercial trade and governance of Tyre. As now understood, each ''{{lang|phn|marzeh}}'' originated in the congeniality inspired and then nurtured by a series of ritual meals, shared together as trusted \"kin\", all held in honor of the deified ancestors.<ref>{{harvp|Markoe|2000|p=120}}, (''{{lang|phn|MRZH}}'', ''{{lang|phn|marzeh}}'').</ref> Later, at the Punic city-state of Carthage, the \"citizen body was divided into groups which met at times for common feasts.\" Such festival groups may also have composed the voting cohort for selecting members of the city-state's [[History of Punic era Tunisia#Constitution of State|Assembly]].{{sfnp|Warmington|1964|p=148}}<ref>Cf., [[William Robertson Smith]], ''Lectures on The Religion of the Semites. Second and Third Series.'' {1890\u20131891} (Sheffield Academic Press 1995), \"Feasts\" at 33\u201343.</ref>\n\n[[Religion in Carthage]] was based on inherited Phoenician ways of devotion. In fact, until its fall embassies from Carthage would regularly make the journey to Tyre to worship [[Melqart]], bringing material offerings.{{sfnp|Lancel|1995|p=193}}<ref>Similarly, [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora]] Jews also sent material support for the second Temple in Jerusalem until its fall in 70 CE. Cf., Allen C. Myers, editor, ''The Eerdmans Bible Dictionary'' (Grand Rapids, Michigan: Eerdmans 1987), \"Temple\" at 989\u2013992, 991.</ref> Transplanted to distant Carthage, these Phoenician ways persisted, but naturally acquired distinctive traits: perhaps influenced by a spiritual and cultural evolution, or synthesizing [[Early History of Tunisia#Ancient Berber religion|Berber tribal practices]], or transforming under the stress of political and economic forces encountered by the city-state. Over time the original Phoenician exemplar developed distinctly, becoming the ''Punic religion'' at Carthage.{{sfnp|Charles-Picard|Picard|1968|p=45}} \"The Carthaginians were notorious in antiquity for the intensity of their religious beliefs.\"{{sfnp|Warmington|1964|p=155}} \"Besides their reputation as merchants, the Carthaginians were known in the ancient world for their superstition and intense religiosity. They imagined themselves living in a world inhabited by supernatural powers which were mostly malevolent. For protection they carried [[amulets]] of various origins and had them buried with them when they died.\"<ref name=\"Abun-Nasr, 1971\">Abun-Nasr, ''A History of the Maghrib'' (1971) at 22.</ref>\n\nAt Carthage, as at [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], religion was integral to the city's life. A committee of ten elders selected by the civil authorities regulated worship and built the temples with public funds. Some priesthoods were hereditary to certain families. Punic inscriptions list a hierarchy of ''cohen'' (priest) and ''rab cohenim'' (lord priests). Each temple was under the supervision of its chief priest or priestess. To enter the Temple of [[Eshmun]] one had to abstain from sexual intercourse for three days, and from eating beans and pork.{{sfnp|Warmington|1964|loc=p. 161 (ten elders, priesthood, Temple of Eshmun)}} Private citizens also nurtured their own destiny, as evidenced by the common use of theophoric personal names, e.g., Hasdrubal, \"he who has Baal's help\" and Hamilcar [Abdelmelqart], \"pledged to the service of Melqart\".{{sfnp|Lancel|1995|pp=193\u20134}}\n\nThe city's [[History of Carthage#Founding of Carthage|legendary founder]], Elissa or [[Dido (Queen of Carthage)|Dido]], was the widow of Acharbas the high priest of Tyre in service to its principal deity [[Melqart]].{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|pp=129\u2013130}} Dido was also attached to the fertility goddess [[Astarte]]. With her Dido brought not only ritual implements for the worship of Astarte, but also her priests and sacred prostitutes (taken from Cyprus).{{sfnp|Warmington|1964|p=157}} The agricultural turned healing god [[Eshmun]] was worshipped at Carthage, as were other deities. Melqart became supplanted at the Punic city-state by the emergent god [[Baal Hammon]], which perhaps means \"lord of the altars of incense\" (thought to be an epithet to cloak the god's real name).{{sfnp|Charles-Picard|Picard|1968|p=45}}<ref>{{harvp|Warmington|1964|pp=155\u20138}}. Warmington associates Melqart with the pan-Semitic father god El. Regarding Baal Hammon, \"the epithet [was] being used to avoid naming the name of the god\" (p. 156).</ref> Later, another newly arisen deity arose eventually to reign supreme at Carthage, a goddess of agriculture and generation who manifested a regal majesty, [[Tanit]].{{sfnp|Lancel|1995|pp=199\u2013204}}\n[[File:Incense burner depicting Baal-Hammon AvL.JPG|thumb|upright=0.7|An [[incense]] burner depicting Ba'al-Hamon, 2nd century BC]]\nThe name [[Baal Hammon]] (\ud802\udd01\ud802\udd0f\ud802\udd0b \ud802\udd07\ud802\udd0c\ud802\udd0d) has attracted scholarly interest, with most scholars viewing it as a probable derivation from the [[Northwest Semitic languages|Northwest Semitic]] ''\u1e25amm\u0101n'' (\"[[brazier]]\"), suggesting the meaning \"Lord of the Brazier\". This may be supported by incense burners and braziers found depicting the god. Frank Moore Cross argued for a connection to ''Ham\u014dn'', the [[Ugaritic language|Ugaritic]] name for Mt. Amanus, an ancient name for the [[Nur Mountains|Nur Mountain range]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-eOycxXAoHMC&vq=Ugaritic|title=Canaanite Myth and Hebrew Epic|last1=Cross|first1=Frank Moore|date=1973|publisher=Harvard University Press|pages=26\u201328|accessdate=19 January 2017|isbn=9780674091764}}</ref> Modern scholars at first associated Baal Hammon with the Egyptian god [[Amun|Ammon]] of [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]], both the Punic and the Egyptian being gods of the sun. Both also had the ram as a symbol. The Egyptian Ammon was known to have spread by trade routes to Libyans in the vicinity of modern Tunisia, well before arrival of the Phoenicians. Yet Baal Hammon's derivation from Ammon is no longer considered the most likely, as Baal Hammon has since been traced to Syrio-Phoenician origins, confirmed by recent finds at [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]].<ref>{{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=195\u20136}}, entertains other etymologies for BL HMN. If instead of HMN, one reads HM-N it would signify \"protector\". One author finds his origin in the name of a mountain to the north of Phoenicia, ''Amanus''. Or the name may signify a small chapel, related to continuity, hence safety. Cf. {{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=194\u20139}}.</ref> Baal Hammon is also presented as a god of agriculture: \"Baal Hammon's power over the land and its fertility rendered him of great appeal to the inhabitants of Tunisia, a land of fertile wheat- and fruit-bearing plains.\"<ref>{{harvp|Markoe|2000|p=130}}. Markoe understands Baal Hammon as similar to [[Dagon]], i.e., an agricultural god.</ref><ref>Cf., {{harvp|Harden|1962|loc=Plate 41, \"Stele of Baal enthroned from [[Hadrumetum]]\" ([[Sousse]], Tunisia)}}. Said by {{harvp|Markoe|2000}} to represent Baal Hammon.</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=\"In Semitic religion El, the father of the gods, had gradually been shorn of his power by his sons and relegated to a remote part of his heavenly home; in Carthage, on the other hand, he became, once more, the head of the pantheon, under the enigmatic title of Ba'al Hammon.\"|author={{harvp|Charles-Picard|Picard|1968|p=45}}}}\n\n[[File:Tunisise Carthage Tophet Salambo 03.JPG|thumb|upright=0.9|Tophet funerary [[stele]], showing (below moon and sun) a symbol of Tanit, queen goddess of Carthage]]\n\nPrayers of individual Carthaginians were often addressed to Baal Hammon. Offerings to Hammon also evidently included [[child sacrifice]].<ref>{{harvp|Soren|Khader|Slim|1990}} in their chapter \"The Precinct of Death\" (123\u201346), discuss rather thoroughly child sacrifice at Carthage. They present archaeological findings (125\u20136, 131\u20139), and cite the works of a dozen ancient authors (126\u201330), to substantiate its macabre reality. The authors also try to understand it from the perspective of its ancient practitioners (130\u20131, 142\u20135). They review (139\u201341) the few modern critics who question whether in fact the evidence is being misconstrued (e.g., the children died of other causes) although the authors appear to find these counter-arguments not convincing enough to refute all the ancient charges and modern archaeology.</ref><ref>{{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=251\u20136}}, also reviews such counter-arguments that, regarding the bones of small children found in the ashes of funerary furnaces, they were already dead when placed in the flames.</ref><ref>Child sacrifice was offered to Tanit as well as Baal Hammon. {{harvp|Soren|Khader|Slim|1990|pp=63, 123}}.</ref> [[Diodorus]] (late 1st century BC) wrote that when [[Agathocles]] had attacked Carthage (in 310) several hundred children of leading families were sacrificed to regain the god's favour.<ref>Diodorus Siculus, ''Bibliothecae Historicae'' at XX, 14, 4, as cited in {{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=197, 249}}.</ref> In modern times, the French novelist [[Gustave Flaubert]]'s 1862 work ''[[Salammb\u00f4 (novel)|Salammb\u00f4]]'' graphically featured this god as accepting such sacrifice.<ref>{{harvp|Lancel|1995|p=197}}. The novel inspired several [[Salammb\u00f4|operas]].</ref>\n\n[[File:Tanit-Symbol.svg|thumb|upright=0.35|left|Sign of [[Tanit]], one of several variations.<ref>On the symbol of Tanit, cf. {{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=201\u20134}}. Her symbol may be related to the Egyptian symbol of life, the [[ankh]]. Lancel (pp. 201\u20132), citing {{Cite book |last=Bisi |first=Anna Maria |authorlink= Anna Maria Bisi |chapter=Simboli animati nella religione fenicio-punica |editor-last=Lanternari |editor-first=Vittorio |year=1982 |title=Religioni e Civilt\u00e0 |location=Bari |publisher=Dedalo |volume=3 |pp=62\u201365 |isbn=978-882202203-5 |language=it |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=QlPu8Gry1X4C&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=Simboli+animati+nella+religione+fenicio-punica#v=onepage&q=Simboli%20animati%20nella%20religione%20fenicio-punica&f=false}}</ref>]]\n\nThe goddess [[Tanit]] during the 5th and 4th centuries became queen goddess, supreme over the city-state of Carthage, thus outshining the former chief god and her associate, Baal-Hammon.<ref>In early inscriptions her name followed that of Baal Hammon. Then her title became ''TNT PN B'L'' or ''Tanit Pene Baal'' (\"Tanit face of Baal\"), and she was named before Baal Hammon on ex-votos found in the [[Tophet]] of Carthage. Lastly, she alone is indicated. {{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=199\u2013200}}.</ref><ref>\"Tanit face of Baal\" signifies Tanit as the presence of the god Baal. A similar epithet occurs in Hebrew religion, e.g., where ML'K PNYW signifies the \"[[angel of the presence]]\" in [[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 33: 14, and in [[Isaiah]] 63: 9. {{harvp|Cross|1973|loc=p. 30 n102}}.</ref> Tanit was represented by \"palm trees weighed down with dates, ripe pomegranates ready to burst, lotus or lilies coming into flower, fish, doves, frogs... .\" She gave to mankind a flow of vital energies.{{sfnp|Charles-Picard|Picard|1968|p=153}}<ref>[[Erich Neumann (psychologist)|Neumann, Erich]], ''Die Gross Mutter: Eine ph\u00e4nomenologie der weiblichen gestaltungen des unbewussten'' (Z\u00fcrich: Rhein Verlag 1956), translated by [[Ralph Mannheim]] as ''The Great Mother. An Analysis of the [[Jungian archetypes|Archetype]]'' (Princeton University: Bollingen 1955, 2d ed. 1963) at 311, describes a relief of Tanith carved on a stone stelae (Plate 157b):<blockquote>\"Thus the winged figure of Tanith, the Carthaginian goddess of heaven, standing beneath the vault of heaven and the zodiac, holds the sun and moon in her hands, and is [flanked] by pillars, the symbols of the Great Mother Goddess. But on the lower plane of the stele, we find the same goddess stylized with upraised arms, possibly as a tree assimilated to the Egyptian life symbol. Her head is the sun, an illusion to the tree birth of the sun, and she is accompanied by two doves, the typical bird of the Great Goddess.\" The \"Egyptian life symbol\" refers to the [[ankh]].</blockquote></ref> Tanit may be [[Early History of Tunisia#Ancient Berber religion|Berbero-Libyan]] in origin, or at least assimilated to a local deity.{{sfnp|Warmington|1964|pp=156\u20137}}<ref>{{harvp|Barton|1934|pp=304\u20136}}: <blockquote>\"It seems probable, therefore, that Tanith was a pre-Phoenician goddess of fertility of the [[Hamitic|Hamites]], ...that she was so popular that after the coming of the Phoenicians they too worshipped her to such a degree that she largely displaced their native goddess Astart.\"{{harvp|Barton|1934|p=305}}</blockquote> Here the [[Early History of Tunisia#Berber background|ancient Berbers]] were the [[Early History of Tunisia#Berber language history|local Hamitic people]].</ref>\n\nAnother view, supported by recent finds, holds that Tanit originated in Phoenicia, being closely linked there to the goddess [[Astarte]].{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|pp=118, 130}}<ref>{{harvp|Lancel|1995|p=200}}: seventh century inscription at [[Sarepta]] mentions TNT-'STRT, i.e., Tanit-Astarte.</ref> Tanit and Astarte: each one was both a [[funerary]] and a [[fertility]] goddess. Each was a [[sea goddess]]. As Tanit was associated with Ba'al Hammon the principal god in Punic Carthage, so Astarte was with [[El (god)|El]] in Phoenicia. Yet Tanit was clearly distinguished from Astarte. Astarte's heavenly emblem was the planet Venus, Tanit's the crescent moon. Tanit was portrayed as chaste; at Carthage religious prostitution was apparently not practiced.<ref>There is some evidence contra: late Punic sacerdotal officials were called ''MTRH'' (\"bridegroom\"), indicating the male role in a \"sacred marriage\" to promote fertility, the \"brides\" of this seasonal rite being females of the temple; the Hebrew prophet [[Hosea]] condemned such rites as \"prostitution\". {{harvp|Gaster|1965|pp=113\u2013143, 132}}.</ref><ref>Warmington doubts that temple prostitution was \"a feature of Carthaginian religion.\" {{harvp|Warmington|1964|p=157}}.</ref> Yet temple prostitution played an important role in Astarte's cult at Phoenicia. Also, the Greeks and Romans did not compare Tanit to the Greek [[Aphrodite]] nor to the Roman [[Venus (goddess)|Venus]] as they would Astarte. Rather the comparison of Tanit would be to [[Hera]] and to [[Juno (mythology)|Juno]], regal goddesses of marriage, or to the goddess [[Artemis]] of child-birth and the hunt.<ref>{{harvp|Charles-Picard|Picard|1968|p=152}}, regarding the comparison of Astarte and Tanit.</ref> [[Tertullian]] (c. 160 \u2013 c.220), the Christian theologian and native of Carthage, wrote comparing Tanit to [[Ceres (Roman mythology)|Ceres]], the Roman mother goddess of agriculture.<ref>{{harvp|Barton|1934|pp=306, 306n5}}. Ceres is often identified with the Greek goddess [[Demeter]] (whose name signifies \"earth mother\").</ref>\n\nTanit has also been identified with three different Canaanite goddesses (all being sisters/wives of [['El|El]]): the above '[[Astarte]]; the virgin war goddess '[[Anat]]; and the mother goddess 'Elat or [[Asherah]].<ref>{{harvp|Cross|1973|pp=28\u201335}}, 'Astarte (29\u201330), 'Anat (31), and 'Elat (31\u201335).</ref><ref>{{harvp|Patai|1990}} describes the goddess 'Anat, and the goddess 'Elat or Asherah:<blockquote>\"In [[Ugarit]]ic mythology, Anath is by far the most important female figure, the goddess of love and war, virginal yet wanton, amorous yet given to uncontrollable outbursts of rage and appalling acts of cruelty. She is the daughter of El, the god of heaven, and of his wife the Lady Asherah of the Sea. ... Her foremost lover was her brother [[Hadad|Baal]]. ... She was easily provoked to violence and, once she began to fight, would go berserk, smiting and killing left and right.\" (60\u20132), who adds that the Phoenician [[Philo of Byblos]] (64\u2013141) compared Anath to the Greek virgin war goddess [[Athena]]. Also, Patai at 63\u20136 identifies Anath with the biblical \"Queen of Heaven\". At 61 Patai, referring to Anath in her r\u00f4le as goddess of love, mentions the Babylonian goddess [[Ishtar]], and remarks that both Astarte and Anath as \"typical goddesses of love, both chaste and promiscuous... [were] perennially fruitful without ever losing their virginity.\"</blockquote><blockquote>\"Asherah was the chief goddess of the Canaanite pantheon... at Ugarit... . ...Asherah figured prominently as the wife of El the chief god. Her full name was 'Lady Asherah of the Sea'--apparently her domain proper was the sea, just as that of her husband El was heaven. She was, however, also referred to simply as Elath or Goddess. She was the 'Progenitress of the Gods': all other gods... were her children... . Asherah was a motherly goddess... .\" {{harvp|Patai|1990|pp=36\u20137}}. In his chapter \"The Goddess Asherah\" (34\u201353), Patai discusses widespread Hebrew worship of Asherah until the 6th century B.C.E. Patai (52\u20133) notes ancient inscriptions (one found near [[Hebron]]) evidencing an early Jewish association of Asherah with Yahweh, a view repugnant to later orthodox Judaism.</blockquote></ref>{{sfnp|Brandon|1970|loc=p. 76 (\"Anat\"), p. 107 (\"Asherah\" and \"Ashtart\")}} With her being a goddess, or symbolizing a psychic [[Archetype#Jungian archetypes|archetype]], accordingly it is difficult to assign a single nature to Tanit, or clearly to represent her to consciousness.<ref>{{harvp|Jung|1969|pp=3\u201341, 23}}: modern psychology understands \"the gods as psychic factors, that is, as archetypes\"; pp. 151\u201381, 160\u20131, (''The Psychology of the Child Archetype'' \u2013 1940): <blockquote>It is an \"illusion that an archetype can be finally explained and disposed of. Even the best attempts at explanation are only more or less successful translations into another metaphorical language. ... The most we can do is ''dream the myth onwards'' and give it a modern dress. And whatever [our] explanation or interpretation does to it, we do to our souls as well, with corresponding results for our own well being. ... Hence the \"explanation\" should always be such that the functional significance of the archetype remains unimpaired, so that an adequate and meaningful connection between the conscious mind and the archetype is assured. ... It represents or personifies certain instinctive data of the dark, primitive psyche, the real but invisible roots of consciousness.\" ... \"The archetype... is a psychic organ present in all of us. ... There is no 'rational' substitute for the archetype any more than there is for the cerebellum or the kidneys.\"</blockquote></ref>\n\nA problematic theory derived from [[sociology of religion]] proposes that as Carthage passed from being a Phoenician trading station into a wealthy and sovereign city-state, and from a monarchy anchored to Tyre into a native-born ''Libyphoenician'' oligarchy, Carthaginians began to turn away from deities associated with Phoenicia, and slowly to discover or synthesize a Punic deity, the goddess Tanit.<ref>Compare {{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=202\u20133}}.</ref> A parallel theory posits that when Carthage acquired as a source of wealth substantial agricultural lands in Africa, a local fertility goddess, Tanit, developed or evolved eventually to become supreme.<ref name=\"Abun-Nasr, 1971\"/> A basis for such theories may well be the religious reform movement that emerged and prevailed at Carthage during the years 397-360. The catalyst for such dramatic change in Punic religious practice was their recent defeat in war when led by their king Himilco (d. 396) against the Greeks of Sicily.<ref>{{harvp|Lancel|1995|p=114}}: Himilco's acts of sacrilege and his subsequent military defeat in Sicily, later his penance and suicide at Carthage; thereafter, introduction to Carthage of Greek goddesses Demeter and Kore.</ref>\n\nSuch transformation of religion would have been instigated by a faction of wealthy land owners at Carthage, including these reforms: overthrow of the monarchy; elevation of Tanit as queen goddess and decline of Baal Hammon; allowance of foreign cults of Greek origin into the city ([[Demeter]] and [[Persephone|Kore]]); decline in child sacrifice, with most votive victims changed to small animals, and with the sacrifice not directed for state purposes but, when infrequently done, performed to solicit the deity for private, family favors. This bold historical interpretation understands the reformer's motivation as \"the reaction of a wealthy and cultured upper class against the primitive and antiquated aspects of the Canaanite religion, and also a political move intended to break the power of a monarchy which ruled by divine authority.\" The reform's popularity was precarious at first. Later, when the city was in danger of imminent attack in 310, there would be a marked regression to child sacrifice. Yet eventually the cosmopolitan religious reform and the popular worship of Tanit together contributed to \"breaking through the wall of isolation which had surrounded Carthage.\"{{sfnp|Charles-Picard|Picard|1968|pp=146\u201354}}<ref>{{harvp|Lancel|1995|pp=202\u20133}}, shows his criticism of the theory that Tanit was adopted in Carthage when it passed from monarchy to oligarchy.</ref><ref>Giovanni Garbini, \"Continuit\u00e0 ed innovazioni nella religione fenicia\" in ''Atti del colloquio in Roma: la religione fenicia'' (Roma 1981) pp 34\u20136. Cited by {{harvp|Lancel|1995|p=203}}, as advancing the theory of religious change re Tanit.</ref>\n\n\"When the Romans conquered Africa, Carthaginian religion was deeply entrenched even in Libyan areas, and it retained a great deal of its character under different forms.\" Tanit became [[Juno (mythology)|Juno]] Caelestis, \"and Caelestis was supreme at Carthage itself until the triumph of Christianity, just as Tanit had been in pre-Roman times.\" {{sfnp|Warmington|1964|pp=156\u20137}} Regarding Berber (Libyan) [[Early History of Tunisia#Ancient Berber religion|religious beliefs]], it has also been said:\n\n{{Quote|text=\"[Berber] belief in the powers of the spirits of the ancestors was not eclipsed by the introduction of new gods\u2014Hammon, or Tanit\u2014but existed in parallel with them. It is this same duality, or readiness to adopt new cultural forms while retaining the old on a more intimate level, which characterizes the [Roman era].\"<ref>{{cite book |author1=Brett, Michael |author2=Fentress, Elizabeth |year=1997 |title=The Berbers |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |p=49}}</ref>}}\n\nSuch Berber ambivalence, the ability to entertain multiple mysteries concurrently, apparently characterized their religion during the Punic era also. After the passing of Punic power, the great Berber king [[Masinissa]] (r. 202\u2013148), who long fought and challenged Carthage, was widely venerated by later generations of Berbers as divine.<ref>[[Theodor Mommsen]], ''R\u00f6mische Geschichte, band 5'' (Leipzig 1885, 5th ed. 1904), translated as ''The Provinces of the Roman Empire'' (London 1886, 1909; reprint Barnes & Noble 1996) at 305, citing the ancient Christian authors [[Cyprian]] and [[Tertullian]].</ref>\n\n=== Deities ===\n\n==== Attested 1st millennium BC ====\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Adonis]]\n* [[Kothar-wa-Khasis|Chusor]]\n* [[Dagon]]\n* [[Eshmun]]-[[Melqart]]\n* Gebory-Kon <small>(Gebory = ''gabri''? Kon = [[Biblical names of stars#Planets|Chiun/Kiyun/Kaiwan/Saturn]]?)</small>\n* [[Melqart]]\n* [[Melqart|Milkashtart]]\n* [[Resheph|Reshef-Shed]]\n* [[Shed (deity)|Shed-Horon]]\n* [[Tanit]]-[[Astarte]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==== Attested 2nd millennium BC ====\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Amen ([[Amun]])\n* [[Asherah]]\n* [[Astarte]]\n* [[Baalat Gebal]] (\"Lady of Byblos\")\n* [[Baalshamin|Baal Shemen]]\n* [[El (deity)|El]]\n* [[Eshmun]]\n* [[Hadad]] (Baal Saphon, the Biblical [[Baal]])\n* Hail{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n* [[Europa (consort of Zeus)|Europa consort of Zeus]]\n* [[Isis]]\n* [[Osiris]]\n* [[Shed (deity)|Shed]]\n* Venerable [[Reshef]] (Reshef of the Arrow)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Foreign relations ==\nPhoenicia's location in the Levant meant it was uniquely positioned between the three early cradles of civilization: Greece, Egypt, and Mesopotamia. Combined with their mastery of seafaring and largely peaceful pursuit of trade, the various Phoenician city-states generally maintained good relations with the many peoples they countered across the Mediterranean. Foreign relations were almost always driven by commercial interests, though this did not preclude the exchange of ideas, culture, science, and technology. To facilitate trade, Phoenician merchants would establish long-lasting relationships with the societies they dealt with, which further solidified diplomatic and cultural relations.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Influence in the Mediterranean region ===\n[[File:Kadmos dragon Louvre E707.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|right|[[Cadmus]] fighting the dragon. Side A of a black-figured [[amphora]] from [[Eub\u0153a]], c. 560 \u2013 550&nbsp;BC, [[Louvre]]]]\nPhoenician culture had a major effect on the cultures of the Mediterranean basin in the early Iron Age, and had been affected by them in turn. In the Phoenician religiob, the tripartite division between [[Baal]], [[Mot (Semitic god)|Mot]] and [[Yam (god)|Yam]] seems to have influenced the Greek division between [[Zeus]], [[Hades]] and [[Poseidon]].<ref name=\"Smith1994\">{{cite book|author=Mark S. Smith|title=The Ugaritic Baal Cycle: Volume I, Introduction with text, translation and commentary of KTU 1.1\u20131.2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlfx4YwtaVkC&pg=PA94|year=1994|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-09995-1|page=94}}</ref> The [[Tartessos]] region probably embraced the whole southern part of the Iberian Peninsula.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Straub|first1=3.2.11|title=TARTESSOS, SW Spain|date=1976|publisher=The Princeton Encyclopedia of Classical Sites|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0006:entry=tartessos|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref> In various Mediterranean ports during the classical period, Phoenician temples sacred to [[Melkart]] were recognized as sacred to the Greek [[Hercules|Herakles]]. Stories like the [[Rape of Europa]] and the coming of [[Cadmus]] also draw upon Phoenician influence.\n\nThe recovery of the Mediterranean economy after the late [[Bronze Age collapse]] ({{circa|1200 BC}}) seems to have been largely due to the work of Phoenician traders and merchant princes, who re-established long distance trade between Egypt and Mesopotamia in the 10th century BC.\n\nThere are many countries and cities around the Mediterranean region that derive their names from the Phoenician language.\n\n* [[Altiburus]], Algeria (southwest of Carthage) From Phoenician: ''{{lang|phn|Iltabrush}}''\n* [[Bosa]], Sardinia: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Bis'en}}''\n* [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Gadir}}''\n* [[Dhali, Cyprus|Dhali]] (Idalion), Cyprus: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Idyal}}''\n* [[Erice]], Sicily: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Eryx}}''\n* [[Malta]]: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Malat}}'' (\"refuge\")\n* [[Marion, Cyprus|Marion]],Cyprus: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Aymar}}''\n* [[Oued Dekri]], Algeria: From Phoenician: ''{{lang|phn|Idiqra}}''\n* Spain: From Phoenician: ''{{lang|phn|I-Shaphan}}'', meaning \"Land of [[Hyraxes]]\". Later Latinized as ''{{lang|la|[[Hispania]]}}''\n* [[Carthage]], Tunisia: From Phoenician ''{{lang|phn|Qart Hada\u0161t}}'' meaning \"New City\"\n* [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]], Spain (({{lang-el|\u039d\u03ad\u03b1 \u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b7\u03b4\u03cc\u03bd\u03b1}}; {{lang-la|Carthago Nova}}; {{lang-es|Cartagena}})) A colony of Carthage, which also gave rise to [[Cartagena, Colombia]]\n\nDue to their wide-ranging, centuries-long network across the Mediterranean, the Phoenicians are credited with laying the foundations for the economic, social, and cultural integration of the Mediterranean, as would be carried on by the Greeks and especially the Romans.<ref>Jerry H. Bentley, \u201cSea and Ocean Basins as Frameworks for Historical Analysis,\u201d Geographical Review 89 (1999): 215-219.</ref>\n\n=== Relations with the Greeks ===\nPhoenicia's ties with the Greeks appeared to have began with the Minoan civilization on Crete (1950-1450 B.C), which together with the later Mycenaean civiliazation, is considered the progenitor of classical Greece. [[Fernand Braudel]] identified Minoan Crete as a bridge between East and West, isolated from the \"[barbaric] Aegean world\" and thus forced to \"[look] towards Cyprus, Ugarit, and Byblos.\"<ref>Fernand Braudel, Memory and Mediterranean, trans. Sian Reynolds (New York: Alfred A. Knopf, (2001), 112-113.</ref> Archaeological research suggests that the Minoans gradually imported Near Eastern goods, artistic styles, and customs through the Phoenicians, who by the third millennium B.C. had become major sea traders and the bearers of Egyptian, Mesopotamian, and other Eastern cultures.\n\n==== Trade ====\n[[File:Cup Idalion Louvre N3455.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Bowl with mythological scenes, a [[sphinx]] [[frieze]] and the representation of a king vanquishing his enemies; Electrum, Cypro-Archaic I, 8th\u20137th centuries BC, from [[Idalion]], Cyprus.]]\nTowards the end of the Bronze Age (around 1200&nbsp;BC) there was trade between the Canaanites (early Phoenicians), Egypt, Cyprus, and Greece. In the Ulu Bulurun shipwreck found off the coast of Turkey, Canaanite storage pottery along with pottery from Cyprus and Greece was found. There are also Greek accounts of Phoenician traders arriving to port with \"trinkets and baubles.\"<ref name=\":42\">Glenn Markoe and Patrick E. McGovern, ''A NATION OF ARTISANS,'' Archaeology, Vol. 43, No. 2 (MARCH/APRIL 1990), p. 32. www.jstor.org/stable/41765806</ref> The Phoenicians were famous metalworkers, and by the end of the 8th century BC, Greek city-states were sending out envoys to the Levant (the eastern Mediterranean) for metal goods.<ref name=\"UPennMuseum\">{{cite web |year=1999 |title=Canaan and Ancient Palestine |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]]\n |url=http://www.penn.museum/sites/canaan/index.html }} See also [http://www.penn.museum/exhibitions/signature-galleries/canaan-and-israel-gallery Gallery].</ref>  \n\nThe height of Phoenician trade was circa the 7th and 8th centuries BC. There is a dispersal of imports (ceramic, stone, and faience) from the Levant that traces a Phoenician commercial channel to the Greek mainland via the central Aegean.{{r|UPennMuseum}} Athens shows little evidence of this trade with few eastern imports, but other Greek coastal cities are rich with eastern imports that evidence this trade.{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|p=174}}\n\nAl Mina, located in Syria, is emblematic of the trade that took place between the Greeks and the Phoenicians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Boardman |first1=John |authorlink=John Boardman (art historian) |year=1964 |title=The Greeks Overseas |location=London |publisher=Thames and Hudson |ref=harv }}</ref> It has been theorized that by the 8th century BC, Euboean traders established a commercial enterprise with the Levantine coast and were using Al Mina as a base for this enterprise. There is still some question about the veracity of these claims concerning Al Mina.{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|p=174}} The Phoenicians even got their name from the Greeks due to their trade: Their most famous trading product was purple dye, the Greek word for which is ''{{lang|grc-Latn|phoenos}}''.{{sfnp|Moscati|1965}}\n\n==== Alphabet ====\nThe Phoenician phonetic alphabet was adopted and modified by the Greeks probably in the 8th century BC (around the time of the ''{{lang|grc-Latn|hippoi}}'' depictions). This most likely did not come from a single instance but from a culmination of commercial exchange.{{sfnp|Moscati|1965}} This suggests a prior a relationship between the Greeks and the Phoenicians. Though there is no evidence to support the suggestion, it is probable that during this period there was also a passing of religious ideas.<ref>Scott B. Noegel, \"Greek Religion and the Ancient Near East, \" The Blackwell Companion to Greek Religion London: Blackwell, Daniel Ogden, ed. (2006), 21-37.</ref> The legendary Phoenician [[hero]] [[Cadmus]] is credited with bringing the alphabet to Greece, but it is more plausible that it was brought by Phoenician emigrants to [[Crete]],<ref>L.H.Jeffery. (1976).''The archaic Greece.The Greek city states 700\u2013500&nbsp;BC''.Ernest Benn Ltd&Tonnbridge.</ref> whence it gradually diffused northwards.\n\n==== Connections with Greek mythology ====\nSeveral prominent figures in Greek myths and legends are Phoenician. In both Phoenician and Greek mythologies, [[Cadmus]] is a Phoenician prince, the son of king Agenor of [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]. Herodotus credits Cadmus for bringing the Phoenician alphabet to Greece{{sfnp|Markoe|2000|p=112}} approximately sixteen hundred years before Herodotus' time, or around 2000 BC,{{sfn|Herodotus, The Histories|loc=[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126%3Abook%3D2%3Achapter%3D145%3Asection%3D4 II.145.4] }} as he attested:\n{{quote|text=These Phoenicians who came with Cadmus and of whom the Gephyraeans were a part brought with them to Hellas, among many other kinds of learning, the alphabet, which had been unknown before this, I think, to the Greeks. As time went on the sound and the form of the letters were changed.|author={{harvnb|Herodotus, The Histories|loc=[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126%3Abook%3D5%3Achapter%3D58%3Asection%3D1 V.58] }}}}\nIn addition to introducing the Greeks to the alphabet, Cadmus was the first Greek hero, and along with [[Perseus]] and [[Bellerophon]], the greatest hero before the days of [[Heracles]]. He is also the legendary founder of Thebes, one of the most powerful and influential of the classical Greek city-states. Europa, a consort of Zeus and mother of [[Basileus|King]] [[Minos]] of [[Crete]], is Phoenician, and is generally described as the daughter of King Agenor and thus the sister of Cadmus. They in turn have several other siblings that in some incarnations are related to Poseidon. The integration of Phoenician figures into Greek mythology, often in a heroic or privileged position, suggests some degree of Greek affinity towards Phoenicians.\n\nDue to the number of deities similar to the \"Lord of the Sea\" in classical mythology, there have been many difficulties attributing one specific name to the sea deity or the \"Poseidon\u2013Neptune\" figure of Phoenician religion. This figure of \"Poseidon-Neptune\" is mentioned by authors and in various inscriptions as being very important to merchants and sailors,<ref>{{cite book |last=Ribichini |first=S. |year=1988 |chapter=Beliefs and Religious Life |editor=Sabatino Moscati |title=The Phoenicians |pp=104\u201325 |location=Milan |publisher=Gruppo Editoriale Fabbri }}</ref> but a singular name has yet to be found. There are, however, names for sea gods from individual city-states. Yamm is the god of the sea of [[Ugarit]], an ancient city-state north to Phoenicia. Yamm and Baal, the storm god of Ugaritic myth and often associated with Zeus, have an epic battle for power over the universe. While Yamm is the god of the sea, he truly represents vast chaos.<ref>Habel, N.C. 1964. ''Yahweh Versus Baal: A Conflict of Religious Cultures''. New York: Bookman Associates</ref> Baal, on the other hand, is a representative for order. In Ugaritic myth, Baal overcomes Yamm's power, in some version killing him with a mace fashioned for him, while in others, the goddess Athtart saves Yamm and states he should should stay in his own province for being defeated. Yamm is the brother of the god of death, Mot.<ref>Ringgren, H. 1917. ''Religions of the Ancient Near East''. Philadelphia: The Westminster Press</ref> Some scholars have identified Yamm with Poseidon, although he has also been identified with [[Pontus (mythology)|Pontus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Baumgarten |first=A.I.|title=The Phoenician History of Philo of Byblos: A Commentary|year=1981|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-90-04-06369-3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BM8UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA207&dq=Poseidon+Phoenician+Yamm#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=207}}</ref>\n\n==== Greek accounts and attitudes ====\nIn his [[The Republic (Plato)|''Republic'']], Greek philosopher [[Plato]] contends that the love of money is a tendency of the soul found amongst Phoenicians and Egyptians, which distinguishes them from the Greeks who tend towards the love of knowledge.<ref>Plato, ''Republic'', IV (435e\u2013436a)</ref> In his ''Laws'', he asserts that this love of money has led the Phoenicians and Egyptians to develop skills in cunning and trickery ([[wikt:\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2|\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b1]]) rather than wisdom ({{lang|grc|[[wikt:\u03c3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1|\u03c3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1]]}}).<ref>Plato Laws V (747c)</ref>\n\nIn his ''Histories'', Herodotus gives the Persian and Greek accounts of a series of kidnappings that led to the Trojan War. While docked at a trading port in Argos, the Phoenicians [[Raptio|kidnapped]] a group of Greek women including King Idacus's daughter, Io. The Greeks then retaliated by kidnapping Europa, a Phoenician, and later Medea. The Greeks refused to compensate the Phoenicians for the additional abduction, a fact which Paris used a generation later to justify the abduction of [[Helen of Troy|Helen]] from [[Argos]]. The Greeks then retaliated by waging war against Troy. After Troy's fall the Persians considered the Greeks to be their enemy.{{sfn|Herodotus, The History|loc=[http://classics.mit.edu/Herodotus/history.1.i.html I.1.1\u20135] }}\n\n== Ancient sources ==\n\n=== In the Bible ===\nHiram (also spelled Huran), the king of Tyre, is associated with the building of [[Solomon's Temple|Solomon's temple]]. [[Books of Kings#Contents|1 Kings 5:1]] says: \"Hiram king of Tyre sent his servants to Solomon; for he had heard that they had anointed him king in the place of his father: for Hiram was ever a lover of David.\" [[2 Chronicles]] 2:14 says: \"The son of a woman of the daughters of Dan, and his father [was] a man of Tyre, skillful to work in gold, silver, brass, iron, stone, timber, royal purple (from the Murex), blue, and in crimson, and fine linens; also to grave any manner of graving, and to find out every device which shall be put to him&nbsp;...\"\n\nIn [[Masonic]] lore, [[Hiram Abiff]] is the architect of Solomon's temple and a central figure Masonic rituals and mythology. \n\nLater, reforming prophets railed against the practice of drawing royal wives from among foreigners: [[Elijah]] execrated [[Jezebel (biblical)|Jezebel]], the princess from [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in [[Lebanon|South Lebanon]] who became a consort of King [[Ahab]] and introduced the worship of her god Baal.\n\nLong after Phoenician culture flourished, or Phoenicia existed as a political entity, Hellenized natives of the region where Canaanites still lived were referred to as \"Syro-Phoenicians\", as in the [[Gospel of Mark]]: \"The woman was a Greek, a Syro-phoenician by birth\".<ref>7:26</ref>\n\nThe word ''[[Bible]]'' itself derives from Greek ''{{lang|grc|biblion}}'', which means \"book\" and either derives from, or is the (perhaps ultimately Egyptian) origin of ''[[Byblos]]'', the Greek name of the Phoenician city Gebal.<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=Bible&searchmode=none Online Etymology Dictionary, s.v. \"Bible\"]. Retrieved November 27, 2012.</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nDue to the paucity of written records from the Phoenicians themselves, their civilization was long overshadowed by those of neighboring Greece, Egypt, and Mesopotamia. Beginning in the early 1960s, new and reexamined discoveries by scholars and archaeologists have shed more light on the Phoenicians and their contributions and achievements. \nThe most widely known legacy was their development and transmission of an [[alphabet]] throughout the Mediterranean, which directly inspired the Greek alphabet that, in turn, influenced the Latin alphabet and numerous European languages thereafter. The Phoenician alphabet allowed for a simplified writing system that did not require a narrow caste of professional scribes, priests, and officials as in Egypt or Mesopotamia. It could be written on a variety of media and was easy to learn due to its fixed nature, allowing for easier communication across classes and cultures. In addition to facilitating commercial relations\u2014and thus leading to an exchange of goods and ideas that brought prosperity to different societies across the region\u2014it's been argued that the Phoenician alphabet's \"egalitarian\" nature proved pivotal to the progress of civilization as a whole.<blockquote>The alphabetical (like the numerical) system is how societies organize information. Beyond literacy and systematization, the alphabet stimulates both abstract and rational thought through the phonetic coding and decoding process. As a result, the adoption of Phoenician letters\u2014 especially in Ionia and Athens\u2014created an intellectual environment for the development of Greek, and, subsequently, Western science.<ref name=\":5\" /></blockquote>Anthropologist Ralph Linton argues that the Phoenician's \"main role in the development of the Greek and other Mediterranean cultures was as intermediaries between Asia and Europe.\"<ref>Ralph Linton, The Tree of Culture (New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 1956), 341.</ref> This was aided by Phoenicia's location at the crossroads of the major civilizations of the eastern Mediterranean and Western Asia. One of the few civilizations to emerge from the [[Bronze Age collapse|Late Bronze Age collapse]] relatively unscathed, the Phoenicians led the way in reopening trade routes that connected the Egyptian, Greek, and Mesopotamian civilizations. As the dominant seafarers and traders well into the Iron Age, the Phoenicians maintained an unparalleled commercial network that revitalized the region and contributed to the \"civilizational development of the Mediterranean basin.\" Historian [[Jerry H. Bentley]] argues that this Phoenician-led flourishing of maritime commerce also furthered the economic, social, and cultural integration of the Mediterranean, leading to unprecedented ties and exchanges between otherwise distinct civilizations. \n\nThe Greeks and Romans eventually emulated this Phoenician model, laying the foundation of the \"Mediterranean as a single economic, political, and cultural unit.\" [[Hans G. Niemeyer]], an expert in Iron Age Phoenicia, claims the Phoenicians \"sparked Western civilization\" through their \"transfusion of Eastern goods, technologies, and ideas that, in turn, became the foundations of Greco-Roman civilization.\" He also credits Phoenicia for the \"dissemination of urban civilization, in the propagation of technical innovations, in the distribution of new [aristocratic] lifestyle paradigms and \u2018modern\u2019 economics.\" The Phoenician mercantile system encouraged the division of labor and accumulation of wealth that allowed for state-building; the adoption of this model is credited for the development of states from Greece to Spain.<ref>Susan Sherratt and Andrew Sherratt, \u201cThe Growth of the Mediterranean Economy in the Early First Millennium BC,\u201d World Archeology 24 (1993): 367, 369.</ref>  These civilizations acknowledged the Phoenician's contributions.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn addition to various manufactured goods and resources, Phoenicians traders imparted the West with Mesopotamian astronomical and mathematical ideas and Egyptian architectural and artistic styles. The \"[[Orientalising period|Orientalising]]\" trend later seen in [[Greek art]] is attributed to the Phoenicians, whose own artistic tradition was an amalgamation of different cultures in the Mediterranean and Near East. The forerunner of [[Ionic order]] and [[Ashlar|ashlar masonry]], which remain staples of classical architecture throughout the West, was the Proto-Aeolic capital developed by Phoenicians. Similarly, Bronze Age Phoenicians developed [[lime mortar]] from which the Greeks created true cement and Romans produced concrete.<ref>Yigal Shiloh (1979). ''The Proto-Aeolic capital and Israelite ashlar masonry''. Institute of Archaeology, Hebrew University of Jerusalem</ref>\n\nHistorian of science [[Leonid Zhmud]] observes \"Semitic borrowings\" and \"Oriental influence\" with respect to the weights, measures, and mathematical calculations utilized by the Greeks. The abacus, which emerged in the fifth century B.C. and remained in widespread use until the late 18th century, likely reached Greece from Phoenicia\n\nPhoenician city-states may have developed \"proto-democratic\" political structures, such as councils of elders and popular assemblies, that possibly inspired democratic Greek city-states such as Athens.<ref name=\":5\">Scott, John C. (2018) ''The Phoenicians and the Formation of the Western World'', Comparative Civilizations Review: Vol. 78\u00a0: No. 78 , Article 4. <nowiki>https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/ccr/vol78/iss78/4</nowiki></ref> The classical Greek philosopher Aristotle also found similarities between Spartan and Carthaginian constitutions. Several scholars have claimed Punic / Phoenician influence in Sparta's political development.<ref>Stephen Stockwell, \u201cBefore Athens: Early Popular Government in Phoenician and Greek City States,\u201d Geopolitics, History, and International Relations 2 (2010): 123-133.</ref>\n\nAs the earliest known people to engage in expansive maritime trade and seafaring, the Phoenicians developed numerous naval and navigational innovations that were adopted by neighboring societies. The bireme, a multi-tiered oared vessel, was created some time in the eighth century B.C. and became common throughout the Mediterranean region, eventually being evolved by the Romans. As the first people to have explored beyond the [[Straits of Gibraltar]], and first to colonise the Western Mediterranean in any significant way, the Phoenicians inspired similar maritime ventures by the Greeks and Romans. Beginning the eighth century B.C., the Greek city-states of [[Euboea]] and Corinth led the movement towards colonization by learning shipbuilding, navigational techniques, and the east-west trade routes of the Phoenicians. Following contact by the Phoenicians with mainland Italy as in the tenth century B.C., the Etruscans and other Italian peoples learned the Phoenician methods of celestial navigation, weights and measures, and even finance that centuries later were received by the Romans.\n\nLong after the Phoenicians ceased to be an independent polity, their successors remained influential and aware of their Phoenician roots. [[Zeno of Citium]], the founder of [[Stoicism]], was possibly of Phoenician heritage.<ref>Diogenes La\u00ebrtius, vii. 3</ref> [[Roman Carthage]], an early epicenter of Christianity, produced some of the earliest and most influential Christian theologians, such as Tertullian and St. Augustine, who were of Punic / Phoenician heritage.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Maronites]]\n* [[Names of the Levant]]\n* [[Phoenicianism]]\n* [[Punic language]]\n* [[Punics]]\n* [[Tarout Island]]\n* [[Theory of Phoenician discovery of the Americas]]\n* [[Israelites]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Aubet |first=Maria Eugenia |year=2001 |title=The Phoenicians and the West: Politics, Colonies and Trade |translator-last = Turton |translator-first = Mary |publisher=Cambridge University Pres |isbn=978-0-521-79543-2 |ref=harv }} See [http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/2003/2003-12-17.html Review by Roger Wright], University of Liverpool.\n* {{cite book |last1=Barton |first1=George Aaron |author-link = George Aaron Barton |year=1934 |title = Semitic and Hamitic Origins. Social and Religious |url=https://archive.org/details/semitichamiticor00bart |location=Philadelphia |publisher=University of Pennsylvania |ref=harv }}\n* Bondi, S. F. 1988. \"The Course of History.\" In ''The Phoenicians'', edited by Sabatino Moscati, 38\u201345. Milan: Gruppo Editoriale Fabbri.\n* {{cite book |url = https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofcomp00bran/page/n5 |editor-last=Brandon |editor-first=S.G.F. |year=1970 |title = Dictionary of Comparative Religion |location=New York City |publisher=Charles Scribner\u2019s Son |ref=harv }}