{"title_page": "Yes, Madam", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{about||the 1939 British film|Yes, Madam?|the 1942 Italian film|Yes, Madam (1942 film)|the 2003 Indian Tamil film|Yes Madam (2003 film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Yes, Madam\n| image          = Yes-madam-poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n|film name ={{Infobox name module\n| traditional    = \u7687\u5bb6\u5e2b\u59d0\n| simplified     = \u7687\u5bb6\u5e08\u59d0\n| pinyin         = hu\u00e1ngji\u0101 sh\u012bji\u011b\n| jyutping       = wong4 gaa1 si1 ze2\n| poj            = \n| translation    =royal elder sister\n| lbl8           = \n| data8          =\n}}\n| caption        = Film poster for ''Yes, Madam!''\n| director       = [[Corey Yuen]]\n| producer       = [[Sammo Hung]]\n| writer         = [[Barry Wong]]\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*[[John Shum]]\n*[[Michelle Yeoh]]\n*[[Mang Hoi]]\n*[[Cynthia Rothrock]]\n*[[Tsui Hark]]}}\n| music          =  [[Romeo Diaz]]<br>Tang Siu-lam\n| cinematography = Bill Wong Chung-piu<ref name=\"yes-madam\" />\n| editing        = Sek Chi-kong<br>Keung Chuen-tak<br>Peter Cheung\n| studio         = D & B Films<ref name=\"yes-madam\" />\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1985|11|30|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 93 minutes\n| country        = Hong Kong\n| language       = Cantonese\n| gross          = HK$10,019,862<ref name=\"yes-madam\" />\n}}\n'''''Yes, Madam''''' ({{zh|t=\u7687\u5bb6\u5e2b\u59d0}}, released in the United Kingdom as '''''Police Assassins''''') is a 1985 [[Hong Kong action cinema|Hong Kong action film]] directed by [[Corey Yuen]], and produced by [[Sammo Hung]], who also appears in a cameo in the film. The film stars [[Michelle Yeoh]] as Senior Inspector Ng who teams up with Inspector Carrie Morris ([[Cynthia Rothrock]]) to get a hold of [[microfilm]] which has been taken unknowingly by low level thieves Asprin ([[Mang Hoi]]) and Strepsil ([[John Shum]]).\n\nThe film was the 26th highest grossing film of the year in Hong Kong and gave Mang an award for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] at the [[5th Hong Kong Film Awards]]. It has been described as the first film of the \"[[girls with guns]]\" subgenre.<ref>{{cite book |last= Funnell|first= Lisa |date=21 May 2014 |title= Warrior Women: Gender, Race, and the Transnational Chinese Action Star |url=|location= |publisher=[[SUNY Press]] |page=172 |isbn=9781438452500}}</ref>  ''Yes, Madam'' received several sequels in the ''[[In the Line of Duty (film series)|In the Line of Duty]]'' film series.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n==Plot==\nIn Hong Kong, Inspector Ng (Michelle Yeoh) manages to stop the theft of an armored car by a group of criminals. In another part of the city, a deal is being made between a Westerner and an assassin. After the deal goes sour, the assassin kills the Westerner while the duo of Asprin (Mang Hoi) and Strepsil (John Shum) enter to pickpocket the Westerner and steal his passport. Unknown to all of them, the Westerner had secret [[microform|microfilm]] that contained details of a group of criminals involved in illegal activities, most notably the crooked businessman Mr. Tin. Inspector Ng arrives later and is heartbroken to discover that the dead man was Richard Nornen, with whom she was romantically involved.\n\nAfter authorities find out that Nornen had been working undercover and that the microfilm is missing, the Scottish investigator Carrie Morris (Cynthia Rothrock) is brought in to assist Ng in recovering it. The microfilm is in the possession of some petty thieves, whilst the police are looking for it to prove the guilt of Mr. Tin and his accomplices, who naturally want it destroyed. Meanwhile, Asprin and Strepsil return the passport to Panadol. Panadol sells the passport to a criminal who attempts to leave the country with it, but is thwarted by Morris, who halts him at the airport. Ng allows the criminal to leave but not on the plane, allowing both Morris and Ng to track down the source of the phony passport to Panadol. With Panadol in custody, he inadvertently mentions Asprin and Strepsil as accomplices.\n\nMr. Tin has the most to lose from the microfilm and sends three thugs to Asprin and Strepsil in order to get it from them. Strepsil admits defeat to them and gives over the microfilm. Ng and Morris then attempt to arrest Mr. Tin for possession of the item, but find that the microfilm in his possession is another one of Panadol's fakes and are unable to arrest him. Tin's thugs then manage to find Panadol but beat him so severely that he dies, while Asperin and Strepsil were going to sell the real microfilm for thousands of dollars. When Strepsil finds that Mr. Tin has the microfilm, Asperin and Strepsil, with the two police officers Morris and Ng closely following, arrive at Tin's house for a final showdown. During the battle, the microfilm is destroyed and Ng and Morris are about to be arrested for trespassing. Strepsil, who had just learned of Panadol's death, becomes enraged and grabs a police officer's gun and shoots Tin, who was about to go free because of the destruction of the evidence.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[John Shum]] as Strepsil\n*[[Michelle Yeoh]] as Senior Inspector Ng (as Michelle Khan)\n*[[Mang Hoi]] as Asprin\n*[[Cynthia Rothrock]] as Senior Inspector Carrie Morris\n*[[Tsui Hark]] as Panadol\n*[[Sammo Hung]] as Sifu\n*[[Richard Ng]] as Weak Heart\n*[[David Chiang]] as Sifu's roommate\n*[[Wu Ma]] as Policeman\n*[[Billy Lau]] as Parking Inspector\n*[[Dick Wei]] as Willie\n*[[James Tien (actor)|James Tien]] as Henry Tin\n*[[Chung Fat]] as Big Moustache\n*[[Fruit Chan]] as Fruit\n*[[Chin Ka-lok]] as Henry's thug\n*[[Hsiao Ho]] as Henry's thug\n*[[Corey Yuen]] as Policeman\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| image1=Cynthia Rothrock 2018 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt1=Cynthia Rothrock in 2018\n| caption1=Cynthia Rothrock in 2018\n| width1    = {{#expr: (200 *481/ 720) round 0}}\n\n| image2=Michelle Yeoh Cannes.jpg\n| alt2=Michelle Yeoh in 2007\n| caption2=Michelle Yeoh in 2007\n| width2    = {{#expr: (200 *455 / 595) round 0}}\n\n| footer=''Yes, Madam'' was the debut film for [[Cynthia Rothrock]] and the first starring role in a feature film for [[Michelle Yeoh]].\n| footer_align=left\n}}\nWhile working a martial arts demonstration team, the magazine ''[[Inside Kung Fu]]'' contacted [[Cynthia Rothrock]]'s team stating that D & B Film was looking for a new male lead to play a [[Bruce Lee]]-esque character in a film.<ref name=\"Schubart145\">Schubart, 2007. p.145</ref> Despite looking for a male lead the team has a few women on their team and decided to bring them to demonstrate their skills as well. The studio producers were so impressed with Rothrock's martial arts skills that they offered her the role in the film on the spot and changed the lead from a male to female.<ref name=\"Schubart145\" /> When arriving to shoot the film, Rothrock was surprised of her role as she assumed she was going to be in a traditional period martial arts film.<ref name=\"Schubart127\" />\n\n''Yes, Madam'' was the first starring role in a feature film for [[Michelle Yeoh]]. Yeoh had previously won the 1982 [[Miss_Malaysia#Miss_World_Malaysia|Miss World Malaysia]] contest in 1983. After winning the contest she met D&B executive producer [[Dickson Poon]] who cast her in a small role in a television commercial with entertainer [[Jackie Chan]] in 1984.<ref name=\"allmovie-yeoh\" /><ref>Meyers, 2011. p.177</ref><ref>Meyers, 2011. p.178</ref><ref name=\"stair30\">Stair, 2001. p.30</ref> Her role in the commercial caught the attention of a film production company D&B Films.<ref name=\"allmovie-yeoh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/michelle-yeoh-p223709|work=[[Allmovie]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|title=Michelle Yeoh|accessdate=24 February 2013|author=Crow, Jonathan}}</ref> Yeoh had previously played small roles in Sammo Hung's film ''[[The Owl vs Bombo|Owl vs. Dumbo]]'' (1985) and ''[[Twinkle Twinkle Lucky Stars]]'' (1985).<ref name=\"stair30\" /><ref>Pang, 2005. p.145</ref> For ''Yes, Madam!'', Yeoh took to stunt work opposed to allowing a double for every stunt. To train for her role, Yeoh worked out in a gym for eight hours a day.<ref>Stair, 2001. p.23</ref> [[Michelle Yeoh]] stated that both herself and Rothrock did not want the film to be \"too hard core\", stating that \"We wanted the family to come in and watch it\"<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\">{{cite newspaper|title=Slam-bam Yes, Madame! Yes, Madame AA Starring Michelle Khan and Cynthia Rothrock, directed by Corey Yuen Kwai. At the Riviera Cinema tomorrow 7.30 p.m. and 9.30 p.m.|last=Goddard|first=Peter|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=April 25, 1997|page=C14}}</ref>\n\n''Yes, Madam!'''s score was composed by [[Romeo Diaz]].<ref name=\"yes-madam\">{{cite web|url=http://ipac.hkfa.lcsd.gov.hk/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=136E7K961798P.20593&profile=hkfa&uri=full=3100024@!36850@!0&ri=3&aspect=basic_search&menu=search&source=192.168.110.61@!horizon&ipp=20&staffonly=&term=Yes%2C+madam&index=FILMBRP&uindex=&aspect=basic_search&menu=search&ri=3|work=[[Hong Kong Film Archive]]|title=Yes, Madam|accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref> Diaz would work with director Yuen again on his other films including ''[[Fong Sai-yuk (film)|Fong Sai Yuk]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/fong-sai-yuk-v132934/cast-crew|work=Allmovie|publisher=Rovi Corporation|title=Fong Sai-Yuk (1993) - Cast and Crew|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref> The score also featured parts of the soundtrack from [[John Carpenter]]'s film ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' (1978).<ref>O'Brien, 2003. p.26</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Yes, Madam'' was released in Hong Kong on 20 November 1985.<ref name=\"yes-madam\" /> The film grossed [[HK$]]10,019,862 at the box office being the 21st highest grossing film of the year in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"Morton146\">Morton, 2009. p.146</ref> The popularity of both ''Yes, Madam'' and ''Royal Warriors'' lead to a small wave of Hong Kong film companies to make their own films featuring fighting females such as the ''[[In the Line of Duty (film series)|In the Line of Duty]]'' and the ''[[Black Cat (1991 film)|Black Cat]]'' film series.<ref name=\"Schubart127\">Schubart, 2007. p.127</ref><ref>Pang, 2005. p.146</ref> The film was released in the Philippines by Asia Films as ''The Super Cops'' on 28 January 1988.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grand Opening Today|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=8cBNEdFwSQkC&dat=19880128&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|accessdate=6 January 2019|work=[[Manila Standard]]|publisher=Standard Publishing, Inc.|date=28 January 1988|quote=JACKY CHAN SALUTES THEM... CHUCK NORRIS FEARS THEM... ALL THE OTHER MASTERS,...BEWARE OF THEM!}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Yes, Madam!'' was released and re-released under various titles. In the United States, it was first released under the title ''Supercops''.<ref>Lott, p.152. 2004</ref> Along with another [[Michelle Yeoh]] film ''Royal Warriors'', ''Yes, Madam'' was released under the title ''Ultra Force 1'' and ''Ultra Force 2'' respectively in the European market.<ref name=\"Schubart126\">Schubart, 2007. p.126</ref> Elsewhere the film were re-titled ''In the Line of Duty'' and ''In the Line of Duty 2''.<ref name=\"Schubart127\" /> The ''In the Line of Duty'' films received several sequels.<ref>Meyers, 2011. p.185</ref><ref>Meyers, 2011. p.186</ref>\n\n''Yes, Madam!'' was released under its original title on DVD on 17 November 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/yes-madam%21-v177185/releases|work=[[Allmovie]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|title=Yes, Madam!}}</ref> In 2002, the film was released on DVD under the title ''Police Assassins'' in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"police-assassins\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2002/02/11/police_assassins_1985_dvd_review.shtml|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|title=Police Assassins DVD (1985)|author=Haflidason, Almar}}</ref> In Hong Kong, ''Yes Madam'' was released on Blu-ray on 7 June 2011 by CMS Media Limited. The Blu-ray features both Cantonese and Mandarin language options and English subtitles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yes Madam! Blu-ray - Huang jia shi jie|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Yes-Madam-Blu-ray/24750/|publisher=blu-ray.com|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the [[5th Hong Kong Film Awards]], [[Mang Hoi]] received the award for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]. [[Michelle Yeoh]] was nominated for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best New Performer|Best New Performer]] and [[Corey Yuen]] and Mang were nominated for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Action Choreography|Best Action Choreography]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfaa.com/winnerlist05.html|script-title=zh:\u7b2c5\u5c46\u9999\u6e2f\u96fb\u5f71\u91d1\u50cf\u734e\u5f97\u734e\u540d\u55ae|work=[[Hong Kong Film Awards]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|language=Chinese}}</ref> \n\nFrom retrospective reviews, the [[BBC]] gave the film a three star rating, describing the film as \"tongue-in-cheek nonsense but fun nonetheless\" and praising the fight scenes involving Yeoh and Rothrock.<ref name=\"police-assassins\" /> [[Peter Goddard (journalist)|Peter Goddard]] (''[[The Toronto Star]]'') stated that despite the lead of Rothrock and Yeoh, the film was still focusing on the male actors.<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\" /> The review commented on [[Corey Yuen]]'s action choreography, describing it as \"slick\" and \"cartoony\" but with no \"particularly memorable\" scenes.<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\" /> In his book ''The Hong Kong Filmography, 1977-1997'', John Charles gave the film a seven out of ten, opining that \"like all D&B genre pictures that followed, the storyline is routine but the action certainly isn't.\"<ref name=\"Charles347\">Charles, 2000. p.347</ref> Both Goddard and Charles highlighted a scene where Michelle Yeoh jumps backwards over a rail and through a plate glass.<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\" /><ref name=\"Charles347\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===References===\n*{{Cite book|last=Charles|first=John|title=The Hong Kong Filmography: 1977-1997|publisher=McFarland|year=2000|isbn=147660262X}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Lott|first=M. Ray|title=The American Martial Arts Film|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|year=2004|isbn=0786418362|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3r0yDJcHYtYC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Meyers|first=Ric|title=Films of Fury: The Kung Fu Movie Book|publisher=[[Eirini Press]]|year=2011|isbn=0979998948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9l_hvsyCX7gC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Morton|first=Lisa|title=The Cinema of Tsui Hark|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|year=2009|isbn=0-7864-4460-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MiulRecfarcC&printsec=frontcover|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Daniel|title=Spooky encounters : a Gwailo's guide to Hong Kong horror|isbn=1900486318|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XehfPFuFY8C|location=Manchester|year=2004|publisher=[[Headpress]]}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Pang|first=Laikwan|title=Masculinities And Hong Kong Cinema|publisher=[[Kent State University Press]]|year=2005|isbn=9622097375|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SmO23wZ6hMwC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Schubart|first=Rikke|title=Super Bitches and Action Babes: The Female Hero in Popular Cinema, 1970-2006|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|year=2007|isbn=0786482842|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GYOeGrtUjAoC&pg=PA127|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Stair|first=Nancy|title=Michelle Yeoh|publisher=[[The Rosen Publishing Group]]|year=2001|isbn=0823935205|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_cwbUsQW1TAC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1980s|Film|Hong Kong|}}\n*[[List of action films of the 1980s]]\n*[[List of Hong Kong films of 1985]]\n*[[Sammo Hung filmography]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0093229}}\n\n{{Corey Yuen}}\n\n[[Category:1985 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action films]]\n[[Category:Cantonese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Corey Yuen]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Girls with guns films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Police detective films]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{about||the 1939 British film|Yes, Madam?|the 1942 Italian film|Yes, Madam (1942 film)|the 2003 Indian Tamil film|Yes Madam (2003 film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Yes, Madam\n| image          = Yes-madam-poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n|film name ={{Infobox name module\n| traditional    = \u7687\u5bb6\u5e2b\u59d0\n| simplified     = \u7687\u5bb6\u5e08\u59d0\n| pinyin         = hu\u00e1ngji\u0101 sh\u012bji\u011b\n| jyutping       = wong4 gaa1 si1 ze2\n| poj            = \n| translation    =royal elder sister\n| lbl8           = \n| data8          =\n}}\n| caption        = Film poster for ''Yes, Madam!''\n| director       = [[Corey Yuen]]\n| producer       = [[Sammo Hung]]\n| writer         = [[Barry Wong]]\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*[[John Shum]]\n*[[Michelle Yeoh]]\n*[[Mang Hoi]]\n*[[Cynthia Rothrock]]\n*[[Tsui Hark]]}}\n| music          =  [[Romeo Diaz]]<br>Tang Siu-lam\n| cinematography = Bill Wong Chung-piu<ref name=\"yes-madam\" />\n| editing        = Sek Chi-kong<br>Keung Chuen-tak<br>Peter Cheung\n| studio         = D & B Films<ref name=\"yes-madam\" />\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1985|11|30|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 93 minutes\n| country        = Hong Kong\n| language       = Cantonese\n| gross          = HK$10,019,862<ref name=\"yes-madam\" />\n}}\n'''''Yes, Madam''''' ({{zh|t=\u7687\u5bb6\u5e2b\u59d0}}, released in the United Kingdom as '''''Police Assassins''''') is a 1985 [[Hong Kong action cinema|Hong Kong action film]] directed by [[Corey Yuen]], and produced by [[Sammo Hung]], who also appears in a cameo in the film. The film stars [[Michelle Yeoh]] as Senior Inspector Ng who teams up with Inspector Carrie Morris ([[Cynthia Rothrock]]) to get a hold of [[microfilm]] which has been taken unknowingly by low level thieves Asprin ([[Mang Hoi]]) and Strepsil ([[John Shum]]).\n\nThe film was the 26th highest grossing film of the year in Hong Kong and gave Mang an award for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] at the [[5th Hong Kong Film Awards]]. It has been described as the first film of the \"[[girls with guns]]\" subgenre.<ref>{{cite book |last= Funnell|first= Lisa |date=21 May 2014 |title= Warrior Women: Gender, Race, and the Transnational Chinese Action Star |url=|location= |publisher=[[SUNY Press]] |page=172 |isbn=9781438452500}}</ref>  ''Yes, Madam'' received several sequels in the ''[[In the Line of Duty (film series)|In the Line of Duty]]'' film series.\n\n==Plot==\nIn Hong Kong, Inspector Ng (Michelle Yeoh) manages to stop the theft of an armored car by a group of criminals. In another part of the city, a deal is being made between a Westerner and an assassin. After the deal goes sour, the assassin kills the Westerner while the duo of Asprin (Mang Hoi) and Strepsil (John Shum) enter to pickpocket the Westerner and steal his passport. Unknown to all of them, the Westerner had secret [[microform|microfilm]] that contained details of a group of criminals involved in illegal activities, most notably the crooked businessman Mr. Tin. Inspector Ng arrives later and is heartbroken to discover that the dead man was Richard Nornen, with whom she was romantically involved.\n\nAfter authorities find out that Nornen had been working undercover and that the microfilm is missing, the Scottish investigator Carrie Morris (Cynthia Rothrock) is brought in to assist Ng in recovering it. The microfilm is in the possession of some petty thieves, whilst the police are looking for it to prove the guilt of Mr. Tin and his accomplices, who naturally want it destroyed. Meanwhile, Asprin and Strepsil return the passport to Panadol. Panadol sells the passport to a criminal who attempts to leave the country with it, but is thwarted by Morris, who halts him at the airport. Ng allows the criminal to leave but not on the plane, allowing both Morris and Ng to track down the source of the phony passport to Panadol. With Panadol in custody, he inadvertently mentions Asprin and Strepsil as accomplices.\n\nMr. Tin has the most to lose from the microfilm and sends three thugs to Asprin and Strepsil in order to get it from them. Strepsil admits defeat to them and gives over the microfilm. Ng and Morris then attempt to arrest Mr. Tin for possession of the item, but find that the microfilm in his possession is another one of Panadol's fakes and are unable to arrest him. Tin's thugs then manage to find Panadol but beat him so severely that he dies, while Asperin and Strepsil were going to sell the real microfilm for thousands of dollars. When Strepsil finds that Mr. Tin has the microfilm, Asperin and Strepsil, with the two police officers Morris and Ng closely following, arrive at Tin's house for a final showdown. During the battle, the microfilm is destroyed and Ng and Morris are about to be arrested for trespassing. Strepsil, who had just learned of Panadol's death, becomes enraged and grabs a police officer's gun and shoots Tin, who was about to go free because of the destruction of the evidence.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[John Shum]] as Strepsil\n*[[Michelle Yeoh]] as Senior Inspector Ng (as Michelle Khan)\n*[[Mang Hoi]] as Asprin\n*[[Cynthia Rothrock]] as Senior Inspector Carrie Morris\n*[[Tsui Hark]] as Panadol\n*[[Sammo Hung]] as Sifu\n*[[Richard Ng]] as Weak Heart\n*[[David Chiang]] as Sifu's roommate\n*[[Wu Ma]] as Policeman\n*[[Billy Lau]] as Parking Inspector\n*[[Dick Wei]] as Willie\n*[[James Tien (actor)|James Tien]] as Henry Tin\n*[[Chung Fat]] as Big Moustache\n*[[Fruit Chan]] as Fruit\n*[[Chin Ka-lok]] as Henry's thug\n*[[Hsiao Ho]] as Henry's thug\n*[[Corey Yuen]] as Policeman\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| image1=Cynthia Rothrock 2018 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt1=Cynthia Rothrock in 2018\n| caption1=Cynthia Rothrock in 2018\n| width1    = {{#expr: (200 *481/ 720) round 0}}\n\n| image2=Michelle Yeoh Cannes.jpg\n| alt2=Michelle Yeoh in 2007\n| caption2=Michelle Yeoh in 2007\n| width2    = {{#expr: (200 *455 / 595) round 0}}\n\n| footer=''Yes, Madam'' was the debut film for [[Cynthia Rothrock]] and the first starring role in a feature film for [[Michelle Yeoh]].\n| footer_align=left\n}}\nWhile working a martial arts demonstration team, the magazine ''[[Inside Kung Fu]]'' contacted [[Cynthia Rothrock]]'s team stating that D & B Film was looking for a new male lead to play a [[Bruce Lee]]-esque character in a film.<ref name=\"Schubart145\">Schubart, 2007. p.145</ref> Despite looking for a male lead the team has a few women on their team and decided to bring them to demonstrate their skills as well. The studio producers were so impressed with Rothrock's martial arts skills that they offered her the role in the film on the spot and changed the lead from a male to female.<ref name=\"Schubart145\" /> When arriving to shoot the film, Rothrock was surprised of her role as she assumed she was going to be in a traditional period martial arts film.<ref name=\"Schubart127\" />\n\n''Yes, Madam'' was the first starring role in a feature film for [[Michelle Yeoh]]. Yeoh had previously won the 1982 [[Miss_Malaysia#Miss_World_Malaysia|Miss World Malaysia]] contest in 1983. After winning the contest she met D&B executive producer [[Dickson Poon]] who cast her in a small role in a television commercial with entertainer [[Jackie Chan]] in 1984.<ref name=\"allmovie-yeoh\" /><ref>Meyers, 2011. p.177</ref><ref>Meyers, 2011. p.178</ref><ref name=\"stair30\">Stair, 2001. p.30</ref> Her role in the commercial caught the attention of a film production company D&B Films.<ref name=\"allmovie-yeoh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/michelle-yeoh-p223709|work=[[Allmovie]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|title=Michelle Yeoh|accessdate=24 February 2013|author=Crow, Jonathan}}</ref> Yeoh had previously played small roles in Sammo Hung's film ''[[The Owl vs Bombo|Owl vs. Dumbo]]'' (1985) and ''[[Twinkle Twinkle Lucky Stars]]'' (1985).<ref name=\"stair30\" /><ref>Pang, 2005. p.145</ref> For ''Yes, Madam!'', Yeoh took to stunt work opposed to allowing a double for every stunt. To train for her role, Yeoh worked out in a gym for eight hours a day.<ref>Stair, 2001. p.23</ref> [[Michelle Yeoh]] stated that both herself and Rothrock did not want the film to be \"too hard core\", stating that \"We wanted the family to come in and watch it\"<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\">{{cite newspaper|title=Slam-bam Yes, Madame! Yes, Madame AA Starring Michelle Khan and Cynthia Rothrock, directed by Corey Yuen Kwai. At the Riviera Cinema tomorrow 7.30 p.m. and 9.30 p.m.|last=Goddard|first=Peter|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=April 25, 1997|page=C14}}</ref>\n\n''Yes, Madam!'''s score was composed by [[Romeo Diaz]].<ref name=\"yes-madam\">{{cite web|url=http://ipac.hkfa.lcsd.gov.hk/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=136E7K961798P.20593&profile=hkfa&uri=full=3100024@!36850@!0&ri=3&aspect=basic_search&menu=search&source=192.168.110.61@!horizon&ipp=20&staffonly=&term=Yes%2C+madam&index=FILMBRP&uindex=&aspect=basic_search&menu=search&ri=3|work=[[Hong Kong Film Archive]]|title=Yes, Madam|accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref> Diaz would work with director Yuen again on his other films including ''[[Fong Sai-yuk (film)|Fong Sai Yuk]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/fong-sai-yuk-v132934/cast-crew|work=Allmovie|publisher=Rovi Corporation|title=Fong Sai-Yuk (1993) - Cast and Crew|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref> The score also featured parts of the soundtrack from [[John Carpenter]]'s film ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' (1978).<ref>O'Brien, 2003. p.26</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Yes, Madam'' was released in Hong Kong on 20 November 1985.<ref name=\"yes-madam\" /> The film grossed [[HK$]]10,019,862 at the box office being the 21st highest grossing film of the year in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"Morton146\">Morton, 2009. p.146</ref> The popularity of both ''Yes, Madam'' and ''Royal Warriors'' lead to a small wave of Hong Kong film companies to make their own films featuring fighting females such as the ''[[In the Line of Duty (film series)|In the Line of Duty]]'' and the ''[[Black Cat (1991 film)|Black Cat]]'' film series.<ref name=\"Schubart127\">Schubart, 2007. p.127</ref><ref>Pang, 2005. p.146</ref> The film was released in the Philippines by Asia Films as ''The Super Cops'' on 28 January 1988.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grand Opening Today|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=8cBNEdFwSQkC&dat=19880128&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|accessdate=6 January 2019|work=[[Manila Standard]]|publisher=Standard Publishing, Inc.|date=28 January 1988|quote=JACKY CHAN SALUTES THEM... CHUCK NORRIS FEARS THEM... ALL THE OTHER MASTERS,...BEWARE OF THEM!}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Yes, Madam!'' was released and re-released under various titles. In the United States, it was first released under the title ''Supercops''.<ref>Lott, p.152. 2004</ref> Along with another [[Michelle Yeoh]] film ''Royal Warriors'', ''Yes, Madam'' was released under the title ''Ultra Force 1'' and ''Ultra Force 2'' respectively in the European market.<ref name=\"Schubart126\">Schubart, 2007. p.126</ref> Elsewhere the film were re-titled ''In the Line of Duty'' and ''In the Line of Duty 2''.<ref name=\"Schubart127\" /> The ''In the Line of Duty'' films received several sequels.<ref>Meyers, 2011. p.185</ref><ref>Meyers, 2011. p.186</ref>\n\n''Yes, Madam!'' was released under its original title on DVD on 17 November 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/yes-madam%21-v177185/releases|work=[[Allmovie]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|title=Yes, Madam!}}</ref> In 2002, the film was released on DVD under the title ''Police Assassins'' in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"police-assassins\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2002/02/11/police_assassins_1985_dvd_review.shtml|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|title=Police Assassins DVD (1985)|author=Haflidason, Almar}}</ref> In Hong Kong, ''Yes Madam'' was released on Blu-ray on 7 June 2011 by CMS Media Limited. The Blu-ray features both Cantonese and Mandarin language options and English subtitles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yes Madam! Blu-ray - Huang jia shi jie|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Yes-Madam-Blu-ray/24750/|publisher=blu-ray.com|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the [[5th Hong Kong Film Awards]], [[Mang Hoi]] received the award for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]. [[Michelle Yeoh]] was nominated for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best New Performer|Best New Performer]] and [[Corey Yuen]] and Mang were nominated for [[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Action Choreography|Best Action Choreography]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkfaa.com/winnerlist05.html|script-title=zh:\u7b2c5\u5c46\u9999\u6e2f\u96fb\u5f71\u91d1\u50cf\u734e\u5f97\u734e\u540d\u55ae|work=[[Hong Kong Film Awards]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|language=Chinese}}</ref> \n\nFrom retrospective reviews, the [[BBC]] gave the film a three star rating, describing the film as \"tongue-in-cheek nonsense but fun nonetheless\" and praising the fight scenes involving Yeoh and Rothrock.<ref name=\"police-assassins\" /> [[Peter Goddard (journalist)|Peter Goddard]] (''[[The Toronto Star]]'') stated that despite the lead of Rothrock and Yeoh, the film was still focusing on the male actors.<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\" /> The review commented on [[Corey Yuen]]'s action choreography, describing it as \"slick\" and \"cartoony\" but with no \"particularly memorable\" scenes.<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\" /> In his book ''The Hong Kong Filmography, 1977-1997'', John Charles gave the film a seven out of ten, opining that \"like all D&B genre pictures that followed, the storyline is routine but the action certainly isn't.\"<ref name=\"Charles347\">Charles, 2000. p.347</ref> Both Goddard and Charles highlighted a scene where Michelle Yeoh jumps backwards over a rail and through a plate glass.<ref name=\"yes-madam-ts\" /><ref name=\"Charles347\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===References===\n*{{Cite book|last=Charles|first=John|title=The Hong Kong Filmography: 1977-1997|publisher=McFarland|year=2000|isbn=147660262X}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Lott|first=M. Ray|title=The American Martial Arts Film|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|year=2004|isbn=0786418362|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3r0yDJcHYtYC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Meyers|first=Ric|title=Films of Fury: The Kung Fu Movie Book|publisher=[[Eirini Press]]|year=2011|isbn=0979998948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9l_hvsyCX7gC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Morton|first=Lisa|title=The Cinema of Tsui Hark|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|year=2009|isbn=0-7864-4460-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MiulRecfarcC&printsec=frontcover|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Daniel|title=Spooky encounters : a Gwailo's guide to Hong Kong horror|isbn=1900486318|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XehfPFuFY8C|location=Manchester|year=2004|publisher=[[Headpress]]}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Pang|first=Laikwan|title=Masculinities And Hong Kong Cinema|publisher=[[Kent State University Press]]|year=2005|isbn=9622097375|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SmO23wZ6hMwC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Schubart|first=Rikke|title=Super Bitches and Action Babes: The Female Hero in Popular Cinema, 1970-2006|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|year=2007|isbn=0786482842|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GYOeGrtUjAoC&pg=PA127|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Stair|first=Nancy|title=Michelle Yeoh|publisher=[[The Rosen Publishing Group]]|year=2001|isbn=0823935205|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_cwbUsQW1TAC|accessdate=24 February 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1980s|Film|Hong Kong|}}\n*[[List of action films of the 1980s]]\n*[[List of Hong Kong films of 1985]]\n*[[Sammo Hung filmography]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0093229}}\n\n{{Corey Yuen}}\n\n[[Category:1985 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action films]]\n[[Category:Cantonese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Corey Yuen]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Girls with guns films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong films]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Police detective films]]\n", "name_user": "Underwaterbuffalo", "label": "safe", "comment": "fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yes,_Madam"}
{"title_page": "Miko Peled", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Miko Peled\n| image       = Miko Peled.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date  = 1961<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Jerusalem]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Israeli-American\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = \n| known_for   = author of ''The General's Son: the Journey of an Israeli in Palestine''\n}} \n'''Miko Peled''' (born 1961) is an Israeli-American activist, author, and karate instructor. He is author of the books ''The General\u2019s Son: The Journey of an Israeli in Palestine''<ref name=\"justworldbooks.com\">{{cite web\n| title =The General's Son: the Journey of an Israeli in Palestine\n| work =Just World Books\n| url =http://justworldbooks.com/the-generals-son-journey-of-an-israeli-in-palestine/\n| access-date =20 May 2013\n| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130527145135/http://justworldbooks.com/the-generals-son-journey-of-an-israeli-in-palestine/\n| archive-date =27 May 2013\n| url-status =dead\n}}</ref> and ''Injustice: The Story of the Holy Land Foundation Five''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Injustice-Story-Holy-Land-Foundation-ebook/dp/B078WHP38B|title=Injustice: The Story of the Holy Land Foundation Five|last=Peled|first=Miko|date=2018-02-01|publisher=Just World Books|isbn=9781682570869|edition= 1st|location=|pages=|language=English}}</ref> He is also an international speaker.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Jerusalem in 1961, Peled grew up in [[Motza Illit]] to a prominent [[Zionist]] family; his grandfather, [[Avraham Katsnelson]], signed Israel\u2019s Declaration of Independence.<ref name=\"justworldbooks.com\"/><ref name=peled>{{cite web| title =About Miko| work =mikopeled.com| url =http://mikopeled.com}}</ref> \nHis father, [[Mattityahu Peled]], fought in the [[1947\u20131949 Palestine war]], and served as a general in the [[Six-Day War]] of 1967; later, after the Israeli cabinet ignored his investigation of a 1967 alleged Israeli war crime, he became an advocate for an Israeli dialogue with the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] (PLO). He condemned the Israeli military for seizing the [[West Bank]], [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]], [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]] and the [[Golan Heights]], calling the war a \"cynical campaign of territorial expansion\".<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Book Review: The Generals Son - Journey of an Israeli in Palestine\n| work =Muslim Link\n| url =http://www.muslimlink.ca/life/book-review/book-review-the-generals-son-journey-of-an-israeli-in-palestine\n}}</ref> Palestinian activist [[Susan Abulhawa]] has described Peled's father, who died in 1995, as \"a man that many of us Palestinians could not figure out whether to love or hate\" and whom \"many notable Palestinians\" nicknamed \"Abu Salam\" (Father of Peace).<ref name=record>{{cite web| last =Abulhawa| first =Susan| title =Miko Peled Sets the Record Straight on Palestines Dispossession| work =Electronic Intifada| date =29 November 2012| url =http://electronicintifada.net/content/book-review-miko-peled-sets-record-straight-palestines-dispossession/11950}}</ref>  His brother is the political scientist [[Yoav Peled]].\n\nMiko Peled followed his father\u2019s footsteps at first, joining Israel\u2019s Special Forces after high school and earning the red beret, but he soon grew to regret his decision. \nHe surrendered his status as soon as he earned it, becoming a medic, and finally, disgusted by the [[1982 Lebanon war|1982 Lebanon invasion]], he buried his service pin in the dirt.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =The General\u2019s Son: Journey of an Israeli in Palestine\n| work =War Resisters League\n| url =https://www.warresisters.org/content/general\u2019s-son-journey-israeli-palestine\n| access-date =4 April 2020\n| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150421205634/http://www.warresisters.org/content/general%E2%80%99s-son-journey-israeli-palestine\n| archive-date =21 April 2015\n| url-status =dead\n}}</ref>\n\nOne evening in 1983, however, he skipped a [[Peace Now]] demonstration in Jerusalem to attend karate class, and on that evening a grenade attack by a right-wing extremist killed one of the demonstrators. \"Peled took this as a sign,\" according to one interview, and consequently \"followed the path of karate \u2013 a practice of non-violence...that teaches one to 'overcome insurmountable obstacles.'\" This path \"that took him to Japan and eventually to San Diego, where he settled with his wife and family\".<ref name=ditmar>{{cite web| last =Ditmars| first =Hidani| title =Following in the footsteps of his father, a Zionist hero, toward a free and democratic Palestine| work =Haaretz| date =8 Apr 2013| url =http://www.haaretz.com/misc/article-print-page/following-in-the-footsteps-of-his-father-a-zionist-hero-toward-a-free-and-democratic-palestine-1.514402?trailingPath=2.169%2C2.216%2C2.221%2C}}</ref> He then distanced himself from activism until 1997, becoming a [[Dan (rank)#Usage in martial arts|sixth-degree]] black belt in karate and moving first to Japan, then to [[San Diego]], [[California]], United States.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\">{{cite web\n| last =Ditmars\n| first =Hadani\n| title =Following in the footsteps of his father, a Zionist hero, toward a free and democratic Palestine\n| work =Haaretz\n| date =Apr 8, 2013\n| url =http://www.haaretz.com/news/features/following-in-the-footsteps-of-his-father-a-zionist-hero-toward-a-free-and-democratic-palestine-1.514402\n}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nIn 1997, Peled\u2019s 13-year-old niece Smadar, daughter of his sister [[Nurit Peled-Elhanan]],  was killed in an anti-Israel suicide attack in Jerusalem.  At her funeral, according to an article summarizing Peled's book, [[Ehud Barak]], who had just been elected to lead the opposition, explained that in order to gain appeal he must disguise his real intentions of becoming a 'peacemaker.\u201d \nIn reply, Peled said, \u201cWhy not tell the truth ... That this and similar tragedies are taking place because we are occupying another nation and that in order to save lives the right thing to do is to end the occupation and negotiate a just peace with our Palestinian partners?\"<ref name=ditmar/>\n\nThe murder of Smadar, and his sister Nurit\u2019s insistence that it was caused by the occupation, \u201cjolted him back into Middle Eastern reality,\u201d an interviewer has written. \u201cThe activist side of me that I\u2019d been suppressing,\u201d Peled has said, \u201csuddenly burst out. It became stronger than anything.\u201d<ref name=ditmar/> He joined a Palestinian/Jewish-American dialogue group in San Diego, where he \u201cfound that the Jewish Americans he met \u2013 with their 'New York humor and deli food' \u2013 were more foreign than the hummus, tabouleh and warm hospitality offered by his new Palestinian friends. He was shocked by random anti-Arab venom spewed casually by Jewish Americans he met who assumed he shared their views, in an atmosphere of growing Islamophobia.\u201d He also befriended Nader Elbanna, \u201ca Palestinian from Nazareth who accompanied him on a dual lecture series at rotary clubs.\u201d<ref name=ditmar/> Thus began a process whereby, in the words of Abulhawa, Peled \u201cdismantled a lifetime of racist assumptions and replaced them with something more human and tender.\u201d<ref name=record/>\n\nReturning to activism, Peled decided that the two-state solution his father had promoted would no longer suffice, and began to support for the creation of a single democratic state with equal rights for Israelis and Palestinians.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/> He claims that Israel is an apartheid state that must go, and that an integrated single-state solution is closer than many people think because of the changing mindsets of many Israelis, American Jews, and Holocaust survivors. The Israeli government, he has written, is \u201ca radical Zionist regime,\u201d and Israel is a country where \u201chalf of the population lives in what it thinks is a Western democracy while keeping the other half imprisoned by a ruthless defense apparatus that is becoming more violent by the day.\u201d<ref name=peled/> He told that \"The State of Israel Will Crumble and We Will See A Free Democratic Palestine from the River to the Sea Sooner than Most People Think\".<ref>[https://ahtribune.com/interview/2487-miko-peled.html Miko Peled: The State of Israel Will Crumble and We Will See A Free Democratic Palestine from the River to the Sea Sooner than Most People Think], September 21, 2018</ref>\n\nPeled has traveled in Palestine, teaching karate to children in refugee camps and engaging in nonviolent activism.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/> In his blog, he calls for the removal of Israel\u2019s separation wall, and the institution of equal rights for Israelis and Palestinians. \"As an Israeli that was raised on the Zionist ideal of a Jewish state\", he writes in the blog, \"I know how hard it is for many Jews and Palestinians to let go of the dream of having a state that is exclusively 'our own.' The articles, the stories and the pictures in this blog are meant to make a single point: For the good of both nations, the Separation Wall must come down, the Israeli control over the lives of Palestinians must be defied so that a secular democracy where all Israelis and Palestinian live as equals be established in our shared homeland\".<ref name=peled/> Peled is a regular contributor to online publications like the ''[[Electronic Intifada]]'' and the ''Palestine Chronicle''.\n\nPeled spoke at a fringe gathering at the British [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party conference]] in Brighton in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url= https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/israeli-born-anti-zionist-calls-israel-a-racist-settler-regime-at-labour-conference-1.444944 |title= Israeli-born anti-Zionist calls Israel a 'racist settler regime' at Labour conference|work= [[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date= 25 September 2017 |accessdate= 26 September 2017}}</ref> At the event, Peled is reported to have said: \"This is about free speech, the freedom to criticise and to discuss every issue, whether it\u2019s the Holocaust: yes or no, Palestine, the liberation, the whole spectrum. There should be no limits on the discussion\". He further went on to compare [[Zionists]] to Nazis and \"apartheid South Africa racists\".<ref name=\"Weaver\">{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Matthew|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/26/new-antisemitism-row-for-labour-over-fringe-speakers-holocaust-remarks-miko-peled|title=Labour fringe speaker's Holocaust remarks spark new antisemitism row|work=The Guardian|date=26 September 2017|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> Deputy Labour leader [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] said the conference organising committee would investigate how Peled was given a platform at the event.<ref name=\"Weaver\"/>\n\nAt a meeting at [[University College London]] the following November, Peled complained about the \"witch-hunt against antisemites and Holocaust deniers\" over the past two years and complimented the \"clear leadership\" of Labour's [[Jeremy Corbyn]] commenting that Corbyn had \"put away this nonsense about Holocaust denial and this nonsense about antisemitism. You focus on what\u2019s important\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Alastair|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/miko-peled-zionists-do-not-deserve-a-platform-1.447859|title=Miko Peled: Zionists do not deserve a platform|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=12 November 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\u201cIsrael has been on a mission to destroy the Palestinian people for over six decades,\u201d Peled has said. \u201cWhy would anyone not give solidarity to the Palestinian people?\u201d<ref name=mclr>{{cite web| last =Mcllroy| first =Jim| title =Generals son condemns Israeli oppression, supports BDS| work =Green Left| date =Oct 7, 2011| url =http://www.greenleft.org.au/node/48978#sthash.fawyWrv3.dpuf}}</ref> He believes that Israel's actions in the Six-Day War of 1967 were not a response to a real threat but acts of bald aggression.<ref name=silver>{{cite web| last =Silver| first =Charlotte| title =Palestine freedom battle will be won: interview with author Miko Peled| work =Electronic Intifada| date =Oct 3, 2012| url =http://electronicintifada.net/content/palestine-freedom-battle-will-be-won-interview-author-miko-peled/11725}}</ref>  And he has said that \u201cevery single Israeli city is a settlement\u201d and that \u201cexpressing solidarity with Palestinians is the most important thing people can do.\u201d<ref name=silver/>\n\nOn his Twitter feed, Peled has written that \u201cIDF lusts for blood,\u201d has called the peace process \u201ca process of apartheid & colonization,\u201d and has accused Israeli officials of \u201cethnic cleansing.\u201d<ref>{{cite web| title =Miko Peled| work =Twitter| url =https://twitter.com/mikopeled}}</ref> In his blog posts, he repeatedly refers to the IDF as an \u201cIsraeli terrorist organization\u201d that is part of a \u201cwell-oiled ethnic cleansing machine.\u201d He has also written that Israel's educational system is designed to turn Israeli children into racists who view Palestinians \u201cas culturally inferior, violent and bent on the annihilation of the Jews, and...void of a true national identity,\u201d and \u201cas a problem that must be solved and as a threat that must be eliminated.\u201d He has decried \u201cabsurd comparisons like that of Yasser Arafat to Hitler, the Palestinians to Nazis, and the Palestinian resistance to Al Qaeda.\u201d<ref>{{cite web| last =Peled| first =Miko| title =Ethnic Cleansing of Invented People| work =mikopeled.com| date =Dec 20, 2011| url =http://mikopeled.com/2011/12/20/ethnic-cleansing-of-invented-people-by-miko-peled/}}</ref>\n\nPeled supports [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|the movement for boycotts, divestment, and sanctions (BDS) against Israel]]. Giving a talk in [[Queensland, Australia]], he supported a BDS campaign against the Israeli-owned [[Max Brenner]] chain of chocolate shops, part of the Strauss group of companies, which, he said, \u201csupports a terrorist organisation, the Golani Brigade.\u201d  BDS, he argued, was a \u201ctotally legitimate\u201d means of \u201ctrying to stop this Israeli armed juggernaut.\u201d<ref name=mclr/>\n\nPeled wrote in a June 2012 op-ed for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that,\n{{quote|\u201cIsrael is faced with two options: Continue to exist as a Jewish state while controlling the Palestinians through military force and racist laws, or undertake a deep transformation into a real democracy where Israelis and Palestinians live as equals in a shared state, their shared homeland. For Israelis and Palestinians alike, the latter path promises a bright future.<ref>{{cite web| last =Peled| first =Miko| title =Six Days in Israel, 45 Years Ago| work =Los Angeles Times| date =Jun 6, 2012| url =http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/06/opinion/la-oe-peled-israel-palestine--six-day-war-201206}}</ref>}}\n\n==Books==\nPeled has described his book, ''The General\u2019s Son: Journey of an Israeli in Palestine'' (2012),<ref name=\"justworldbooks.com\"/> as an account of how he, \"the son of an Israeli General and a staunch Zionist, came to realize that \"the story upon which I was raised ... was a lie.\"<ref name=peled/>  The book, he has said, is based largely on long conversations with his mother, on a thorough reading of \"everything my dad had ever written,\" and on material about his father's career in the Israeli army archives.<ref name=silver/>\n\nThe book, which has been characterized as \"part confessional, part cinematic epic and part emotional appeal for 'different answers' to the Israeli-Palestinian conundrum,\"<ref name=ditmar/> contains a foreword by [[Alice Walker]], author of ''[[The Color Purple]]''.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = archives\n |work        = The Madison Times\n |url         = http://www.themadisontimes.com/news_details.php?news_id=2369\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20121210211850/http://www.themadisontimes.com/news_details.php?news_id=2369\n |archivedate = 10 December 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn Peled's book, ''Injustice: The Story of the Holy Land Foundation Five'' (2018), he catalogs the trial of the criminalization and dismantling of the [[Holy Land Foundation for Relief and Development]], leading to the arrest and jailing of Foundation President Shukri Abu Baker, Chairman [[Ghassan Elashi]], Mohammad el-Mezain, [[Mufid Abdulqader]] and Abdulraham Odeh.\n\n==Elbanna-Peled Foundation==\nPeled is, with Nader Elbanna, co-founder of the Elbanna-Peled Foundation. Established in 2010 and based in Coronado, California, it describes itself as being \"committed to peace, justice and equality by operating exclusively for charitable and educational purposes, including, but not limited to the following:\n#Humanitarian aid to civilians who were injured as a result of Israeli Palestinian conflict.\n#Support existing educational efforts that promote Israeli Palestinian reconciliation.\n#Support local grassroots organizations that work together (Israelis and Palestinians) toward a non-violent resolution of the conflict.\"<ref>{{cite web| title =About| work =Elbanna Peled Foundation| url =http://www.elbannapeledfoundation.org/?page_id=2| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20131224110801/http://www.elbannapeledfoundation.org/?page_id=2| archivedate =24 December 2013| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation describes itself as working closely with Rotary International. According to its website, \"Peled and Elbanna sent 1000 wheelchairs for Palestinians and Israeli children, and have been part of numerous project to help the people of their shared homeland.\"\n\nThe foundation, however, was established under the National Taxonomy of Exempt Entities (NTEE) categories \"Foreign Affairs\" and \"National Security.\"Its exempt status, moreover, was automatically revoked by the IRS because it failed to file a Form 990 (\"Return of Organization Exempt from Income \nTax\") for three consecutive years.<ref>{{cite web| title =ELBANNA-PELED FOUNDATION| work =Guidestar| url =http://www.guidestar.org/organizations/80-0192335/elbanna-peled-foundation.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Martial Arts America==\nSince 28 May 1989, Peled, a sixth-degree black belt, owned, operated, and taught at Martial Arts America, a school in [[Coronado, California]], which \"is dedicated to teaching leadership skills and non-violent conflict resolution through martial arts.\" In October 2012, he sold the business to his top student of over twenty years, David Michael Adams, in order to focus on promoting his book ''The General's Son''.<ref>{{cite web| title =Welcome to our website| work =Coronado Karate| url =http://coronadokarate.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mikopeled.com/ Miko Peled's blog]\n* [http://thegeneralsson.com/ ''The General's Son'' website]\n* [http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=767&Itemid=74&jumival=16303 Video] of Peled interview with [[Chris Hedges]], 10 May 2016; and a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VTepqDOMdZw video] of Peled's second interview with Hedges, 24 September 2016\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TOaxAckFCuQ&feature=player_embedded Video] of Peled's talk in Seattle, USA, 9 October 2012\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4ZfnpN4Dfc/ Interview] with Miko Peled by Alternate Focus; and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rI9-dEs9HIM/ Second interview] with Miko Peled by Alternate Focus\n* [https://therealnews.com/bios/miko-peled interviews] with [[Paul Jay]] of ''[[The Real News]]''\n* https://ahtribune.com/interview/2487-miko-peled.html\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peled, Miko}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Israeli anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Motza Illit]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Miko Peled\n| image       = Miko Peled.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date  = 1961<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Jerusalem]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Israeli-American\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = \n| known_for   = author of ''The General's Son: the Journey of an Israeli in Palestine''\n}} \n'''Miko Peled''' (born 1961) is an Israeli-American activist, author, and karate instructor. He is author of the books ''The General\u2019s Son: The Journey of an Israeli in Palestine''<ref name=\"justworldbooks.com\">{{cite web\n| title =The General's Son: the Journey of an Israeli in Palestine\n| work =Just World Books\n| url =http://justworldbooks.com/the-generals-son-journey-of-an-israeli-in-palestine/\n| access-date =20 May 2013\n| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130527145135/http://justworldbooks.com/the-generals-son-journey-of-an-israeli-in-palestine/\n| archive-date =27 May 2013\n| url-status =dead\n}}</ref> and ''Injustice: The Story of the Holy Land Foundation Five''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Injustice-Story-Holy-Land-Foundation-ebook/dp/B078WHP38B|title=Injustice: The Story of the Holy Land Foundation Five|last=Peled|first=Miko|date=2018-02-01|publisher=Just World Books|isbn=9781682570869|edition= 1st|location=|pages=|language=English}}</ref> He is also an international speaker.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Jerusalem in 1961, Peled grew up in [[Motza Illit]] to a prominent [[Zionist]] family; his grandfather, [[Avraham Katsnelson]], signed Israel\u2019s Declaration of Independence.<ref name=\"justworldbooks.com\"/><ref name=peled>{{cite web| title =About Miko| work =mikopeled.com| url =http://mikopeled.com}}</ref> \nHis father, [[Mattityahu Peled]], fought in the [[1947\u20131949 Palestine war]], and served as a general in the [[Six-Day War]] of 1967; later, after the Israeli cabinet ignored his investigation of a 1967 alleged Israeli war crime, he became an advocate for an Israeli dialogue with the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] (PLO). He condemned the Israeli military for seizing the [[West Bank]], [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]], [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]] and the [[Golan Heights]], calling the war a \"cynical campaign of territorial expansion\".<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Book Review: The Generals Son - Journey of an Israeli in Palestine\n| work =Muslim Link\n| url =http://www.muslimlink.ca/life/book-review/book-review-the-generals-son-journey-of-an-israeli-in-palestine\n}}</ref> Palestinian activist [[Susan Abulhawa]] has described Peled's father, who died in 1995, as \"a man that many of us Palestinians could not figure out whether to love or hate\" and whom \"many notable Palestinians\" nicknamed \"Abu Salam\" (Father of Peace).<ref name=record>{{cite web| last =Abulhawa| first =Susan| title =Miko Peled Sets the Record Straight on Palestines Dispossession| work =Electronic Intifada| date =29 November 2012| url =http://electronicintifada.net/content/book-review-miko-peled-sets-record-straight-palestines-dispossession/11950}}</ref>  His brother is the political scientist [[Yoav Peled]].\n\nMiko Peled followed his father\u2019s footsteps at first, joining Israel\u2019s Special Forces after high school and earning the red beret, but he soon grew to regret his decision. \nHe surrendered his status as soon as he earned it, becoming a medic, and finally, disgusted by the [[1982 Lebanon war|1982 Lebanon invasion]], he buried his service pin in the dirt.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =The General\u2019s Son: Journey of an Israeli in Palestine\n| work =War Resisters League\n| url =https://www.warresisters.org/content/general\u2019s-son-journey-israeli-palestine\n| access-date =4 April 2020\n| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150421205634/http://www.warresisters.org/content/general%E2%80%99s-son-journey-israeli-palestine\n| archive-date =21 April 2015\n| url-status =dead\n}}</ref>\n\nOne evening in 1983, however, he skipped a [[Peace Now]] demonstration in Jerusalem to attend karate class, and on that evening a grenade attack by a right-wing extremist killed one of the demonstrators. \"Peled took this as a sign,\" according to one interview, and consequently \"followed the path of karate \u2013 a practice of non-violence...that teaches one to 'overcome insurmountable obstacles.'\" This path \"that took him to Japan and eventually to San Diego, where he settled with his wife and family\".<ref name=ditmar>{{cite web| last =Ditmars| first =Hidani| title =Following in the footsteps of his father, a Zionist hero, toward a free and democratic Palestine| work =Haaretz| date =8 Apr 2013| url =http://www.haaretz.com/misc/article-print-page/following-in-the-footsteps-of-his-father-a-zionist-hero-toward-a-free-and-democratic-palestine-1.514402?trailingPath=2.169%2C2.216%2C2.221%2C}}</ref> He then distanced himself from activism until 1997, becoming a [[Dan (rank)#Usage in martial arts|sixth-degree]] black belt in karate and moving first to Japan, then to [[San Diego]], [[California]], United States.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\">{{cite web\n| last =Ditmars\n| first =Hadani\n| title =Following in the footsteps of his father, a Zionist hero, toward a free and democratic Palestine\n| work =Haaretz\n| date =Apr 8, 2013\n| url =http://www.haaretz.com/news/features/following-in-the-footsteps-of-his-father-a-zionist-hero-toward-a-free-and-democratic-palestine-1.514402\n}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nIn 1997, Peled\u2019s 13-year-old niece Smadar, daughter of his sister [[Nurit Peled-Elhanan]],  was killed in an anti-Israel suicide attack in Jerusalem.  At her funeral, according to an article summarizing Peled's book, [[Ehud Barak]], who had just been elected to lead the opposition, explained that in order to gain appeal he must disguise his real intentions of becoming a 'peacemaker.\u201d \nIn reply, Peled said, \u201cWhy not tell the truth ... That this and similar tragedies are taking place because we are occupying another nation and that in order to save lives the right thing to do is to end the occupation and negotiate a just peace with our Palestinian partners?\"<ref name=ditmar/>\n\nThe murder of Smadar, and his sister Nurit\u2019s insistence that it was caused by the occupation, \u201cjolted him back into Middle Eastern reality,\u201d an interviewer has written. \u201cThe activist side of me that I\u2019d been suppressing,\u201d Peled has said, \u201csuddenly burst out. It became stronger than anything.\u201d<ref name=ditmar/> He joined a Palestinian/Jewish-American dialogue group in San Diego, where he \u201cfound that the Jewish Americans he met \u2013 with their 'New York humor and deli food' \u2013 were more foreign than the hummus, tabouleh and warm hospitality offered by his new Palestinian friends. He was shocked by random anti-Arab venom spewed casually by Jewish Americans he met who assumed he shared their views, in an atmosphere of growing Islamophobia.\u201d He also befriended Nader Elbanna, \u201ca Palestinian from Nazareth who accompanied him on a dual lecture series at rotary clubs.\u201d<ref name=ditmar/> Thus began a process whereby, in the words of Abulhawa, Peled \u201cdismantled a lifetime of racist assumptions and replaced them with something more human and tender.\u201d<ref name=record/>\n\nReturning to activism, Peled decided that the two-state solution his father had promoted would no longer suffice, and began to support for the creation of a single democratic state with equal rights for Israelis and Palestinians.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/> He claims that Israel is an apartheid state that must go, and that a single-state solution is closer than many people think because of the changing mindsets of many Israelis, American Jews, and Holocaust survivors. The Israeli government, he has written, is \u201ca radical Zionist regime,\u201d and Israel is a country where \u201chalf of the population lives in what it thinks is a Western democracy while keeping the other half imprisoned by a ruthless defense apparatus that is becoming more violent by the day.\u201d<ref name=peled/> He told that \"The State of Israel Will Crumble and We Will See A Free Democratic Palestine from the River to the Sea Sooner than Most People Think\".<ref>[https://ahtribune.com/interview/2487-miko-peled.html Miko Peled: The State of Israel Will Crumble and We Will See A Free Democratic Palestine from the River to the Sea Sooner than Most People Think], September 21, 2018</ref>\n\nPeled has traveled in Palestine, teaching karate to children in refugee camps and engaging in nonviolent activism.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\"/> In his blog, he calls for the removal of Israel\u2019s separation wall, and the institution of equal rights for Israelis and Palestinians. \"As an Israeli that was raised on the Zionist ideal of a Jewish state\", he writes in the blog, \"I know how hard it is for many Jews and Palestinians to let go of the dream of having a state that is exclusively 'our own.' The articles, the stories and the pictures in this blog are meant to make a single point: For the good of both nations, the Separation Wall must come down, the Israeli control over the lives of Palestinians must be defied so that a secular democracy where all Israelis and Palestinian live as equals be established in our shared homeland\".<ref name=peled/> Peled is a regular contributor to online publications like the ''[[Electronic Intifada]]'' and the ''Palestine Chronicle''.\n\nPeled spoke at a fringe gathering at the British [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party conference]] in Brighton in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url= https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/israeli-born-anti-zionist-calls-israel-a-racist-settler-regime-at-labour-conference-1.444944 |title= Israeli-born anti-Zionist calls Israel a 'racist settler regime' at Labour conference|work= [[The Jewish Chronicle]] |date= 25 September 2017 |accessdate= 26 September 2017}}</ref> At the event, Peled is reported to have said: \"This is about free speech, the freedom to criticise and to discuss every issue, whether it\u2019s the Holocaust: yes or no, Palestine, the liberation, the whole spectrum. There should be no limits on the discussion\". He further went on to compare [[Zionists]] to Nazis and \"apartheid South Africa racists\".<ref name=\"Weaver\">{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Matthew|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/26/new-antisemitism-row-for-labour-over-fringe-speakers-holocaust-remarks-miko-peled|title=Labour fringe speaker's Holocaust remarks spark new antisemitism row|work=The Guardian|date=26 September 2017|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> Deputy Labour leader [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] said the conference organising committee would investigate how Peled was given a platform at the event.<ref name=\"Weaver\"/>\n\nAt a meeting at [[University College London]] the following November, Peled complained about the \"witch-hunt against antisemites and Holocaust deniers\" over the past two years and complimented the \"clear leadership\" of Labour's [[Jeremy Corbyn]] commenting that Corbyn had \"put away this nonsense about Holocaust denial and this nonsense about antisemitism. You focus on what\u2019s important\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Alastair|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/miko-peled-zionists-do-not-deserve-a-platform-1.447859|title=Miko Peled: Zionists do not deserve a platform|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=12 November 2017|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\u201cIsrael has been on a mission to destroy the Palestinian people for over six decades,\u201d Peled has said. \u201cWhy would anyone not give solidarity to the Palestinian people?\u201d<ref name=mclr>{{cite web| last =Mcllroy| first =Jim| title =Generals son condemns Israeli oppression, supports BDS| work =Green Left| date =Oct 7, 2011| url =http://www.greenleft.org.au/node/48978#sthash.fawyWrv3.dpuf}}</ref> He believes that Israel's actions in the Six-Day War of 1967 were not a response to a real threat but acts of bald aggression.<ref name=silver>{{cite web| last =Silver| first =Charlotte| title =Palestine freedom battle will be won: interview with author Miko Peled| work =Electronic Intifada| date =Oct 3, 2012| url =http://electronicintifada.net/content/palestine-freedom-battle-will-be-won-interview-author-miko-peled/11725}}</ref>  And he has said that \u201cevery single Israeli city is a settlement\u201d and that \u201cexpressing solidarity with Palestinians is the most important thing people can do.\u201d<ref name=silver/>\n\nOn his Twitter feed, Peled has written that \u201cIDF lusts for blood,\u201d has called the peace process \u201ca process of apartheid & colonization,\u201d and has accused Israeli officials of \u201cethnic cleansing.\u201d<ref>{{cite web| title =Miko Peled| work =Twitter| url =https://twitter.com/mikopeled}}</ref> In his blog posts, he repeatedly refers to the IDF as an \u201cIsraeli terrorist organization\u201d that is part of a \u201cwell-oiled ethnic cleansing machine.\u201d He has also written that Israel's educational system is designed to turn Israeli children into racists who view Palestinians \u201cas culturally inferior, violent and bent on the annihilation of the Jews, and...void of a true national identity,\u201d and \u201cas a problem that must be solved and as a threat that must be eliminated.\u201d He has decried \u201cabsurd comparisons like that of Yasser Arafat to Hitler, the Palestinians to Nazis, and the Palestinian resistance to Al Qaeda.\u201d<ref>{{cite web| last =Peled| first =Miko| title =Ethnic Cleansing of Invented People| work =mikopeled.com| date =Dec 20, 2011| url =http://mikopeled.com/2011/12/20/ethnic-cleansing-of-invented-people-by-miko-peled/}}</ref>\n\nPeled supports [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|the movement for boycotts, divestment, and sanctions (BDS) against Israel]]. Giving a talk in [[Queensland, Australia]], he supported a BDS campaign against the Israeli-owned [[Max Brenner]] chain of chocolate shops, part of the Strauss group of companies, which, he said, \u201csupports a terrorist organisation, the Golani Brigade.\u201d  BDS, he argued, was a \u201ctotally legitimate\u201d means of \u201ctrying to stop this Israeli armed juggernaut.\u201d<ref name=mclr/>\n\nPeled wrote in a June 2012 op-ed for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' that,\n{{quote|\u201cIsrael is faced with two options: Continue to exist as a Jewish state while controlling the Palestinians through military force and racist laws, or undertake a deep transformation into a real democracy where Israelis and Palestinians live as equals in a shared state, their shared homeland. For Israelis and Palestinians alike, the latter path promises a bright future.<ref>{{cite web| last =Peled| first =Miko| title =Six Days in Israel, 45 Years Ago| work =Los Angeles Times| date =Jun 6, 2012| url =http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/06/opinion/la-oe-peled-israel-palestine--six-day-war-201206}}</ref>}}\n\n==Books==\nPeled has described his book, ''The General\u2019s Son: Journey of an Israeli in Palestine'' (2012),<ref name=\"justworldbooks.com\"/> as an account of how he, \"the son of an Israeli General and a staunch Zionist, came to realize that \"the story upon which I was raised ... was a lie.\"<ref name=peled/>  The book, he has said, is based largely on long conversations with his mother, on a thorough reading of \"everything my dad had ever written,\" and on material about his father's career in the Israeli army archives.<ref name=silver/>\n\nThe book, which has been characterized as \"part confessional, part cinematic epic and part emotional appeal for 'different answers' to the Israeli-Palestinian conundrum,\"<ref name=ditmar/> contains a foreword by [[Alice Walker]], author of ''[[The Color Purple]]''.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = archives\n |work        = The Madison Times\n |url         = http://www.themadisontimes.com/news_details.php?news_id=2369\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20121210211850/http://www.themadisontimes.com/news_details.php?news_id=2369\n |archivedate = 10 December 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn Peled's book, ''Injustice: The Story of the Holy Land Foundation Five'' (2018), he catalogs the trial of the criminalization and dismantling of the [[Holy Land Foundation for Relief and Development]], leading to the arrest and jailing of Foundation President Shukri Abu Baker, Chairman [[Ghassan Elashi]], Mohammad el-Mezain, [[Mufid Abdulqader]] and Abdulraham Odeh.\n\n==Elbanna-Peled Foundation==\nPeled is, with Nader Elbanna, co-founder of the Elbanna-Peled Foundation. Established in 2010 and based in Coronado, California, it describes itself as being \"committed to peace, justice and equality by operating exclusively for charitable and educational purposes, including, but not limited to the following:\n#Humanitarian aid to civilians who were injured as a result of Israeli Palestinian conflict.\n#Support existing educational efforts that promote Israeli Palestinian reconciliation.\n#Support local grassroots organizations that work together (Israelis and Palestinians) toward a non-violent resolution of the conflict.\"<ref>{{cite web| title =About| work =Elbanna Peled Foundation| url =http://www.elbannapeledfoundation.org/?page_id=2| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20131224110801/http://www.elbannapeledfoundation.org/?page_id=2| archivedate =24 December 2013| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation describes itself as working closely with Rotary International. According to its website, \"Peled and Elbanna sent 1000 wheelchairs for Palestinians and Israeli children, and have been part of numerous project to help the people of their shared homeland.\"\n\nThe foundation, however, was established under the National Taxonomy of Exempt Entities (NTEE) categories \"Foreign Affairs\" and \"National Security.\"Its exempt status, moreover, was automatically revoked by the IRS because it failed to file a Form 990 (\"Return of Organization Exempt from Income \nTax\") for three consecutive years.<ref>{{cite web| title =ELBANNA-PELED FOUNDATION| work =Guidestar| url =http://www.guidestar.org/organizations/80-0192335/elbanna-peled-foundation.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Martial Arts America==\nSince 28 May 1989, Peled, a sixth-degree black belt, owned, operated, and taught at Martial Arts America, a school in [[Coronado, California]], which \"is dedicated to teaching leadership skills and non-violent conflict resolution through martial arts.\" In October 2012, he sold the business to his top student of over twenty years, David Michael Adams, in order to focus on promoting his book ''The General's Son''.<ref>{{cite web| title =Welcome to our website| work =Coronado Karate| url =http://coronadokarate.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mikopeled.com/ Miko Peled's blog]\n* [http://thegeneralsson.com/ ''The General's Son'' website]\n* [http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=767&Itemid=74&jumival=16303 Video] of Peled interview with [[Chris Hedges]], 10 May 2016; and a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VTepqDOMdZw video] of Peled's second interview with Hedges, 24 September 2016\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TOaxAckFCuQ&feature=player_embedded Video] of Peled's talk in Seattle, USA, 9 October 2012\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4ZfnpN4Dfc/ Interview] with Miko Peled by Alternate Focus; and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rI9-dEs9HIM/ Second interview] with Miko Peled by Alternate Focus\n* [https://therealnews.com/bios/miko-peled interviews] with [[Paul Jay]] of ''[[The Real News]]''\n* https://ahtribune.com/interview/2487-miko-peled.html\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peled, Miko}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Israeli anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Motza Illit]]\n", "name_user": "Gromte", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eActivism:changed \"thinks that singstate soln is getting more popular)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miko_Peled"}
{"title_page": "Milad Ebadipour", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball player\n| name           = Milad Ebadipour\n| image          = Milad Ebadipour.jpg\n| imagesize      = \n| fullname       = Milad Ebadipour Gharahassanlou\n| nationality    = {{flagicon|IRN}} [[Iran|Iranian]]\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1993|10|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Urmia]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    =  \n| height         = 1.96 m\n| weight         = 78 kg\n| spike          = 358 cm\n| block          = \n| position       = Outside hitter\n| currentclub    = {{flagicon|POL}} [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]]\n| currentnumber  = 11\n| years          = 2012\u20132014<br>2014\u20132016<br>2016\u20132017<br>2017<br>2017\u2013\n| clubs          = {{flagicon|IRI}} [[Kalleh Mazandaran VC|Kalleh Mazandaran]]<br>{{flagicon|IRI}} [[Shahrdari Urmia VC|Shahrdari Urmia]]<br>{{flagicon|IRI}} [[Sarmayeh Bank Tehran VC|Sarmayeh Bank Tehran]]<br>{{flagicon|QAT}} [[Al Rayan SC Volleyball Team|Al Rayyan]]<br>{{flagicon|POL}} [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]]\n| nationalyears  = 2011\u20132012<br />2014\u2013\n| nationalteam   = {{flagicon|IRN}} [[Iran men's national under-21 volleyball team|Iran U21]]<br> {{flagicon|IRN}} [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[volleyball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{IRI}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Champions Cup|World Grand Champions Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2017 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Grand Champions Cup|2017 Japan]]|Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Asian Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|2019 Tehran]]|Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Volleyball at the Asian Games|Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 Asian Games|2014 Incheon]]|[[Volleyball at the 2014 Asian Games \u2013 Men|Team]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Asian Games|2018 Jakarta-Palembang]]|[[Volleyball at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Milad Ebadipour Gharahassanlou''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0639\u0628\u0627\u062f\u06cc \u067e\u0648\u0631}}, born 17 October 1993) is an Iranian [[volleyball player]], a member of [[Iran men's national volleyball team]] and Polish club [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]], Polish Champion ([[2017\u201318 PlusLiga|2018]]).\n\n==Career==\nHe was invited to the [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Men's National Team]] for the [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 FIVB World League]] for the first time, following consistent and strong performance in the Iranian Super League, and made his first appearance in the match against Italy. He competed at the [[Volleyball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Rio 2016 Summer Olympics]].\nEbadipour was for the first time in the Iranian Super League with a three year contract played in [[Kalleh Mazandaran]] club. After the [[2017 FIVB Volleyball World League|2017 FIVB World League]] he joined the Polish club [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]] in August 2017.<ref>[https://sportowefakty.wp.pl/siatkowka/703943/oficjalnie-milad-ebadipour-w-pge-skrze-belchatow ''Oficjalnie: Milad Ebadipour w PGE Skrze Be\u0142chat\u00f3w''] \u2013 onet.pl \u2013 10-08-2017</ref> Milad achieved bronze medal of the [[2017 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Grand Champions Cup|2017 World Grand Champions Cup]] and he received individual award for the Best Outside Spiker of the tournament.<ref>[https://www.fivb.org/viewPressRelease.asp?No=72981&Language=en#.WcfV_Vu0PIU ''World Grand Champions Cup: Iran take bronze with 3-2 win over France''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 17-09-2017</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n* '''[[AVC Club Volleyball Championship|AVC Asian Club Championship]]'''\n** [[File:Gold medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2013 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship|Iran 2013]] \u2013 with [[Kalleh Mazandaran VC|Kalleh Mazandaran]]\n** [[File:Gold medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2016 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship|Myanmar 2016]] \u2013 with [[Sarmayeh Bank Tehran VC|Sarmayeh Bank Tehran]]\n** [[File:Gold medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2017 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship|Vietnam 2017]] \u2013 with [[Sarmayeh Bank Tehran VC|Sarmayeh Bank Tehran]]\n\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2012/2013''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012-13 Iranian Volleyball Super League|Iranian Championship]], with [[Kalleh Mazandaran VC|Kalleh Mazandaran]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2013-14 Iranian Volleyball Super League|Iranian Championship]], with [[Kalleh Mazandaran VC|Kalleh Mazandaran]]\n** '''2014/2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014-15 Iranian Volleyball Super League|Iranian Championship]], with [[Shahrdari Urmia VC|Shahrdari Urmia]]\n** '''2015/2016''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015-16 Iranian Volleyball Super League|Iranian Championship]], with [[Shahrdari Urmia VC|Shahrdari Urmia]]\n** '''2016/2017''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016-17 Iranian Volleyball Super League|Iranian Championship]], with [[Sarmayeh Bank Tehran VC|Sarmayeh Bank Tehran]]\n** '''2016/2017''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[Emir of Qatar Cup (volleyball)|Emir Cup]], with [[Al Rayyan SC Volleyball Team|Al Rayyan]]\n** '''2017/2018''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[Polish Men's Volleyball SuperCup#Winners|Polish SuperCup]], with [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]]\n** '''2017/2018''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2017\u201318 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]]\n** '''2018/2019''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[Polish Men's Volleyball SuperCup#Winners|Polish SuperCup]], with [[PGE Skra Be\u0142chat\u00f3w]]\n\n* '''National team'''\n** '''2012''' [[File:Bronze medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2012 Asian Junior Men's Volleyball Championship|AVC U21 Asian Championship]]\n** '''2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball a